<FIRST>u a AM-Bush-Baseball 2ndLd-Writethru a0780 08-04 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Baseball, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0780,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0401 to correct writethru designation</HEAD>
<HEAD>President Goes to See Orioles-Rangers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs, The president, with final score; SUBS penultimate
graf with further color</HEAD>
<BYLINE>LaserPhoto BAB1 ^By MICHAEL SNIFFEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush took his wife Barbara to
Memorial Stadium Friday night to watch their eldest son's American
League baseball team, the Texas Rangers, play the Baltimore Orioles.
   George W. Bush, the 43 year-old Texas oilman who heads the
partnership that purchased the Rangers earlier this year, and his
wife Laura joined his parents behind home plate in the skybox of
Orioles' owner Eli Jacobs.
   Before the game, the president, baseball Commissioner A.
Bartlett Giamatti and American League President Bobby Brown visited
the Rangers' and then the Orioles' locker rooms.
   The president and first lady left with the Orioles batting in
the bottom of the sixth inning and the Rangers ahead 6-2. The
Orioles ended up 6-4 losers.
   Spokesman Marlin Fitzwater had said earlier it would be hard for
the president to decide for whom to root.
   The Orioles, leading the American League East, have won during
previous presidential visits this year. The president is a keen
baseball fan who captained the 1948 Yale team and keeps his old
first baseman's mitt in his desk.
   He came on opening day with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and
again on June 28 when he brought his 13-year-old grandson, George
P. Bush.
   His son's Rangers began the evening in fourth place in the
American League West with a record of 57-49, two more victories
than the Orioles have in their weaker division.
   On a humid 91-degree night, Bush shed his jacket and tie to
watch the game in a white short-sleeved shirt.
   Barbara Bush, who arrived earlier in the day from the family's
vacation home at Kennebunkport, Maine, wore a belted red tunic over
a black skirt. Their son, also in shirt sleeves, wore a blue
Rangers cap.
   All three waved to the crowd before the game. The president and
his wife drew cheers, but his son was hooted when he waved the
Rangers cap.
   All drank large sodas; the president had peanuts and he and his
wife also had corn on the cob. The president took time out to
autograph some baseballs and occasionally they used binoculars to
follow the action.
   The Bushes also were accompanied by Woody Willoughby, an usher
in the White House residence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
