<FIRST>u a AM-PlaneEmergency 3rdLd-Writethru a0402 08-04 0772</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plane Emergency, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0402,0794</SECOND>
<HEAD>Piedmont Pilot Says Not a Hero For Landing Crippled Plane</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS two grafs with report right landing gear might have been
obstructed also.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot who brought a crippled
Piedmont Airlines jet to a safe landing with one engine cowl
scraping the ground said Thursday he's tried since to think of a
better way of bringing in the plane.
   ``I landed that aircraft probably a thousand times last night to
see if I could have done any better _ and I couldn't,'' pilot Larry
Fuda said during a news conference Thursday at Piedmont Triad
International Airport.
   Flight 1489 originated at Washington National Airport and was
bound for Columbia, S.C., with a stop in Charlotte. It was diverted
to Greensboro when the crew couldn't get the left landing gear down.
   Fuda said he decided to go to Greensboro to avoid the more
congested Charlotte-Douglas International Airport. Fuda said he
liked the emergency equipment at Greensboro and knew Greensboro's
runway was as long as Charlotte's. He also knew a large contingent
of Piedmont people were close by.
   Fuda set the Boeing 737-400 down on its right and nose landing
gear, then settled the plane onto its left engine and skidded to a
halt on the 10,000-foot runway, a shower of sparks coming from the
dragging metal.
   ``I hardly knew that the wheel wasn't there when we touched
down,'' Fuda said.
   Fuda said he had no previous experience like Wednesday's in his
21 years of flying for Piedmont. ``I always wondered what I would
do if it did happen,'' he said.
   Passengers aboard Piedmont Flight 1489, which made the landing
at Piedmont Triad International Airport, said later they thought
Fuda was a hero.
   ``There was no hysteria,'' said Richard Kochan of Washington, a
lobbyist who says he flies a lot. ``But there were a lot of trips
to the bathroom.''
   Fuda's wife, Margaret, said her husband doesn't think of himself
as a hero.
   ``He's just glad it worked out,'' she said. ``The whole crew did
just what they were supposed to do. He says he doesn't consider
himself a hero.''
   ``This time it worked out the way it was supposed to work.
Sometimes the crew does the right things and things don't work out
as well,'' she said. ``He's pooped. I've been giving him kisses and
hugs since he got home.''
   Fuda was not originally scheduled to pilot Flight 1489, said his
neighbor Donnie Campbell, a retired Piedmont pilot.
   ``He was supposed to work Friday night, but they're having a
`Farewell to Piedmont' party in Roanoke (Va.) Friday night, and he
wanted to go to that. So he just picked up a flight that somebody
dropped.''
   ``I'm waiting to see the pilot I picked it up from,'' Fuda said.
   The party is to celebrate Piedmon't final flight on Saturday
before its merger with USAir is completed _ to which Fuda made
jocular reference:
   ``I have made my last and best landing for Piedmont,'' he said.
   The 94 passengers and six crew members safely jumped down
emergency chutes.
   A rubber wheel chock found wedged in the wheel well had
prevented the left main landing gear from deploying, said the
National Transportation Safety Board.
   Piedmont spokesman David Shipley said Thursday it would be mere
speculation to suggest that the chock, a triangular rubber block 30
inches long and 6 inches high used to keep planes from rolling when
they're parked, was left in the wheel well at Washington National.
   ``There's really nothing else to say,'' Shipley added. ``The
airplane's in the hangar, and we estimate it to be in service
Saturday.''
   Only the left engine housing was damaged during the landing,
Shipley said. The 11-month-old plane's left wing and skin were
unharmed. The plane's engine housing is designed to hold up during
that type of emergency landing, he said.
   ``Apparently, (the wing) never touched the ground,'' he said.
``The engine itself is apparently undamaged, but we will remove it
and replace it and run it through a complete structural check as
well.''
   Phillip Powell, an NTSB air safety investigator, said
investigators found the chock wedged between two wheels on the left
landing gear.
   While airline officials doubt the chock was deliberately placed,
they declined to rule out any possibility pending further
investigation, Shipley said.
   The Washington Post in Friday editions quoted Powell as saying
the right landing gear might also have been obstructed.
   Two bent hydraulic lines were found in the right wheel well,
raising the possiblity that a chock might also have been stuck in
the right landing gear and fallen out, Powell said.
</TEXT>
