<FIRST>r a PM-Hostages-Beckwith     08-04 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hostages-Beckwith,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leader in Failed Iran Hostage Rescue Attempt Urges Action</HEAD>
<HEAD>With US-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEGGY FIKAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States should warn Iran that
support of terrorism in Lebanon will result in a military strike,
said the ground force commander in the ill-fated 1980 Iran hostage
rescue attempt.
   President Bush also should pressure the Central Intelligence
Agency to get information he has indicated the United States needs
to rescue American hostages, to take a strong stand against
terrorism, retired Army Col. Charlie Beckwith said Thursday.
   ``If we don't do this, it's going to keep on getting worse and
worse,'' Beckwith said.
   Terrorists claimed they killed one American hostage, Marine Lt.
Col. William Higgins, on Monday, and have threatened to kill
another, Joseph Cicippio, after Israel captured a Shiite Moslem
religious leader accused of promoting terrorism.
   ``I'd like to see the United States be able to go in there and
eliminate all of those terrorists and bring those beautiful
hostages home,'' Beckwith said. ``I'd like to see us do it in such
a vigorous way that we tell the rest of the world, `Never fool with
the United States again.'''
   Beckwith, a security consultant, led troops in the aborted 1980
attempt to rescue American hostages being held by Iran. Eight
Americans died in that mission.
   Beckwith criticized the CIA as not being active enough since
director William Casey died in 1987.
   The CIA relies too heavily on electronic wizardry and has
forgotten about the need for ``a pair of good solid eyeballs, and a
good human being on the ground,'' he said.
</TEXT>
