<FIRST>r a PM-Fires-Glance     08-04 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fires-Glance,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Western Wildfires at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Fires Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a state-by-state look at wildfires burning in the West:
   IDAHO: Hundreds of lightning-caused fires have joined to form
huge blazes in forests in the western and central part of the
state, burning 98,000 acres by Thursday. Cool, moist weather
overnight helped firefighting efforts. Although warmer weather is
predicted for the weekend, fire bosses say there is little chance
of the lightning that sparked many of the fires 12 days earlier.
   OREGON: Fires east of the Cascades have burned more than 93,000
acres. About 650 soldiers from Fort Lewis, Wash., were brought in
to help fight a 13,300-acre blaze in the Monument Rock Wilderness,
70 miles southwest of Baker. A 23,300-acre fire burned on the
boundary of the Eagle Cap Wildneress area northwest of Baker.
   CALIFORNIA: More than 35,000 acres have burned, and the biggest
active blaze was a brushfire in the Cleveland National Forest
southeast of Los Angeles. The 10,800-acre blaze was 60 percent
contained, but was burning toward rough terrain three miles from
the Palomar Observatory, which houses the nation's largest optical
telescope. Scientists were forced to shut down the observatory
Thursday for fear that ash would damage the instrument.
   MONTANA: An 800-acre blaze in the Custer National Forest was
contained, but a fire on the Crow Indian Reservation southeast of
Billings quickly spread to 500 acres and threatened two mountain
cabins.
   WASHINGTON: Crews were mopped up an 850-acre forest fire in the
Pasayten Wilderness near the Canadian border.
</TEXT>
