<FIRST>r w PM-Alexander-Gingrich 1stLd-Writethru a0469 08-04 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Alexander-Gingrich, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0469,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alexander Says He'll Expand Gingrich Allegations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 9 grafs new with Gingrich quotes today; picks up 9th graf
pvs, The ethics panel.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Republican Whip Newt Gingrich said today
the Democratic congressman threatening to expand allegations of
possible misconduct against him is ``almost irrational.''
   Rep. Bill Alexander of Arkansas on Thursday made public a letter
to the House ethics committee in which he predicted his original
complaint ``may have only scratched the surface.''
   ``There could well be over 200 additional instances of
potentially unethical, illegal or criminal conduct by Mr.
Gingrich,'' Alexander said, declining to give reporters specific
information on the allegations.
   ``I think in terms of the substance of the charges you have an
almost irrational Democrat in Bill Alexander, who is wandering
around wildly saying things and I am comfortable after the ethics
committee investigates it that they are going to say there is
nothing to the charges,'' Gingrich, R-Ga., said on ABC-TV's ``Good
Morning America'' program.
   Gingrich, who filed charges that led to the resignation of Jim
Wright, D-Texas, as House speaker, said ``a number of very powerful
Democrats said they were going to destroy me, that they would get
even and, in that sense, of course I'm battling for my (political)
life.''
   In an interview Thursday with WAGA-TV in Atlanta, the Georgia
lawmaker said: ``When you hear a politician say he has 200 hidden
charges he may eventually file, you know he has a lot of baloney.''
   Alexander said he wouldn't file an expanded complaint against
Gingrich until at least September.
   His April complaint to the ethics committee focused on an
investment partnership formed by Gingrich to promote a book he
wrote with his wife and another person.
   Alexander accused Gingrich of possibly violating campaign
finance law, House limitations on outside income and a rule
prohibiting receipt of gifts from people with a direct interest in
legislation.
   The ethics panel has hired a Chicago law firm to recommend
whether it should begin a formal investigation.
   Alexander said other allegations could involve:
   _The possible failure of Gingrich to disclose substantial, and
potentially illegal, campaign contributions he made through his
campaign committee during 1986.
   _Information that contributors to the book promotion partnership
were ``recipients of substantial federal grants and loan
guarantees, including at least one major award under the
politically controlled housing programs mal-administered by the
Department of Housing and Urban Development.''
   _The propriety of Gingrich's management of a former political
action committee that may have raised hundreds of thousands of
dollars for candidates, but only donated a miniscule portion of the
money to those running for office.
   _Use of official stationery and congressional free mailing to
promote the personal business endeavors of friends.
   _Improper settlement of personal and corporate debts incurred by
Gingrich's campaign committee and the possibility that Gingrich
improperly enriched himself in a questionable real estate
transaction.
</TEXT>
