<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 0948EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Adams-Tankers     08-04 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Adams-Tankers,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Adams Says He Will Press Ahead With Adams Amendment on Double Hulls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Brock Adams says he will press on with
his proposal to require new oil tankers to be built with double
hulls despite its narrow rejection by the Senate.
   ``We were close and there is no stopping me now,'' Adams,
D-Wash., said Thursday following the 51-49 vote to table, and thus
reject, his amendment to a pending bill tightening oil tanker
safety regulations and creating a special fund to clean up oil
spills.
   Adams' amendment would have required double hulls and double
sides on all new tankers over 20,000 deadweight tons that operate
in U.S. waters.
   It was prompted by the Exxon Valdez oil spill in Alaska's Prince
William Sound earlier this year, which Adams said might not have
grown into the nation's largest oil spill ever if the vessel had
been equipped with a double hull.
   The pending bill would require that the secretary of
transportation study for one year the use of double hulls and
require them in new tankers unless it is found they won't enhance
tanker safety, or other structural requirements were found to be
better.
   ``None of us are naval architects,'' said Sen. John Breaux,
D-La., who moved to table Adams' amendment. ``I don't think we are
absolutely competent to make a final decision.''
</TEXT>
