<SECOND>PM-Hostages-Iran, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0521,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Rafsanjani Says He'll Help Solve Lebanon Problem</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to ADD quotes from Rafsanjani offering to help in
hostage situation. No pickup. ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's president, Hashemi Rafsanjani,
today said he would help find a solution to the hostage situation
in Lebanon and urged the White House to approach the problem in a
reasonable manner, Tehran radio said.
   ``These bullyings, arrogant approaches and tyranny will not
solve the problems,'' the president said during his weekly prayer
sermon at Tehran University. ``Come let us approach the problem
reasonably. We too will help solve the problems there, so the
people of the region can live in peace and harmony,'' he said in
the broadcast, monitored in Nicosia, Cyprus.
   ``I tell the White House, the problem of Lebanon has solutions,
the freeing of the hostages has solutions, reasonable, prudent
solutions,'' Rafsanjani said.
   However, Rafsanjani also said the United States must take the
initiative by pressuring Israel to free Sheik Abdul Karim Obeid, a
Shiite Moslem cleric it kidnapped from south Lebanon a week ago.
   If the U.S. responds by saying it cannot do so, ``this isn't
acceptable to us,'' he said.
   Israel has offered to swap Obeid for the 16 foreign hostages in
Iran and three Israeli soldiers held there.
   The pro-Iranian group Hezbollah, of which Obeid is reputed to be
a member, rejected such a swap. Hezbollah is believed to be the
umbrella for factions holding most of the foreign hostages.
   On Thursday, one of those factions, the Revolutionary Justice
Organization, suspended a threat to kill American hostage Joseph
Cicippio but demanded that Israel free Obeid and Palestinian and
Lebanese prisoners it holds. It did not say what would happen if
Israel refused.
   On Monday, another faction, the Organization of the Oppressed on
Earth, claimed it killed American hostage William Higgins, a Marine
lieutenant colonel, in retaliation for Israel's refusal to free
Obeid.
   ``We do not make any judgment about the group which executed the
American colonel,'' Rafsanjani said.
   ``You cannot condemn the innocent people of Lebanon ... on the
vague basis that some group has possibly killed someone (Higgins)
for a crime,'' he added.
   Higgins' captors accused him of being a spy.
   Rafsanjani, known as a pragmatist who wants to improve Iran's
ties with the West, has not said whether Iran played a role in the
reprieve granted Cicippio. A knowledgeable Shiite Moslem source in
Beirut, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the final word on
Cicippio's reprieve came from him.
   The 54-year-old Rafsanjani is believed to want to end the
international terrorist image Iran developed under the leadership
of the late Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   After Khomeini's death June 3, Rafsanjani moved quickly to gain
the upper hand against a radical faction headed by Interior
Minister Ali Akbar Mohtashemi. The radicals favor Khomeini's
anti-Western views and backing of terrorist groups abroad.
</TEXT>
