<FIRST>r i PM-Greece-Crash 1stLd-Writethru a0494 08-04 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Greece-Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0494,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede ATHENS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Rescuers Crawl to Crash Site; No Survivors</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 13 grafs to UPDATE with detail from crash site. Pickup
9th pvs, ``Gelastathis told...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NIKOS KONSTANDARAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAMOS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers crawled on their hands and knees
today to reach the site of an Olympic Airways crash, but they found
no survivors from the aircraft that slammed into a mountain with 34
people aboard.
   The British-built Short plane crashed Thursday into 4,800-foot
Mount Kerkis on Samos island. Airline officials blamed the accident
on heavy fog that covered the mountain, the highest in the Aegean
Sea.
   Rescuers searched for the flight recorders, which should contain
information on the plane's equipment and any conversations
involving the pilot.
   Transport and Communications Minister Nikos Gelestathis said the
plane, which was flying to the island from Salonica in northern
Greece, carried 31 passengers, including an infant, and three crew
members. All were Greek.
   Rescuers said they apparently were killed instantly when the
aircraft hit the mountain.
   ``Unfortunately, we could do nothing, I checked every body I
could find,'' said Emmanuel Karlas, a doctor from a village on this
eastern Aegean island within sight of Turkey's southwestern coast.
   The propeller-driven plane gave no sign of trouble before it
disappeared from radar screens, officials said.
   Only a wing and twin-tail section of the aircraft was
recognizable. The front disintegrated on impact and was just a
black scar on the mountainside.
   Police could identify only four of the charred bodies. Olympic,
Greece's national carrier, was flying in relatives to help identify
victims.
   Helicopters could not land close to the crash site and rescuers
crawled up the mountainside on hands and knees for 90 minutes in
the dark.
   The steep terrain prevented them from carrying down the dead.
   ``We'll have the helicopters hoist out the human remains, ''
said police officer Panayiotis Kourdonouris.
   Officials ruled out foul play as the cause of the crash.
   An Olympic official who spoke on condition of anonymity said:
``It appears that thick fog in the area at the time played the
villain's role as the pilot flew blindly into the mountain.''
   Gelestathis told lawmakers in Parliament today that a terrorist
act was out of the question.
   Military teams were dispatched to the crash site after a
shepherd reported seeing an explosion on the mountain.
   The Athens airport duty officer, Emmanuel Fragiadakis, said the
control tower lost contact with the plane at about 4:55 p.m., an
hour after it left Salonika. It was scheduled to land on Samos at
5:30 p.m. The plane disappeared from radar screens when it was 25
miles northwest of Samos.
   Olympic officials said the pilot, Petros Moutzoureas, was a
veteran with an excellent flight record. They said the aircraft was
bought in 1981 and was used for inter-island flights.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
