<DOCNO> AP890804-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 1131EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     08-04 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrian-Christian Clashes in Beirut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian and Christian forces battled with
howitzers, mortars and tank cannons across Beirut's dividing Green
Line today. Police said two people were killed and seven wounded.
   The shelling kept many Moslems from attending their weekly
Friday prayers.
   The latest casualties raised the overall toll to 516 killed and
2,183 wounded in the 20-week-old confrontation between Gen. Michel
Aoun's predominantly Christian troops and Syrian soldiers in
Lebanon.
   ``They've started early today,'' grocer Najib Masoud said as he
closed his store in west Beirut and headed for a bomb shelter.
``What a life! We are living under the ground like the dead. We
might as well die.''
   A police spokesman, who cannot be named in line with
regulations, said the clash involved the Christian district of Ein
Rummaneh and the adjacent Syrian-controlled Moslem neighborhood of
Chiyah.
   He said the clash started with an exchange of sniper fire then
developed into an artillery duel. It was not immediately clear who
started the clash.
   Shells crashed into apartment buildings on both sides of the
Green Line, which has divided Beirut into Moslem and Christian
sectors since the civil war broke out in April 1975.
   The two fatalities occurred in the densely populated slum of
Chiyah, a stronghold for the Syrian-backed Shiite Moslem Amal
militia.
   Amal did not take part in the confrontation, the spokesman said.
   Shell explosions echoed across Chiyah and residents rushed to
underground bomb shelters as calls were blared from mosque minarets
for noon prayers.
   The police spokesman said the shelling of Chiyah did not reach
the nearby slum of Bir el-Abed, where followers of the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, attended prayers at the
main mosque. Friday is the Moslem holy day.
   Syrian gunners deployed in Chiyah fired their 130mm
Soviet-designed howitzers at the Christian suburb of Kfarshima,
southeast of Beirut, where Aoun's forces maintain some artillery
batteries.
   Aoun's gunners, the spokesman said, responed by shelling Chiyah
and the Druse suburb of Choueifat with 155mm U.S.-designed
howitzers deployed northeast of the capital.
   The thuds of shell blasts resounded across the bomb-ravaged
Lebanese capital, forcing the few businesses that opened early in
the morning to close.
   Only 200,000 people of Beirut's original 1.5 million population
still live in the city, which has been the site of ferocious
shelling duels since the confrontation broke out March 8. Most of
the evacuees have settled in safer areas in south Lebanon, the
eastern Bekaa Valley and the Christian-controlled mountain resorts
northeast of Beirut.
   The confrontation broke out over a blockade imposed by Aoun on
illegal ports run by Syrian-backed militias south of Beirut for
denying the ailing state treasury about $100 million in lost
customs dues annually.
   The Syrians and allied Moslem and leftist forces retaliated by
shelling and besieging the 310-square-mile Christian enclave, home
to about one million people northeast of the capital.
   Aoun, 54, a Maronite Catholic, escalated the confrontation with
the Syrians by declaring a ``war of liberation'' against their
40,000 troops, deployed in predominantly Moslem sections of the
nation.
   An Arab mediation committee has failed to solve Lebanon's
crisis, rooted in an effort by the Moslem majority to wrest more
power from Christians, who traditionally have dominated Lebanon.
The panel blamed Syria for blocking a settlement.
</TEXT>
