<FIRST>r i PM-Austria-Bloch     08-04 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Austria-Bloch,0374</SECOND>
<HEAD>Austria Closes Its Investigation of Bloch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said today it is closing
its investigation of Felix S. Bloch, the U.S. diplomat suspected of
spying for Moscow, after determining that ``Austria's interests
were not affected.''
   However, Interior Minister Franz Loeschnak also told Austrian
radio that 10 politicians have been asked about their relationship
with Bloch and that their answers will be forwarded to Washington
for its investigation.
   The Austrian-born Bloch served at the U.S. Embassy in Vienna in
1980-87 and was friends with many politicians, including Foreign
Minister Alois Mock.
   In the radio interview, Loeschnak refused to identify the
Austrian politicians asked to fill out questionnaires about their
dealings with Bloch.
   He also said that Austria is leaving it up to the politicians to
respond at their own discretion.
   Some of the 10 have promised to comply, he said without
identifying them.
   Loeschnak said police interviewed an Austrian woman with whom
Bloch had an extended friendship. But their questioning yielded no
evidence that the woman suspected anything about Bloch's alleged
spying activities, he said.
   No charges have been brought against Bloch, who has been
stripped of his diplomatic passport and placed on administrative
leave. He is under constant surveillance in Washington by the FBI.
   Bloch, 54, reportedly had broad contacts with Austrian
politicians and officials, and he regularly attended all kinds of
diplomatic and other parties while he was economics chief at the
embassy in 1980-83 and then the No. 2 until his return to
Washington in July 1987.
   Loeschnak noted the American's contacts with the Austrian
politicians ``have no (relevance) for Austria's security
interests.''
   At a news conference July 28, Loeschnak said the suspicions
against Bloch are ``the affair of the United States.''
   Bloch is the highest-ranking U.S. diplomat to be investigated
under suspicion of collaborating with the Soviets. U.S. officials
were alerted to Bloch's possible links with the KGB when they
intercepted an international telephone call arranging a meeting in
Paris in May.
   There, Bloch was filmed exchanging briefcases with a man known
as Pierre, whom the FBI considers a Soviet spy. Bloch says he knows
Pierre as a stamp collector.
</TEXT>
