<FIRST>u a PM-Women'sCaucus 1stLd-Writethru a0482 08-04 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Women's Caucus, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0482,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion if Vietnam of '80s, Abzug Tells Women Activists</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Abzug remarks; picks up 4th
graf pvs: `Brown said ...; SUBS grafs 9-10 pvs, `No action' with 2 grafs
and DELETES penultimate graf to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY R. SANDOK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The battle over abortion will involve
young people today as the Vietnam War did in the 1960s, former U.S.
Rep. Bella Abzug told female political activists today.
   ``Abortion is the Vietnam of this nation for young people
everywhere,'' Abzug told the opening session of the National
Women's Political Caucus' Biennial Convention.
   Abzug, a former Democratic representative from New York and a
founder of the caucus 18 years ago, was the first of several
speakers who are expected to address the abortion issue. The caucus
runs through Sunday.
   ``No civilized nation can be allowed to declare an unborn fetus
a person under the Constitution before women are declared persons
under the Constitution,'' Abzug said.
   On Thursday, Democratic National Committee Chairman Ron Brown
told the steering committee that the Democrats lost a chance to win
the 1988 presidential election by not doing more to garner votes
from women.
   ``In fact, we blew a major gender gap that might have carried
the Democratic candidate for president to the White House,'' Brown
said.
   Brown said he understands ``the frustrations of working in the
coalition.'' But he said those who counsel the formation of a third
party ``ignore the second half of the adage that begins, `United we
stand.'
   ``No matter where the struggle for justice ... divided we will
indeed fall and fail to reach our goals,'' he said.
   ``I have worked in the struggle for civil rights my entire adult
life, and I do not deny the problems of advancing a cause through
the Democratic Party,'' Brown told the steering committee of the
National Women's Political Caucus.
   ``But the alternative is self-righteous failure. It may feel
good when the first speeches are made, but it will be very, very
tragic when the votes are counted.''
   Brown told reporters later that the creation of a women's
political party probably would hurt Democrats more than
Republicans, but he added, ``I don't think it's going to hurt
anybody because I don't think it's going to happen.''
   No action similar to NOW's is expected at the National Women's
Political Caucus biennial convention, according to Irene Natividad,
head of the caucus. The convention, which officially convened
today, is expected to attract 1,500 delegates and guests.
   Brown also touched on the battle over abortion because of
restrictions allowed under a July 3 U.S. Supreme Court ruling.
   ``The Supreme Court and the right wing of this country threaten
women's rights and all of our rights,'' Brown said.
   He said the Democratic Party platform supports the right of a
woman to choose whether to have an abortion, as well as such
proposals as an Equal Rights Amendment.
   An invitation to Republican National Committee Chairman Lee
Atwater to address the leaders of the non-partisan caucus was
declined, Natividad said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
