<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica 1stLd-Writethru   08-04 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0499,0508</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede CAPE TOWN</HEAD>
<HEAD>Homeland Reported Cracking Down On Dissidents, Violence In Soweto</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with crackdown on two communities resisting
incorporation into a homeland. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The black homeland of
Bophuthatswana is intensifying its crackdown on two communities
that have violently resisted incorporation into the territory, an
anti-apartheid group said today.
   Also today, police imposed restrictions on the funeral of two
slain activists in a township near Cape Town and reported a series
of skirmishes between police and mixed-race youths.
   In other incidents, police said five blacks were killed in three
separate clashes in Natal Province, where supporters of militant
and relatively conservative political factions have engaged in a
three-year power struggle claiming hundreds of lives.
   Bophuthatswana, one of South Africa's four nominally independent
homelands, has arrested a local leader, banned anti-apartheid
groups and restricted a lawyer's access to people in the
communities of Braklaagte and Leeuwfontein.
   Lydia Kompe, spokeswoman for the Transvaal Rural Action
Committee which is opposed to the tribal homeland system, said the
Bophuthatswana government ``is still increasing its efforts against
its opponents'' in the two communities.
   The two neighboring villages were incorporated into the homeland
on Jan. 1 despite protests by many of the estimated 25,000
residents.
   The residents of Braklaagte and Leeuwfontein say they want to
remain part of South Africa and fear they will be discriminated
against by the Bophuthatswana government because of their
opposition to incorporation.
   The homelands are not recognized by any foreign countries.
   Eleven people, including nine policemen, were killed July 1 when
authorities sought to break up a rally in Leeuwfontein arranged by
residents who opposed joining Bophuthatswana.
   Thirty-three people charged with involvement in the fighting
were to appear in a Bophuthatswana court.
   Pupsey Sebogodi, leader of the Braklaagte community, has been
arrested three times this year and remains in detention, said the
Transvaal Rural Action Committee, which was banned from
Bophuthatswana by the homeland government.
   Authorities have threatened to deport the Rev. Eberhard Richter,
a German citizen and Luthern missionary who has served the
Braklaagte community since 1981, Ms. Kompe said.
   A South African lawyer representing the defendants, James
Sutherland, has been ordered to apply for a visa before he can
return to the homeland. The homeland has few formal border posts
and usually no visa is required to visit.
   About 2 million blacks live in Bophuthatswana, which consists of
seven separate pieces of land scattered across north-central South
Africa.
   The Cape Town regional police commissioner, Maj. Gen. Flip
Fourie, imposed restrictions on Saturday's funeral of two
mixed-race activists who died in a bomb blast last month. Police
said Robbie Waterwitch, 20, and Coline Williams, 22, were trying to
plant the bomb in a public toilet when it exploded.
   Fourie said the funeral service must take place indoors and be
addressed only by ordained clergymen. He said mourners cannot march
to the cemetery and cannot display any political posters, flags or
banners.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
