<FIRST>u w PM-DefenseSpending 3rdLd-Writethru a0555 08-04 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Defense Spending, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0555,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Military Spending Eliminates Funds for Two Bush Programs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New lead and inserts 4th graf, And in, to raise veto threat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House, deliberating less than an hour and
ignoring talk of a possible veto, today approved a $286.5 billion
military spending bill that makes wholesale changes in President
Bush's defense program.
   By a vote of 312-105, the House voted to adopt a spending plan
that slashes nearly $2 billion for Star Wars from the president's
request. strictly limits the B-2 stealth bomber program and makes
drastic cuts in the MX and Midgetman nuclear missiles.
   Despite the unusually rapid approval of the costly bill by the
Democratic-controlled House, the ranking Republican on the House
Armed Services Committee, Rep. William Dickinson of Alabama, said
Bush may veto the measure.
   And in advance of the vote, the White House budget office said
the president's senior advisers would recommend a veto on grounds
the measure ``would severely compromise the administration's
objective of providing adequate defense capabilities within
constrained resources.''
   ``They have conformed,'' Dickinson said of the appropriations
measure that conforms to the separate defense authorization bill
the House adopted last week. ``But that still makes it veto-bait in
my opinion.''
   The bill, approved as Congress rushed to complete pending
business before starting a month-long recess later today, slashed
$2 billion from classified programs that include the advanced
fighter and advanced cruise missile.
   The money bill also incorporates the cuts the House made in the
Star Wars anti-missile program, the B-2 stealth bomber and the MX
and Midgetman nuclear missiles in the policy-setting authorization
bill.
   The House cut Bush's request of $4.9 billion for Star Wars by
$1.8 billion, imposed strict limitation on production of the
radar-evading B-2, trimmed $502 million from the $1.1 billion
sought for the MX rail-garrison system and eliminated all $100
million sought for the Midgetman.
   Dickinson said he hoped that when members of the the Senate and
House meet early in September to craft a final version of the bill,
the ``most egregious add-ons and deletions can be modified and
limited to make it acceptable to the administration.''
   But he said as they stand now, he does not support the
authorization and appropriations bills and would recommend that
Bush veto the legislation.
   ``I think it will be vetoed,'' Dickinson said.
   But Rep. Ted Weiss, D-N.Y., complained about suggestions that
House-Senate conferees will change what the House did after the
chamber ``worked its will on the defense authorization bill.''
   ``That really borders on the ridiculous. The House has spoken,''
Weiss said.
   The bill adds $893 million to the administration's budget for
the purchase of 24 new F-14 jet fighters and 12 EA-6B Prowlers,
both manufactured by Grumman Aerospace Corp.
   Bush has proposed canceling the F-14D, a carrier-based fighter
plane the House restored in its authorization bill. The House
earmarked about $1 billion for 24 planes over two years.
   Rep. John Murtha, D-Pa., chairman of the House Appropriations
defense subcommittee, criticized the increasing costs of the
Advanced Tactical Fighter and favored spending money on
conventional projects.
   The appropriations bill is designed to provide the money for the
defense programs approved by the House last week. The measure calls
for $286.5 billion in budget authority and $281.9 billion in
outlays, but doesn't include money for the Department of Energy and
military construction.
   The House defense authorization bill totals $305 billion _ $295
billion for the Defense Department and $10 billion for military
nuclear programs handled by the Energy Department.
  
</TEXT>
</DOC>
