<DOCNO> AP890804-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 1239EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-CentralAmerica     08-04 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Central America,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sandinistas, Opposition Agree Contras Should Be Disbanded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega said today the
Sandinista government and opposition groups have agreed that the
U.S.-supported Contra rebels should be disbanded.
   The government also said it would suspend the military draft for
five months, starting in September, to ease tensions with the
opposition and to help keep the war from flaring up.
   Ortega, who will attend a two-day Central American summit this
weekend, said he will insist at the summit that camps housing
12,000 Contras and thousands of their dependents in southern
Honduras be disbanded.
   Honduran President Jose Azcona Hoyo has also been saying for
some time that his country finds the Contras a burden.
   The summit, involving the presidents of El Salvador, Nicaragua,
Guatemala and Costa Rica, is part of a regional peace plan that
aims to negotiate an end to the Contra conflict and to the leftist
guerrilla war in El Salvador. It is being held in the Caribbean
beach resort of Tela.
   The talks Saturday and Sunday will concentrate mostly on
Nicaragua.
   Both the United States and Contra leaders are resisting the move
to disband the Contras and want to postpone such a move until after
Nicaragua's government holds free and fair elections Feb. 25, as
promised.
   The agreement to back disbandment was reached after 22 hours of
talks between Sandinistas and leaders of 20 opposition parties. The
talks recessed Thursday night.
   Sandinista leaders also said they planned to suspend the
military draft from September until after the February elections in
an effort to ease tensions with the opposition and de-escalate the
war.
   The talks were called by the Sandinistas to reform Nicaragua's
election laws to accomodate opposition objections that their
candidates were not allowed to campaign freely in past elections.
   Past constraints on the opposition included news censorship.
   The agreement on disbanding the Contras ``calls on the
presidents of Central America to push forward the plan to
demobilize and repatriate voluntarily'' the rebels.
   It also called on ``the region's governments to abstain from
carrying out undercover activities during Nicaragua's electoral
process.''
   The Sandinistas also pledged to grant unconditional amnesty to
all people arrested for inciting political disorder.
   Bernard Aronson, assistant secretary of state for inter-American
affairs, visited Guatemala and other Central American nations this
week to urge against disbanding the Contras until after elections.
   Adolfo Calero, a member of the rebel political directorate, said
he was ``elated that President Bush has come out unequivocally in
favor of having the resistance remain as a viable force.''
   The process of democratization in Nicaragua, promised by the
leftist Sandinista government, remains to be seen, Calero said.
``You do not take down the scaffold before the building is
finished,'' he said.
   A senior State Department official in Washsington, briefing
reporters on the Aronson trip, cited complaints that the Sandinista
government is mounting raids against suspected Contra sympathizers
in northern Nicaragua and has failed to create fair conditions for
political opponents.
   All U.S. military aid to the Contras was cut off a year ago and
the rebels now receive a trickle of non-lethal assistance, such as
food and boots.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
