<FIRST>u w PM-Ethics 1stLd-Writethru a0576 08-04 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ethics, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0576,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethics Committee To Investigate Three Accused of Sexual Improprieties</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 4 grafs new with comment, picking up at 3rd graf pvs, Three
House; subs last 3 grafs pvs with 5 grafs with new material</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House ethics committee has voted to
investigate three lawmakers accused in complaints of sexual
improprieties, two of the members and congressional sources said
today.
   The committee voted in secret session Thursday to conduct
preliminary inquiries into the conduct of Reps. Gus Savage, D-Ill.,
Donald E. ``Buz'' Lukens, R-Ohio, and Jim Bates, D-Calif.
   William Jarrell, press spokesman for Lukens, said the
congressman confirmed to him that he has been formally notified by
the ethics panel of the decision. Bates said he was also was
formally notified of the committee action.
   Savage's office had no immediate comment. But House sources,
speaking only on condition they not be named, confirmed that he
also would be investigated.
   Three House Democrats filed a complaint against Savage this
month, after news accounts said a Peace Corps volunteer complained
the lawmaker fondled her while he was traveling in Zaire.
   Since the incident, the State Department inspector general has
sent investigators to collect information on Savage's actions
during official foreign travels, according to a House member who
would speak only as an unnamed source.
   News accounts this week said that when Savage was in China as
part of a delegation from the House Science and Technology
Committee, he revised his schedule and went to Hong Kong and South
Korea for shopping and sightseeing.
   Before he moved to Hong Kong, Savage locked himself in a hotel
room to protest the U.S. embassy's failure to immediately get him
on a flight, the accounts said.
   Savage told reporters two weeks ago, ``I did nothing, that's
what I did. This lie was leaked by the State Department for
political reasons.''
   ``They tried to destroy Dr. Martin Luther King with a lie. ...
I'm in good company,'' he said at the time..
   The House Republican caucus, composed of all Republicans, asked
the ethics panel to investigate Lukens, who was convicted in Ohio
on a misdemeanor charge of contributing to the unruliness of a
child. Lukens was sentenced June 30 to 180 days in jail and fined
$1,000 for having sex with a teen-age girl. He is appealing.
   Lukens has said his conviction is no worse than drunk driving or
shoplifting. He has criticized House Republican leaders for seeking
the ethics investigation.
   Jarrell, the Lukens aide, said the Ohio Republican ``has already
said he welcomes a full and open investigation where his accusers'
motives and the full record can be brought forth.''
   He added that Lukens would be able to bring the committee
information about the credibility of the teen-age girl and her
mother, which was inadmissible in the courtroom. ``That's a
positive for Lukens,'' he said.
   The complaint against Bates was filed last year by two former
aides, who alleged he sexually harassed female members of his
staff, and pressured congressional employees into doing campaign
work.
   Bates said the committee told him there were ``sworn complaints
from two individuals saying they were sexually harassed and that
congressional resources were used to perform political activity. I
would deny they were sexually harassed and that the staff and
resources were used to perform campaign-related activities _ at
least under my direction.''
   Bates added, ``I look forward to having the matter resolved. It
has gone on for a year without any action. I would like it
resolved. I don't think it warrants a preliminary inquiry, but if
the committee does, we'll cooperate in any way we can.''
</TEXT>
