<FIRST>u i AM-China 1stLd-Writethru a0604 08-04 0766</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0604,0782</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Says Intellectuals Will Be Spared, But Punishes Fang</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to DELETE reference to throat cancer.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China said Friday it would not crack down on
intellectuals even though some participated in recent pro-democracy
protests, but it also stripped leading dissident Fang Lizhi of his
post on an academic board.
   The Foreign Ministry, meanwhile, refused immediate comment on
reports by a Japanese news agency that senior leader Deng Xiaoping
is gravely ill with prostate cancer.
   An unsigned commentary in the Communist Party newspaper People's
Daily appeared aimed at reassuring China's educated elite, some of
whom have come under sharp attack for supporting what the party
calls ``bourgeois liberalism'' _ Western liberal ideas _ and the
student-led pro-democracy movement.
   ``There has been some concern as to whether the party's policy
toward intellectuals would change. It is necessary to reaffirm that
(it) has not changed and will not change,'' the commentary said.
   It called the intellectuals who took part in the student
movement ``scum of the intellectuals (who) do not represent the
intellectuals'' and ``enemies of the party and of the people.''
   ``It is in the interest of the workers, peasants and
intellectuals to punish them, and the party will protect that
interest,'' it said.
   ``Those who were under the influence of the wave of bourgeois
liberalism ...will elevate their understanding and continue to make
contributions'' to China's modernization program, it said.
   The army's violent crackdown on mass demonstrations in early
June has ushered in a new era of repression. Chinese are urged to
turn in friends and family members who participated in the
protests, and many must attend weekly political study sessions
reminiscent of the ultra-leftist Cultural Revolution.
   The crackdown has brought an end to a period of relatively free
political debate. Newspapers once more are under strict party
control, and the works of 10 writers, including Fang, have been
banned.
   The official Xinhua News Agency said Friday that Fang, an
astrophysicist, was relieved of his position on the Academic
Degrees Committee under the State Council, China's Cabinet, and of
his qualification to tutor doctoral students.
   Fang, who took refuge inside the U.S. Embassy in Beijing with
his wife shortly after the crackdown, already had lost another
minor post but apparently still retains his main job at the Beijing
Observatory.
   The government has issued arrest warrants for Fang and his wife,
physics professor Li Shuxian, for allegedly inciting pro-democracy
protests and has demanded that the U.S. Embassy turn them over to
Chinese authorities.
   Thousands of students, intellectuals and others are believed to
have been arrested for participating in the seven-week movement.
   During the 1966-76 Cultural Revolution, intellectuals were
severely persecuted as ``class enemies.'' Since then, Deng hasd
emphasized the need for skilled and talented intellectuals to help
China modernize.
   The educated elite, however, remains among the lowest paid and
most politically vulnerable of all Chinese.
   In Japan on Friday, the Jiji Press quoted unidentified Chinese
sources as saying the health of Deng, 84, had deteriorated
seriously a few days ago, and that emergency medical personnel were
sent to care for him at a coastal resort east of Beijing. It quoted
doctors as saying they were discussing whether Deng was too ill to
be moved to Beijing, where better facilities were available.
   An employee in the information department of China's Foreign
Ministry said he had received many queries about Deng's health but
could issue no immediate response. There was no answer Friday night
at the Communist Party's news office.
   In another development, Britain's Home Ofice said it has granted
political asylum to three Chinese diplomats and is considering an
application from a fourth.
   A Home Office spokesman identified one of the diplomats given
asylum Nin Hongshan, a second secretary in the embassy's
educational section. He said the others were all middle-ranking
diplomats but would not identify them.
   In New York, two Chinese exiles said a group that aims to
provide a democratic alternative to China's Communist Party will
hold its inaugural congress of 120 delegates from around the world
next month.
   The congress will be held secretly in the West and will involve
exiled student leaders and intellectuals as well as individuals
traveling surreptitiously from China, said the exiles, Wan Runnan
and Yan Jiaqi.
   Wan is former chairman of the Stone Corp., a large computer
company that is one of China's most successful private enterprises.
Yan is a former member of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences
and a former close adviser to deposed Communist Party leader Zhao
Ziyang.
</TEXT>
