<FIRST>u a PM-NYCCorruption 1stLd-Writethru a0565 08-04 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NYC Corruption, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0565,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Koch Aide Indicted for Perjury</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with announcement, arraignment,
details. Picks up 7th graf, `The commission....'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former high-ranking aide to Mayor Edward I.
Koch has been indicted for perjury in testimony regarding political
patronage, officials announced today, less than six weeks before
the mayoral primary election.
   Joseph DeVincenzo, former special assistant to Koch, was accused
of lying to the New York State Commission on Government Integrity
on July 13 and 21 last year and in a public hearing of that
commission this past Jan. 11.
   DeVincenzo, 46, told the commission that politically connected
job applicants were not given favorable treatment, a position
contradicted by other witnesses.
   DeVincenzo appeared in state court today, pleaded innocent and
was released on his own recognizance pending an Aug. 11 hearing.
   Assistant District Attorney Michael Cherkasky, who announced
today that the 11-count indictment issued up Thursday, noted that
patronage is not illegal. Perjury, however, is punishable by a
maximum of seven years in prison.
   DeVincenzo was responsible for the city's Talent Bank, which
ostensibly recruited minorities to fill city posts. Critics claim
the program actually was a patronage mill, doling out the highest
paying jobs to whites.
   Files relating to the program's operations were destroyed at the
beginning of city corruption scandals. DeVincenzo and others told
the commission that the destruction of those records was routine
and not part of a cover-up.
   The Talent Bank, which operated out of an office in the basement
of City Hall, has become a campaign issue as Koch seeks the
Democratic nomination to run for a fourth term in November.
   District Attorney Robert Morgenthau, in an telephone interview,
defended the timing of the indictment.
   ``We did consider it,'' Morgenthau said. ``But we could not be
in the role of censor, deciding what the public could and could not
hear.''
   He said that if possible, the charges would have been filed
earlier, but ``we moved as expeditiously as we could.''
   The commission was told that some of the files at the Talent
Bank were marked with color codes, indicating a party leader or
other political sponsor who might have referred an applicant to
DeVincenzo.
   His own assistant, James G. Hein, testified that DeVincenzo had
ordered him in February 1986 to ``cleanse'' the employment computer
and paper files of ``any references to political figures.''
   In February, Koch announced that he had asked for DeVincenzo's
resignation. But DeVinenzo had already filed papers to resign,
ensuring his pension of $52,000 a year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
