<DOCNO> AP890804-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 1530EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hostages-Decision     08-04 0752</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostages-Decision,0772</SECOND>
<HEAD>Analysts Say Obeid Abduction Put Hostages Back on World Agenda</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hostages Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli analysts said Friday the apparent
willingness of pro-Iranian kidnappers to suspend threats and start
talking has vindicated Israel's decision to abduct a Shiite Moslem
cleric.
   They say creating movement on the hostage issue is an
achievement, even though there is no guarantee negotiations will
start in earnest or result in freeing either Israeli soldiers or
Western hostages.
   The Israelis have offered to trade Sheik Abdul Karim Obeid for
three of their soldiers held prisoner in Lebanon and the 16 Western
hostages, who include eight Americans. Obeid is a spiritual leader
of Hezbollah, a Shiite group believed responsible for kidnappings
of foreigners.
   ``Israel put the issue of hostages back on the international
agenda,'' said Shlomo Avineri, a former director-general of the
Foreign Ministry.
   Until the current crisis, ``the West accepted people being
captured by bandits and had come to believe nothing could be done
about it,'' he said in an interview.
   Shlomo Gazit, a former chief of military intelligence, said the
abduction was a catalyst for a new willingness by Hezbollah to
trade hostages. Without it, ``nothing would have happened and all
the existing hostages would be in the same hopeless situation as
before,'' he said.
   Gazit said it also ``put the Israeli hostages on the agenda, and
that was the exact purpose.''
   Zeev Schiff, a leading military commentator, was among the few
public critics. Writing in the liberal daily Haaretz on Friday, he
called the abduction a policy of ``restrained lunacy,'' but added
that it might help deter future acts of terror.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin authorized the July 28 abduction
by Israeli commandos after coming under intense pressure to get the
Israeli soldiers home.
   Dore Gold of Tel Aviv University's Jaffee Center for Strategic
Studies, said there was a special sensitivity in Israel about not
abandoning soldiers in the field.
   Failure to act, he said, ``would have a very deleterious effect
on the morale of the army when it goes into battle. So that leaves
an activist policy as the only choice after efforts to arrange
negotiations failed.''
   ``Sometimes there is a misunderstanding why Israel is not more
aggressive in offering peace,'' he said, adding that the week's
events ``show that the Middle East is a violent region ... and you
have to understand Israel's caution.''
   Obeid's abduction brought criticism from the United States,
especially after the captors of Lt. Col. William R. Higgins, a U.S.
Marine kidnapped while on U.N. duty, said Monday they had hanged
him in retaliation. They released a videotape of a man who appeared
to be Higgins on a gallows.
   Some critics said Israel had failed to consider the effect of
its actions on American hostages, even though Israeli officials and
some other reports say Higgins was killed several months ago.
   Such attacks caused concern in Israel, which depends on
Washington for $3 billion a year in economic and military aid, but
Avi Pazner, chief spokesman for Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, said
there was no lasting damage.
   ``The attempt by Hezbollah to drive a wedge between Israel and
the United States failed,'' Pazner said. ``All and all, we are
pleased to see our standing in public opinion is very high on this
issue. This is very gratifying.''
   Israel may not be out of the woods, however. Some analysts
believe the final evaluation of Israel's actions will depend on the
results of negotiations.
   Avineri, of Hebrew University in Jerusalem, said the action
``will be judged by its outcome. If the outcome is horrible and
hostages are killed, Israel will be condemned. If some or all the
hostages are freed, no one will split hairs about marginal
mistakes.''
   How far Israel will go in meeting Shiite demands for release of
an unspecified number of Palestinians remains a question. About
8,000 Palestinians have been jailed since an uprising against
Israeli occupation began 20 months ago in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip.
   Officials are likely to oppose allowing hard-core activists and
convicted killers to return to the occupied lands, which happened
after 1,050 Arabs were traded in May 1985 for three soldiers held
by a radical Palestinian group led by Ahmed Jibril.
   Moshe Nativ, a retired general who helped negotiate that
exchange, said on army radio Obeid was the strongest card for
getting hostages out of Lebanon. In 1985, he noted, there was no
movement in negotiations ``until we kidnapped (Jibril's) nephew.''
</TEXT>
