<FIRST>r w AM-MessyDesks     08-04 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Messy Desks,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>`I'll Call You Back If I Can Find My Phone Under This Stuff'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Washington consulting firm has thrown down
the gauntlet. Atop last week's milk carton, the call of the roll
from the 1964 Republican National Convention and a copy of the
Washington Star, which folded Aug. 7, 1981, turns up an
announcement looking for the messiest desk in Washington.
   The prize, worth $415, is free tuition in the firm's training
course in time management. That is, how to have a tidy desk and,
presumably, tidy habits.
   The offer comes from Priority Management, which trains people in
how to arrange their day, manage their time, keep their files and,
above all else, prioritize.
   Priority Management has no intention of inspecting the nominated
desks to separate the truly disgusting from the merely slovenly. It
will settle for photographic evidence, says Cynthia M. Rozzo,
director of marketing and the brains behind the contest.
   True to form, this is what she has to say, unprompted:
   ``A cluttered desk is a cluttered mind.''
   The contest entries, says Ms. Rozzo, on whose desk there is a
place for everything and everything is in its place, will be
scrutinized for these symptoms:
   _Multiple calendars. (They lead to overbooking, says Ms. Rozzo.)
   _Those little pink phone messages, scattered around. (One may
return yesterday's call more than once.)
   _Reminders on scraps of paper, strewn about. (Tch, tch.)
   _Someday files (as in ``someday I'll get around to it'').
   _Leaning towers in the ``in'' box.
   _Open files atop the desk.
   ``Open files distract from the task at hand,'' Ms. Rozzo said,
yielding to an impulse to instruct.
   ``Let's say you have four projects going on at the same time.
People usually have files from all four on their desks. We show
people they shouldn't do that. We say put three of the files on
some other piece of office furniture. We love credenzas. People who
make credenzas love us.''
   Ms. Rozzo said her firm teaches people how to organize their
day, how to say ``No, I can't talk to you,'' how to delegate and
how to keep a boss or colleague from laying on an unscheduled chore
by asking, ``Is it urgent and important? Can it wait?''
   Instead of saying, ``I'll get back to you,'' says Ms. Rozzo,
``you should say, `I will call you on Aug. 9.'''
   One should not say, ``I will call you on Aug. 9 if I can find my
telephone under this pile of stuff.'' That is very untidy. It will
not do.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
