<FIRST>u i AM-Israel     08-04 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Uprising Leaders Warns Against Infighting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The underground leadership of the Palestinian
uprising Friday denounced groups that have threatened Arab
nationalists, claiming the infighting is inspired by Israel.
   ``Nationalists have been accused of collaboration and their cars
have been burned in the name of the uprising,'' said a leaflet
signed by the Unified Leadership Strike Forces and circulated in
the West Bank.
   It urged Palestinians to ``declare war'' on those issuing false
leaflets, which it said were ``inspired by suspicious elements
working in the enemy's (Israel's) intelligence.''
   The statement comes amid a growing trend of violence, threats
and factional rivalry within the Arab community in the 20-month-old
uprising.
   At least 87 Palestinian deaths have been blamed on other Arabs
since the revolt against Israeli rule began in December 1987. Army
gunfire and Israeli settlers have killed 527 Palestinians.
Thirty-eight Israelis also have died.
   The army said Friday it is investigating the stabbing death of
an Arab man whose body was found near Kufr Zibad village, 30 miles
northwest of Jerusalem.
   Israel radio quoted residents as saying the man was suspected of
collaborating with Israel and had been interrogated by uprising
leaders before he was slain.
   The underground leadership's leaflet condemned statements issued
by 10 largely obscure groups, including the Palestinian Popular
Army.
   A statement issued in the name of the Popular Army on July 16
threatened Bir Zeit University Professor Sari Nusseibeh for
allegedly misusing uprising funds and cooperating with Israel.
   Prosecution papers filed in an Israeli case against several
uprising leaders alleged Nusseibeh was paymaster of the uprising.
But the professor, a Palestine Liberation Organization supporter,
never was charged.
   Jamil Tarifi, a West Bank lawyer, was threatened by wall slogans
signed by the Marxist Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine. The leaflet did not refer to that group, which
participates in the unified leadership.
   Tarifi recently announced that he took part in talks with
Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir. Several Arabs have met with
Shamir to discuss his peace initiative, but Tarifi is the only one
to publicly admit it.
   The initiative calls for elections in the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip to select Palestinians to open talks with Israel on
limited autonomy.
   Shamir on Friday again ruled out any dealings with the PLO,
which Israel brands a terrorist organization but many Palestinians
consider their sole legitimate representative.
   ``We will not meet and talk with the PLO,'' Shamir told a
delegation from the United Jewish Appeal. ``They are not partners
to peace. They are the very opposite of peace. Their objective is
to eliminate the Jewish state and replace it with another Arab
state.''
   His comments coincided with the general congress of the PLO's
dominant Fatah faction in Tunisia, where chairman Yasser Arafat is
seeking support for his recent moderate stance and calls for peace
with Israel.
</TEXT>
