<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon     08-04 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrian-Christian Clash in South Beirut Kills 2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shells crashed into residential areas of
Beirut on Friday during a five-hour battle that sent civilians
rushing to bomb shelters. Police said two people died and seven
were wounded.
   The clash started as an exchange of sniper fire between the
Christian district of Ein Rummaneh and the adjacent Shiite Moslem
slum of Chiyah. It developed into a duel with howitzers, mortars
and cannons that lasted until midday.
   Each side accused the other of starting the clash.
   Explosions echoed through the narrow alleys of Chiyah, and
people ran for cover as the call to Friday prayers blared from
mosque minarets. Businesses that opened in nearby districts closed.
   ``Now they're shelling Chiyah. It might develop and reach us,''
said Najib Masoud, a grocer in the Zarif neighborhood.
   ``What a life. We are living under the ground like the dead. We
might as well die,'' he murmured as he lowered his shop's shutter
and headed off for a shelter with a bag of canned food and some
bottled water.
   By police count, the 20-week-old confrontation between the
predominantly Christian troops of Gen. Michel Aoun and Syrian
troops has killed 516 people and wounded 2,183.
   A spokesman for Aoun's command, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Syrian snipers in Chiyah targeted his soldiers'
positions in Ein Rummaneh.
   ``Our sharpshooters responded to the fire. They (Syrians)
upgraded their fire power and we responded in kind,'' the spokesman
said.
   A spokesman for the mainstream Shiite Moslem Amal militia,
Syria's closest ally and dominant in Chiyah, said Syrian soldiers
``had to open fire at Aoun's army to protect Chiyah's citizens.''
   ``Aoun's soldiers were shooting at everything that moved in
Chiyah early in the morning. The Syrians fired back to silence the
sources of fire,'' said the Amal spokesman, who identified himself
only by the code name Abu Ali.
   He said Amal fighters did not take part in the confrontation.
   A police spokesman, who cannot be named in line with
regulations, said the two fatalities occurred in Chiyah.
   Syrian gunners Chiyah opened up with 130mm Soviet-designed
howitzers at the Christian suburb of Kfarshima, southeast of
Beirut, the police spokesman said.
   He said Aoun's gunners responded with 155mm U.S.-made howitzers,
shelling Chiyah and the Druse suburb of Choueifat.
   Aoun's tanks deployed in the suburb of Haszmiyeh, east of
Beirut, also shelled the Shiite slums of Sfeir and Moallem on
Chiyah's southern edge, he added.
   Only 200,000 people of Beirut's original 1.5 million population
remain in the city, the main arena for ferocious shelling duels
since the Christian-Syrian confrontation broke out March 8.
   Most refugees have settled in south Lebanon, the eastern Bekaa
valley and the Christian-controlled mountain resorts northeast of
Beirut.
   The confrontation broke out after Aoun blockaded illegal ports
run by Syrian-backed militias to recover lost customs dues.
   The Syrians and allied Moslem and leftist forces retaliated by
shelling the 310-square-mile Christian enclave northeast of the
capital.
   Aoun, a Maronite Catholic, escalated the confrontation by
declaring a ``war of liberation'' against the 40,000 Syrian troops
deployed in predominantly Moslem sections of Lebanon.
</TEXT>
