<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Climber     08-04 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Climber,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paraplegic Ranger Presents Flag to President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A paraplegic Park Service ranger who used only
his arm strength to climb a 3,200-foot rock face in Yosemite
presented President Bush on Friday with an American flag that he
and his partner carried.
   ``This is great,'' the president told climber Mark Wellman, who
came to the Oval Office in his wheelchair. ``You certainly captured
the imagination of the whole country.''
   Wellman later said the Park Service needs more federal money to
spend on making the national parks accessible to the handicapped.
But he said he did not have time in his brief meeting with Bush to
discuss such issues.
   ``We just need more attention brought to it,'' he told reporters
after the meeting.
   Wellman, a naturalist for the park service and director of
Yosemite's program for the disabled, said he and Bush discussed the
president's love of the outdoors and fishing.
   The 29-year-old climber, dressed in his park ranger uniform, and
his fellow climber, Mike Corbett, gave Bush an American flag that
was in the gear they cut loose before they reached the summit of El
Capitan on their climb of seven days and four hours.
   Also attending the meeting were Park Service Director Jim
Ridenour and Jack Moorehead, associate director of operations for
the Park Service.
   Wellman and Corbett completed the climb on July 26.
   Wellman hauled himself, six inches at a time, to the top of the
cliff, one of Yosemite's most well-known landmarks.
   Their climb captured widespread media attention, including a
news conference attended by some 55 reporters and rangers when they
reached the summit.
   Wellman, whose legs were paralyzed in a 1982 fall from another
Yosemite peak, was the first paraplegic to make the vertical trek,
doing 7,000 pullups on ropes placed by Corbett.
   Wellman chose a route that was almost straight up because it was
more practical for him.
   The route included tackling the Shield Roof, a ledge jutting 40
feet out from the monolith at 2,000 feet above Yosemite Valley.
Wellman and Corbett had to dangle beneath it and hoist themselves
up a rope with the valley floor far below them.
</TEXT>
