<FIRST>r i AM-Greece-Plane     08-04 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece-Plane,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rescuers Recover Bodies, Flight Recorder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NIKOS KONSTANDARAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAMOS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers crawled on their hands and knees
up a mountain slope Friday to recover bodies and the flight
recorder of an Olympic Airlines plane that slammed into the highest
peak in the Aegean, killing 34 people.
   The twin-engine plane, circling in thick fog Thursday, hit
4,785-feet Mount Kerkis in the Kournies region of this eastern
Aegean island off Turkey's southwest coast.
   The rescuers found remains of bodies and the aft section of the
30-seat British-built aircraft on an inaccessible slope of the
mountain at 3,960 feet. The plane was split in half with debris
scattered over a wide area.
   The front part of the plane had disintegrated when it hit the
mountain, leaving only a black scar on the steep slope.
   Searchers said they found the flight recorder in the aft section
of the aircraft, one of the few parts left intact.
   ``It appears that thick fog in the area at the time played the
villain's role as the pilot flew blindly into the mountainside,''
said an airline official who spoke on condition of anonymity. He
added that pilots fly ``visually'' on flights to small Aegean
islands that Olympic services.
   The rescuers approached the crash site early Friday, crawling on
their hands and knees for 90 minutes up a steep slope in darkness.
   ``Unfortunately, we could do nothing,'' said Emmanuel Karlas, a
doctor from a nearby village.``I checked every body I could find.''
   No immediate attempts were made to remove the bodies because of
the inaccessible terrain, but managed to ferry out at least nine
bodies later in the day.
   Officials did not say how many bodies were recovered.
   It was the first air crash for Olympic in 13 years. Officials
said the propeller-driven plane had not experienced any serious
problems since it went into service in 1981.
   There were 34 people aboard, including an infant, airline
officials said.
   Officials said pilot Petros Moutzoureas was an hour into his
domestic flight from Salonica in northern Greece when he radioed
his final position as he made his approach for landing.
   The plane disappeared from Athens and Salonica radar screens
when it was about 25 miles off the island's northwest coast. When
it failed to land at 5:30 p.m., officials ordered and air and sea
search.
   Transport and Communications Minister Nikos Gelestathis said all
the victims were Greeks, although Yannis Orphanides, a Canadian of
Greek descent, said in Salonica that his parents, brother, wife and
infant son _ all Canadians from Toronto _ were killed.
   The Canadian Embassy in Athens said three other passengers who
had booked their tickets in Toronto also could have been Canadian
citizens. An embassy official said they were checking with their
foreign office in Ottawa to confirm their nationality.

</TEXT>
