<FIRST>r i AM-Hostages-Goulding     08-04 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostages-Goulding,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top U.N. Official Meeting Pro-Iranian Groups In Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N. envoy investigating the reported
hanging of U.S. Marine Lt. Col. William Higgins is the world body's
top peacekeeping official, a career British diplomat and an Arabist.
   Marrack I. Goulding, known to colleagues as ``Mig,'' is the U.N.
undersecretary-general for special political affairs, the
department in charge of peacekeeping and major political issues
from the Middle East to Namibia.
   Goulding, 52, is an Arabic speaker who served in Kuwait, Libya
and Egypt. In 1986 he succeeded Brian E. Urquardt, the U.N.
undersecretary-general who pioneered peacekeeping. He served as
British ambassador to Angola from 1983 to 1985.
   From 1979 to 1983 Goulding was counsellor and head of chancery
at the British Mission to the United Nations. During that period he
served as alternate representative to the Security Council.
   He also served in the British delegation to the General Assembly
and was president of the U.N. Trusteeship Council from 1981 to 1982.
   Goulding graduated from Magdalen College, Oxford, where he
received honors in Greek and Latin language and literature, ancient
history, Greek and modern philosophy.
   He joined the British diplomatic service in 1959 and served at
the British embassy in Kuwait from 1961 to 1964. He subsequently
served in the Foreign Office in London, and in postings in Libya,
Egypt and Portugal.
