<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-US     08-04 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-US,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ambassador Says U.S. Bases Vital to Development</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American military bases in the
Philippines play a vital role in regional stability and should be
maintained despite favorable changes in the Soviet political
climate, the U.S. ambassador said Friday.
   Ambassador Nicholas Platt told a seminar at the University of
the Philippines that economic development in the Philippines and
elsewhere in Asia ``cannot happen without security.''
   ``There is a regional consensus that the U.S. security umbrella
is as important now, even in this changing era, as it was before,''
Platt said.
   ``If we are to have a successful new partnership, we will need
continuing American involvement in the security of this region,''
Platt said. ``Our military facilities here in the Philippines are
one element of the security equation.''
   The United States and the Philippines are expected to begin
preliminary talks this year on whether to extend the lease on the
six American installations, which expires in 1991.
   After 1991, any extension must be approved by two-thirds of the
23-member Philippine Senate.
   Opposition to the bases has been growing here. Several leading
politicians have called for the bases to be closed in 1991 or
phased out over a 10-year period.
   President Corazon Aquino has refused to say whether she will
support an extension.
   Platt said the economy of the Philippines depends on trade and
the bases play a vital role in protecting sea lanes.
   ``There is a balance between the United States, the Soviet
Union, Japan and China,'' Platt said. ``And the maintenance of that
balance creates the stability that everybody is trying to preserve.
The maintenance of that stability provides the background for the
progress, the economic progress, that everybody wants.''
   Platt noted that the Soviet Union is undergoing political
changes that ``are welcome to us.
   ``But we don't think it is smart, and we don't think it makes
sense, to dismantle the alliance relationships that we have while
we are assessing what these changes are.''
   In a related development, Filipino diplomats said a U.S.
congressional delegation will visit the Philippines to look into
the possibility of withdrawing some troops in the next few years.
   About 40,000 U.S. troops, civilian employees and military
dependents are stationed in the Philippines.
   The diplomats said Reps. Patricia Schroeder, John Murtha, and
Dante Fascell will arrive Aug. 11.
</TEXT>
