<FIRST>r w AM-EducationFunding 1stLd-Writethru a0642 08-04 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Education Funding, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0642,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Educators Say Bush Will Need to Provide Money as Well as Leadership</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs graf 6, bgng ``Atwell and,'' to insert bill has passed
House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two education leaders said Friday it will take
money as well as leadership to turn President Bush into the
education president he has said he wants to be.
   ``As long as there is a budget deadlock and the administration
has its hands tied by its own budget policies, it's going to be
very difficult for Bush to be the education president,'' said
Robert Atwell, president of the American Council on Education, an
umbrella group for all U.S. colleges and universities.
   Atwell and Dick Rosser, president of the 830-member National
Association of Independent Colleges and Universities, said they
hope Bush's education summit next month with the nation's governors
will include higher education as well as the elementary and
secondary grades.
   ``There are very serious problems'' in higher education, Rosser
said, among them ``an incredible need for science facilities'' and
more federal money for research support and student aid.
   ``It cannot be simply leadership at the national level. It's got
to be money,'' he said.
   Atwell and Rosser said higher education did not fare as well as
the lower grades in the House appropriations bill for fiscal 1990
that passed earlier this week.
   ``The House appropriations overall are really quite insufficient
and could do great damage to students,'' Atwell said. ``We're going
to be working very hard to do better in the Senate in higher
education than we did in the House.''
   Atwell and Rosser also pledged to continue fighting for a
separate aid program for students at for-profit schools, which have
a loan default rate four times as high as the 9 percent average for
four-year institutions.
   The House committee said it was concerned about sky-high default
rates at some trade schools and said there would be ``a full
review'' of defaults and other problems in the financial aid
program next year when the Higher Education Act comes up for
reapproval.
   The for-profit schools are attracting an ever-greater proportion
of grants and loans, some of them for classes of dubious value or
students with dubious ability, educators say.
   The shift prompted Atwell's controversial call for a separate
aid program and has also resulted in colleges and universities
devoting more of their own resources to campus-based student aid.
   Rosser said school-sponsored aid rose from $900 million in 1979
to $3.5 billion in the past year at the private, non-profit schools
he represents.
   Rosser said faculty salaries still don't match the purchasing
power they had in 1972 while ``staff salaries are much lower and
probably in much worse shape.''
   In addition, he said, schools are spending money on science
equipment that can't wait and a whole array of new services
designed to meet student needs and help schools stay competitive _
career placement departments, security forces, drug and alcohol
abuse programs, and counselors to help minority students and others
with special needs.
</TEXT>
