<FIRST>u w AM-US-Haiti     08-04 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Haiti,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Resumes Haiti Aid Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has agreed to provide Haiti
with $10 million in food aid, the first such assistance since the
failed elections of November 1987, it was announced Friday.
   Under terms of an agreement signed Thursday in Port-au-Prince,
Haiti will receive about 45,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat, which it
will sell on the local market. Proceeds will be used for
development projects.
   In making the announcement, which was first reported Thursday on
Haitian television, the Agency for International Development said
Congress approved the new aid in recognition of continuing progress
by the interim government of Gen. Prosper Avril toward free
elections.
   The decision also was based on Haiti's cooperation with the
United States in narcotics interdiction efforts, AID said.
   The Haitian government cancelled the November 1987 national
elections after an outburst of violence on the morning of the
balloting claimed at least 50 dead and dozens wounded.
   The Reagan administration suspended $62 million in economic aid
hours after Haiti disbanded the national electoral council.
   The only assistance provided since then has been for an
anti-narcotics program and for emergency aid following Hurricane
Gilbert last year.
   Humanitarian aid to the Haitian people through non-governmental
organizations has continued.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
