<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan     08-04 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rocket Barrage Hits Kabul, Kills 1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A barrage of rockets hit Kabul on
Friday, killing one person, injuring eight people and ending a
three-day lull in attacks on the Afghan capital, the government
said.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani said nine rockets
pounded the capital and most fell on the Duralaman district, where
the Defense Ministry has its headquarters, and the nearby
residential area of Cart-i-Se. He gave a casualty toll of one
killed and eight injured.
   The Afghan news agency Bakhtar said 19 rockets fell on the city,
killing one civilian and injuring four others.
   Amani said later he could not find out whether the figure of 19
was correct because government offices are closed on Friday.
   Officials at Avicina emergency hospital said one rocket hit the
mountain below the the Afghan TV broadcasting tower and one fell in
Cart-i-Char district near Kabul University.
   The Red Cross hospital said five injured persons were brought
there from Cart-i-Se and Cart-i-Char districts.
   This city of 2.25 million people had been subjected to almost
daily rocketing until earlier this week. Between June 25 and Aug.
1, U.N. sources said 281 people were killed and 745 injured in
rocket attacks and a car bombing. Nearly all victims were civilians.
   Afghan security forces launched a major search operation in and
around the capital Monday night and no rockets fell on Kabul until
Friday.
   During the operation, Amani said, security forces confiscated
100 Egyptian-made and Chinese-made rockets.
   Bakhtar quoted a security source as saying that from Tuesday to
Thursday, the air force flew 380 missions over areas where they
suspected there were enemy batteries.
   Supported by artillery and rockets, the air force carried out
attacks on the Paghman Valley, 15 miles west of Kabul, and in a
15-mile area east and southeast of the capital, Bakhtar reported
Thursday.
   It quoted the security source as saying the government plans to
expand the security belt around Kabul to prevent rocket attacks.
   Most rockets used against Kabul have a range of less than 20
miles, though longer range rockets also have been launched.
   No group has claimed responsibility for the recent attacks
against Kabul, though U.S.-backed guerrillas fighting to oust
President Najib's Soviet-backed government have said they were
responsible for previous rocketing.
   The guerrillas say they aim at military targets and blame the
government for attacks on schools, markets, bus stops and other
civilian targets _ an allegation vehemently denied by the
government.
</TEXT>
