<FIRST>r i AM-Tunisia-PLO     08-04 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tunisia-PLO,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fatah Affirms Support for Palestinian State, Israel's Existence</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO leader Yasser Arafat's Fatah movement
Friday affirmed its support for the declaration of a Palestinian
state and the recognition of Israel's right to exist, the
Palestinian news agency reported.
   The declarations were contained in a program adopted in November
by the Palestine National Council, the PLO's parliament in exile. A
third element, renunciation of terrorism, also was supported by
Fatah, the news agency Wafa said.
   About 1,000 delegates to the General Congress of Fatah, the main
component of the Palestine Liberation Organization, are meeting
behind closed doors in Tunis, where the PLO has its headquarters.
   At the congress, Arafat had been expected to come under fire
from Fatah members who opposed concessions to Israel, but the Wafa
dispatch suggested he was able to beat back the challenge.
   The second day of the congress was characterized by ``a frank
and animated discussion concerning internal and political problems,
which shows that the Fatah movement has restored its unity and
solidarity,'' Wafa said.
   The congress opened Thursday and was expected to last about five
days.
   Wafa said participants called for support for the intefadeh, or
Palestinian uprising against Israeli rule of the occupied
territories. The delegates accused Israel of ``a policy of the iron
fist against the Palestinian people in order to neutralize the
intefadeh.''
   Fatah spokesman Ahmed Abdel-Rahman said the congress decided not
to admit any non-Palestinian reporters, and foreign reporters were
not allowed in the vicinity of the Tunis congress hall where the
meeting was held.
   Several Palestinian reporters were allowed into the meeting but
remained silent about the proceedings.
   The Tunisian news agency said only 980 of the 1,059 congress
delegates were in Tunis on Friday but that others were arriving
from many parts of the world.
   The congress set up its group of officers and divided into
committees for discussion of its main topics.
   The essential point on the agenda was the nomination of 10
central committee members. Since the last Fatah congress in 1980,
five members have either been assassinated or joined more militant
PLO factions, and five new seats have been added to the central
committee.
</TEXT>
