<HEAD>Trains Collide in Cuba; 25 Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with search for victims. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two trains collided in Colon, Cuba, on
Friday, killing at least 25 people and injuring about 100, Cuba's
official Prensa Latina news agency said.
   The agency, monitored in Mexico City, said the collision
occurred about 4 a.m. in Colon, about 60 miles east of Havana, and
that many of the injured were reported seriously hurt.
   ``People trapped inside the cars are receiving attention from
medical teams,'' the dispatch said.
   The Mexican government news agency Notimex reported from Havana
that both locomotives were destroyed when the trains collided at
high speed. It said one train was bound from Havana to Sancti
Spiritus and the other from Camaguey to Havana.
   A search for victims continued, Notimex said.
