<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 1713EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-OldJustice     08-04 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Old Justice,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeal Filed In Age Discrimination Case Involving Vermont Jurist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER GRAFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for the state of Vermont said
Friday that they are appealing a federal judge's ruling that a
70-year-old state Supreme Court justice cannot be forced to retire
because of his age.
   Lawyers for the state of Vermont on Friday filed a notice in
U.S. District Court in Rutland that the case was being appealed to
the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, based in New York.
   At issue is whether a federal law prohibiting age discrimination
applies to appointed state judges. U.S. District Judge Lee
Gagliardi ruled last month that it does and struck down a state
order that Justice Louis Peck retire.
   His ruling, in effect, nullified a section of the Vermont
Constitution that requires all judges to retire at age 70. Peck
turned 70 last December, but refused to retire and filed suit when
the state ordered that he do so.
   Lawyer William Gray, representing the state, said he filed a
notice in U.S. District Court in Rutland that the state was
appealing to the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New York.
   ``The decision by the district court is inconsistent with other
rulings on the question and we feel it appropriate that the issue
be addressed by the 2nd Circuit,'' he said.
   Even though Peck won in the first round, he said he welcomed the
appeal. ``I think it is fair to say that both sides want this to go
as high as it can,'' said the justice, one of five on Vermont's
only appeals court.
   ``The higher it goes, the greater an impact it will have,'' Peck
said. ``What we really hope is that the U.S. Supreme Court will
agree to hear this so that we can finally settle the question once
and for all.''
   Gagliardi's ruling within the territory covered by the 2nd
Circuit conflicts with rulings by a federal judge in Massachusetts
and the 1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, which said the federal
law prohibiting discrimination does not apply to appointed state
judges.
   ``We believe that the confusion coming out of these cases may
make it more attractive for the (U.S. Supreme) court to agree to
hear this,'' said Peck.
   The disagreement is whether the federal Age Discrimination in
Employment Act supersedes state mandatory retirement provisions for
judges. The law prohibits age discrimination, but excludes certain
groups from the provision.
   The Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, which represents
Peck, argues that judges don't fall under any of the exceptions.
   Gray argues that judges fall under the exception granted for
policymakers, and that the Constitution requires Congress to state
its intention clearly when it wants to regulate qualifications for
such important state offices as judges.
   ``I expect our brief will address both the interpretation of the
statute and the constitutional implications,'' Gray said.
   If the ruling stands under appeal, Peck can remain on the
Supreme Court until his term expires in three years. He could also
seek another six-year term.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
