<DOCNO> AP890804-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 1639EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-SriLanka     08-04 0669</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0689</SECOND>
<HEAD>India Proposes Withdrawal Schedule; Three Killed In Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   India on Friday offered to withdraw
1,500 troops a week if the largest Tamil guerrilla group observes a
cease-fire, government sources said.
   Police said a strike called Friday by Sinhalese radicals to
protest 150 deaths disrupted normal life in the island nation, and
at least 15 people died in ethnic violence since Thursday,
including a Bhuddist priest.
   About 45,000 Indian troops are in Sri Lanka to enforce a July
1987 peace accord aimed at ending a Tamil ethnic strife in the
Indian Ocean republic, where the government is dominated by the
Sinhalese majority.
   Sri Lankan Foreign Ministry sources said the Indian offer came
Friday before the two sides ended a weeklong talk in New Delhi
aimed at finding ways to make India withdraw its troops.
   ``At this moment I can say that the talks went on well,'' Sri
Lankan High Commissioner, or Ambassador S.S.P.P. Kalpage said.
``There are proposals and counter-proposals, and also there are ifs
and buts,'' Kalpage said in New Delhi, the Indian capital.
   But Sri Lankian Foreign Ministry sources in Colombo said India
agreed to withdraw 1,500 troops a week provided the main Tamil
guerrilla group, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, observed a
cease-fire and that no Indians are attacked.
   The withdrawal also was conditional on Sri Lanka agreeing to
give more powers to the Tamil adminstration in the north and east
of Sri Lanka, where Tamils are a majority.
   Indian government officials in New Delhi were not available for
comment on the proposal. India has said that a hasty withdrawal
could cause even more bloodshed.
   Sinhalese-language posters signed by the guerrillas of the
Sinhalese People's Liberation Front warned businesses to close
Friday to protest the killing of 150 people by security forces a
week ago.
   Police and witnesses said the daylong strike appeared to be
successful as the usually-bustling capital was deserted. Shops and
offices were closed and vehicles stayed off the street.
   At least 150 people were killed July 28 when supporters of the
radicals defied a nationwide curfew and demonstrated against the
continued presence of Indian troops. Sinhalese radicals also oppose
the autonomy plan for Tamils.
   The government had said curfew violators would be shot on sight
to prevent what it calls a campaign of terror by the militants. The
curfew remains in effect from dusk to dawn.
   In Colombo, two Sinhalese men were killed Friday when a bomb
they were carrying exploded in Colombo, police said. A Sinhalese
woman was killed when troops fired at her vehicle which it did not
stop at a checkpoint.
   The priest, Kotikawatte Saddhatissa, was killed Thursday night
by six gunmen in a Colombo temple, police said. The gunmen were
suspected members of the Sinhalese People's Liberation Front, said
police officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Saddhatissa, 72, a supporter of President Ranasinghe Premadasa,
is the second religious leader to be killed by the radicals. In
February, the front's gunmen killed Bodaramulle Subitha, the head
priest of the Kalutara temple, 25 miles south of Colombo.
   Six Indian soldiers and five Tamil Tiger militants were killed
in a gunbattle in the northern Jaffna peninsula on Thursday, said
Indian officials in New Delhi, speaking on condition of anonymity.
Some civilians were also killed, they said.
   Authorities blame the Sinhalese radicals for at least 4,000
killings and a series of crippling strikes since the start of an
anti-government uprising two years ago.
   At least 11,000 people, including 1,000 Indian soldiers, have
been killed in the 6-year-old Tamil insurgency.
   India became involved in the peace plan because of pressures
from its own 60 million Tamils who are sympathetic to the rebel
cause.
   Tamils, who make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people,
have been fighting for an independent nation since 1983, claiming
they are discriminated against by the Sinhalese, who make up 75
percent of the population and control the government and the
military.
</TEXT>
