<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 1644EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-HUD-Transfer     08-04 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-Transfer,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>HUD Transfers NY Regional Official Under Investigation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The acting head of the Department of Housing
and Urban Development's New York regional office is being
transferred to agency headquarters pending the outcome of three
investigations of her conduct, a department official said Friday.
   Geraldine McGann was told to report to Washington effective
Monday and will be assigned to nonmanagerial duties in the
department's office of housing, said the official, who spoke on the
condition of anonymity.
   Housing Secretary Jack Kemp last month placed McGann on
administrative leave from her $68,500-a-year job because of
questions about her role in awarding federal subsidies to housing
in Island Park, a small beachfront village that is home to Sen.
Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y.
   McGann, who in addition to her HUD job served as a village
trustee, and other Island Park officials have been accused of
rigging the distribution of HUD-subsidized houses in the early
1980s, ensuring that they went to politically connected townspeople
instead of minorities, as the program intended.
   McGann's son purchased one of the houses although he did not
qualify under HUD guidelines, according to a 1984 investigation by
HUD's inspector general. A cousin of D'Amato's also bought one of
the houses, although the senator maintains that he played no role
and that the man was qualified.
   McGann has also been accused of voting on HUD-related matters
before the town board. She has denied casting such votes but the
former town clerk recently said he was ordered to alter minutes to
show McGann had abstained.
   Her conduct is being investigated by HUD's inspector general,
the U.S. attorney's office in New York and the Nassau County
district attorney. HUD general counsel Frank Keating wrote to U.S.
Attorney Andrew J. Maloney on Thursday asking for a quick
resolution of the investigation and information about its scope.
   ``We are anxious to resolve her status as an employee but
obviously cannot do so as long as your investigation is under
way,'' Keating said in the letter, a copy of which was obtained by
The Associated Press.
   Kemp last month prohibited HUD managers from serving on
government boards and said all HUD employees will be barred from
serving on government or other panels that could have HUD-related
dealings or benefit from agency programs.
   McGann was told she will be reassigned to Washington for up to
120 days, the official said. The department had to make the move
because it can put an employee on administrative leave for only 30
days. She is the highest-ranking HUD official to be affected in a
number of recent personnel moves related to the investigations of
abuse, influence-peddling and mismanagement.
   HUD has initiated the process of firing three former officials
at its Washington field office, including the office's former head,
because of alleged mismanagement. The head of the Richmond, Va.,
field office also was recently reassigned to nonmanagerial duties.
   As acting head of the New York regional office, McGann was
repsonsible for HUD programs and officials in New York, New Jersey
the U.S. Virgin Islands and Puerto Rico.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
