<DOCNO> AP890804-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 1716EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NavyDeath     08-04 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Navy Death,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Autopsy Fails to Solve Mysterious Death of Naval Trainee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Final autopsy results Friday failed to
explain the death of an aviation officer candidate from Wisconsin
during an abandon-ship drill in a training pool, a Navy spokesman
said.
   Michael Fedie, 22, of Altoona, Wis., died of ``a seizure
disorder of unknown cause accompanied by acute cerebral edema,''
said Cmdr. Dennis Hessler of the Naval Education and Training
Command, which has its headquarters at Pensacola Naval Air Station.
   ``The autopsy found no indication of trauma, pre-existing
disease or congenital abnormalities and no evidence of
hemorrhage,'' Hessler said. Although inconclusive, the autopsy was
still valuable because it did exclude those possible causes, he
said.
   Hessler also said the autopsy by the Armed Services Institute of
Pathology in Washington, D.C., did not change a preliminary finding
that no wrongdoing is indicated in the June 23 death.
   That was not the case in the death last year of another
Wisconsin trainee, also in a Pensacola training pool. Five enlisted
instructors were punished, including one sentenced to 90 days in
the brig for negligent homicide, and an officer was reprimanded for
the March 2, 1988, death of Airman Recruit Lee Mirecki, 19, of
Appleton, Wis.
   Mirecki was undergoing rescue-swimmer training when he panicked
during a strenuous rescue drill, climbed from the pool and shouted
that he was quitting. Court-martial testimony indicated he had an
unusual fear of being pushed under water and suffered heart failure
and drowned after instructors pushed him back in the pool and held
his head under water.
   The death of Fedie drew unusual attention because of the
previous Mirecki investigation, which was pressed by Mirecki's
congressman after complaints were raised by his family about the
Navy's handling of the case.
   Fedie died during a different type of drill, one in which
aviation trainees jump off a 12-foot tower and swim about 15 yards
under water while wearing their flight suits. Most sailors go
through similar drills during basic training.
   Fedie completed the exercise and was walking from the pool when
he collapsed back into shallow water, witnesses said. Medical
examiners said there was little doubt of a seizure, but they were
uncertain whether it was triggered by the central nervous or
cardiovascular systems, Hessler said.
</TEXT>
