<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Miners     08-04 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Miners,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Premier Says Mine Settlement Will Cost $3 Billion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's concessions to improve living and
working conditions for hundreds of thousands of coal miners will
cost more than $3 billion, Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov said Friday.
   Ryzhkov told official media that coming up with that sum will be
difficult for the financially strapped government, and cautioned
other workers not to expect the same concessions if they walk off
their jobs.
   The package of financial measures ``is not an easy one, and it
will require mobilization of the financial and material resources
of the country,'' Ryzhkov said in an interview on state-run
television.
   ``If we follow the road of strikes, no one will benefit from it,
and low-paid sections of the population will be hit first,'' the
official Tass news agency quoted him as saying. ``One should
understand that if others follow the miners' example, the country
may find itself in a most difficult situation.''
   The current package will cost 2 billion rubles ($3.2 billion).
Previous estimates of the cost of the package ranged up to 5
billion rubles ($8 billion.)
   Ryzhkov said the government had put together a series of
measures, many of which were submitted to the Supreme Soviet
legislature, which ended its first session Friday.
   The legislature presumably will be able to approve those
measures only when it resumes its work Sept. 25.
   Hundreds of thousands of miners in Siberia and the Ukraine
walked off their jobs in July in frustration over poor living and
working conditions.
   They returned to work after the government promised improvements.
   Miners of 17 mines in the Kuznetsk coal region of western
Siberia went on strike for two hours Thursday because they said the
government was not living up to its pledge to halt the operation of
a hydroelectric station they say is harming the environment.
</TEXT>
