<DOCNO> AP890804-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 2046EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan     08-04 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Candidates Running For Prime Minister</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two more politicians of the governing Liberal
Democratic Party declared their candidacies Friday in next week's
election to choose Japan's new prime minister, throwing open what
once looked like a walkover election.
   Former Welfare Minister Yoshiro Hayashi, 62, and former
Transport Minister Shintaro Ishihara, 56, a prominent author, said
they will seek the party presidency in Tuesday's balloting.
   Until Friday, former Education Minister Toshiki Kaifu, 58, had
been considered a shoo-in for the job.
   The party president is assured of becoming prime minister
because of the Liberal Democrats' large majority in the lower house
of Parliament, which selects the prime minister.
   The winner Tuesday will be Japan's third prime minister since
June.
   The party has been crippled by an unpopular new sales tax and
money and sex scandals. Noboru Takeshita was forced to resign in
June. Sousuke Uno announced he would resign after only two months
in office following July 23 elections in which the Liberal
Democrats lost their majority in the upper chamber for the first
time since the party's formation in 1955.
   ``Our party must reform itself radically and reform politics
with an eye toward the future,'' Hayashi told a news conference
late Friday. ``I am determined to devote myself entirely to the
task.''
   Ishihara also called for party reforms and said, ``Politics do
not exist for politicians, but for the country. If we leave the
situation as it is now, factionalism and power politics will
continue to prevail.''
   Uno asked party members on Friday to refrain from factionalism
in the presidential race.
   Half a dozen major factions in the party are separated more by
personal and financial allegiances than their conservative
political leanings.
   The large faction led by former Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa
decided on Friday to support Hayashi, who belongs to one of the
party's smallest groups.
   Seiichi Ohta, a leading member of the Miyazawa faction, branded
Kaifu's candidacy a product of back room deals involving large
factions.
   ``It will disappoint the public,'' he said.
   Analysts said Kaifu remains the front-runner because of strong
backing from factions led by former Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita
and former Foreign Minister Shintaro Abe.
   The party's popular No. 2 official, Ryutaro Hashimoto, 52,
formally declined to run Friday, saying his candidacy would further
split the party.
   Former Defense Agency head Ganri Yamashita, 68, had said he
would run, but had to drop out Friday when he failed to draw enough
support from party members to become a candidate. He said he and
his supporters would back Hayashi.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
