<FIRST>r i AM-Greece-Scandal     08-04 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece-Scandal,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee Proposes Charges Against Former Minister</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Parliament committee proposed Friday
that a minister of the former Socialist government be charged with
complicity in an agricultural fraud that cheated the European
Economic Community.
   The 12-member committee investigated whether Nikos
Athanassopoulos, former deputy finance minister, was involved in
the alleged forgery of harbor logs and customs invoices to show
that 9,000 tons of Yugoslav maize sold to the Community in 1986 was
from Greece, an EEC member.
   In May, the European Court issued a ruling against Greece,
citing lost revenues to the EEC of $1.16 million. The sentence is
expected to be announced later this year.
   Athanassios Tsaldaris, speaker of Parliament, said floor debate
on the committee's proposal would take place late this month.
   After inconclusive elections in June, communists and
conservatives formed a coalition government to prosecute those
involved in several financial scandals that arose during the
Socialist administration of former Premier Andreas Papandreou.
   They said the coalition probably would stay in office only about
three months.
   The committee report indicated Athanassopoulos had tried to
cover up for whoever was behind the scheme, which defrauded the EEC
of import duties on the maize and caused it to pay subsidies for
produce from a nonmember nation.
   All five Socialist members of committee voted against the
proposal, which was supported by the six members from the
conservative New Democracy party and the single deputy from the
Coalition of the Left and Progress, which is dominated by the
Communist party.
   New Democracy has claimed the $1.16 million obtained by the
state-run ITCO trading company in the fraud is missing. The
Socialist Party denies it.
</TEXT>
