<FIRST>u w AM-AntPoison     08-04 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ant Poison,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Bans Ant Killer as Danger to Children</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency on Friday
banned household ant killers containing the chemical sodium
arsenate because of the danger of small children ingesting the
compounds.
   The EPA said the chemical is used to kill ants that are merely a
nuisance and do not threaten human health, food crops or wood
structures.
   EPA spokesman Ed Heier said the product is a surgary liquid made
by several companies and sold under numerous brand names. He said
that because the purchaser normally applies the ant killer and
leaves it exposed, it is not child-proof.
   Most often, the EPA said, the compound is applied to carboard,
wax paper, bottle caps or food to attract ants.
   The EPA's Ronald McCallum, who wrote the order banning the
pesticide, said that manufacturers of such compounds have failed to
show ``that the benefits of continued use of open sodium arsenate
baits to control household ants justifies the risks to human health
associated with the baits, particularly the risk to small
children.''
   In other action, the EPA said it had reached agreement with the
International Paper Co. in a case involving violatios of federal
clean air requirements at the company's Androscoggin mill in Jay,
Maine.
   The settlement, part of a consent decree, calls for the company
to pay a $900,000 fine for air pollution and begin a program to
reduce emissions from the plant.
   The agreement involved federal and state environmental officials
and the paper company.
   The EPA also announced a proposed $253,200 fine against Monsanto
Co., for its failure to promptly report to the EPA test results on
a new chemical even though the tests indicated the chemical may
pose a risk to public health.
   The agency said the test results were provided the EPA five
years late.
   Monsanto may appeal the proposed fine and request a formal
hearing, officials said.
   The chemical is called Santogard PVI and is used in the
processing of natural and synthetic products.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
