<DOCNO> AP890804-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 2049EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DenverSymphony     08-04 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Denver Symphony,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Denver Symphony Will Play Sharply Reduced Season</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS M. SEARLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The financially plagued Denver Symphony Orchestra
is making plans to play this season after all, thanks to a survival
plan approved Friday that includes shortening the season by half
and cutting musicians' salaries.
   The final two months of last season were canceled because of
lack of money, and observers had thought the odds were good the
upcoming season would be canceled outright.
   Terms of the plan approved by the orchestra's board include
negotiating pay cuts and concessions from its 81 musicians,
cutbacks in staff and operating costs, and winning writeoffs of
$3.2 million of the symphony's $4 million debt.
   The 1989-90 symphony season, which usually lasts 41 weeks and
begins in September, was pruned to 21 weeks and will begin Jan. 21,
1990. The board approved a $3.5 million budget for the limited
season, down from last season's $7.3 million.
   ``Although we regret the need to shorten the season, we feel
this is the financially prudent way to proceed,'' said Denver
Symphony Association Board Chairman John Low.
   He said that the season could still be canceled if the
orchestra's creditors refuse to forgive the debts.
   ``I want to emphasize I am optimistic about getting that debt
forgiven,'' he said. But if the goal of $3.2 million in forgiven
debts is not reached, he said, ``we're going to have to look very
hard at what that does to our ability to proceed.''
   Among the debts is $700,000 owed to the city for back rent for
Boettcher Hall. Some city council members have said they would
oppose any debt forgiveness.
   Earlier in the summer, the board rejected a proposed 27-week
season that was to have begun in November, citing the unresolved $4
million debt and the fact that musicians had not agreed to contract
concessions.
   Earlier this week, the symphony notified its musicians that
their health and dental benefits were canceled, saving the
association about $30,000 a month. Three years ago the musicians
agreed to 20 percent pay cuts to keep the symphony solvent.
   The symphony's financial problems have been blamed on Denver's
recession, the city's 10 percent seat tax, continual turnover in
management and the $600,000-a-month cash flow needed to operate the
symphony.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
