<DOCNO> AP890804-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 1830EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NYCCorruption     08-04 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NYC Corruption,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>As Mayoral Primary Approaches, Former Mayoral Aide Indicted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just weeks before the mayoral primary, a former
top aide to Mayor Edward I. Koch has been indicted on charges he
lied when he denied that a city agency he ran was really a
patronage mill, a prosecutor said Friday.
   Joseph DeVincenzo, 46, indicted on 11 counts of perjury, ran the
city's Talent Bank, set up ostensibly to recruit women and
minorities to fill city posts. Critics said the agency was really
used to handle patronage requests, and doled out the highest paying
jobs to whites.
   The indictment said DeVincenzo lied when he told the State
Commission on Government Integrity at a public hearing that
politically connected job applicants were not given preference for
city government posts. Other witnesses contradicted this.
   Assistant District Attorney Michael Cherkasky, who announced the
indictment, noted at a news conference that patronage is not
illegal and said there was no underlying crime in the case.
   But he said the grand jury found that DeVincenzo committed
perjury by lying to cover up his patronage dealings at commission
hearings on July 13 and 21 last year and Jan. 11 this year.
   The indictment was filed Thursday, Cherkasky said. DeVincenzo
pleaded innocent at his arraignment and was released on his own
recognizance. A hearing was scheduled for Aug. 11.
   The indictment comes less than six weeks before the primary
election in which Koch is seeking the Democratic nomination for an
unprecedented fourth term. His opponents sought to capitalize on
the indictment but Koch declared: ``I don't think it does anything
to my campaign. There's nothing to hide here.''
   The Koch administration has been shaken by several scandals,
particularly since his election to a third term in November 1985.
Six of the mayor's appointees have been jailed and about 200
lower-level city employees have been convicted of various crimes.
   The scandals have ranged from the serious _ kickbacks from
collection agencies hired by the Parking Violations Bureau _ to the
trivial _ the chef at the mayoral Gracie Mansion used city
equipment for his catering business. Bess Myerson, a city
commissioner, was acquitted of charges she tried to fix her
boyfriend's divorce case.
   Speaking about the Job Bank case, Koch said Friday that compared
with patronage at the state capital in Albany and in Washington,
the use of patronage in his administration ``is piddling and
legal.''
   But Koch said lying to the commission is ``simply unacceptable''
and that he would have counseled DeVincenzo to tell the truth.
   Some witnesses testified to the commission that files at the
Talent Bank were sometimes marked with color codes, indicating a
political sponsor might have referred an applicant to DeVincenzo.
   His own assistant, James G. Hein, testified that DeVincenzo had
ordered him in February 1986 to ``cleanse'' the computer and paper
employment files of ``any references to political figures.''
   Six month ago, Koch announced that he had asked for DeVincenzo's
resignation. But DeVincenzo had already filed papers to resign,
ensuring his pension of $52,000 a year.
   District Attorney Robert Morgenthau, reached by telephone in
Massachusetts, said his office did consider the timing of the
indictment, so close to the election, but conlcuded that ``we could
not be in the role of censor, deciding what the public could and
could not hear.''
   First-degree perjury is punishable by a maximum of seven years
in prison.
</TEXT>
