<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 1750EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Cyprus-Mosaics     08-04 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cyprus-Mosaics,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cypriot Archbishop Hails U.S. Decision on Looted Treasures</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Chrysostomos one name is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop Chrysostomos of Cyprus on
Friday hailed a U.S. court decision restoring looted mosaics to his
church as opening the way for the recovery of stolen archaelogical
treasures worldwide.
   ``We are overjoyed by the decision of the American court,'' said
Chrysostomos, head of the Greek Orthodox church in Cyprus.
   ``This encourages us to seek the recovery of other looted
treasures because it will discourage international art merchants
who deal in such stolen property,'' he said in an interview.
   U.S. District Judge James E. Noland in Indiana ruled Thursday
that four 6th-century mosaics purchased by an Indianapolis art
dealer were the property of the Cyprus church and should be
returned to it.
   But attorneys for both sides were unable to reach an agreement
on when the artwork would be released, and they were back before
Noland in Indianapolis late Friday afternoon.
   In his ruling Thursday, Noland said dealer Peg Goldberg never
obtained title to the mosaics, which she bought last summer in
Switzerland.
   The ruling did not address damages, custody or transfer of the
mosaics, which remained locked in an Indianapolis vault while
attorneys negotiated for their release.
   The mosaics depict the Virgin Mary, Jesus Christ and the
apostles. They were removed from the walls of the church of The
Virgin of Kanakaria in the village of Lythrangomi in north Cyprus,
which has been under Turkish occupation since 1974.
   Ms. Goldberg, of suburban Indianapolis, bought the mosaics from
a Turkish middleman, Aydin Dikmen, for $1.1 million and offered
them for sale to the Paul Getty Museum in California for $20
million.
   The Cyprus government has accused Turkish authorities and the
breakaway Turkish Cypriot state in north Cyprus of allowing the
systematic looting of churches and rich archaelogical sites to
eradicate the Christian and Greek cultural heritage of the island,
going back more than three thousand years.
   The Cyprus church and the Cyprus government sued for the
recovery of the mosaics when informed by the Getty museum of the
development.
   The Indiana court decision had been awaited eagerly by
international art circles as a precedent for the recovery of looted
artifacts worldwide.
   ``On the basis of this decision we shall now proceed to demand
the return of numerous other ecclesiastical treasures looted from
churches and monasteries in the Turkish-occupied region,''
Chrysostomos said.
   Cyprus has been unofficially partitioned since a Turkish
invasion in 1974. The breakaway state established in north Cyprus
in 1985, which is only recognized by Turkey, argued unsuccessfully
in the Indiana court that the mosaics should be returned to it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
