<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 1831EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HomelessAlderman     08-04 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Homeless Alderman,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alderman Tries Life on the Streets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A city alderman who left behind his
wallet and his Cadillac to spend five days on the streets said he's
gained a new perspective on what it's like to be homeless.
   ``It was a good experience for me,'' Michael Wooden, 39, said on
his return Thursday to his job as senior spokesman for Humana Inc.,
the giant hospital company. ``I learned a lot.''
   Wooden began his adventure Saturday, when he set off with a
quarter in his pocket and a change of socks and underwear in a gym
bag. Calling himself Mike Wayne, he told people he was passing
through town, out of work and looking for a job and a place to
sleep.
   After a night on a bench at a downtown plaza, Wooden found his
way to a shelter _ and began to enjoy himself, he said.
   He was ``adopted'' by a man named Frank, who, along with Wooden,
was staying at the Wayside Christian Mission downtown.
   Frank showed Wooden how to panhandle. The alderman said he
didn't feel very comfortable asking people for spare change; most
ignored him or mumbled that they didn't have change.
   Wooden said that by Wednesday he fit in with the men at the
shelter. That afternoon, a group of them sat on a corner, laughing.
The other men were drinking, and Wooden smoked cigars he bought
after selling his blood for $15.
   ``We had the best time,'' he said. ``I like to meet people. So I
found that part of this adventure fun and exciting.
   ``They've all got serious problems,'' Wooden said. ``But they're
making the best of a bad situation, and some of them are managing
to have fun and laugh and joke.''
   Wooden had planned to stay on the streets a week, but said that
by Wednesday he'd done what he set out to do: ``meeting some of the
people, knowing what kind of services were available and really
living the life.''
   The alderman said he might not have time to introduce ordinances
or otherwise help the homeless during the six months left in his
term, but plans to ask workers in missions and shelters what the
Board of Aldermen can do for Louisville's estimated 1,200 homeless.
He said he might volunteer his own time.
   Wooden said that as he drove to work Thursday, he spotted some
of the men he'd gotten to know at the shelter.
   ``For the first time, I can see them as real human beings with
feelings and families,'' he said.
</TEXT>
