<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-04 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Around Great Lakes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms carrying heavy rain developed Friday around the
Great Lakes and the Upper Midwest, and one stream flooded near
Chicago.
   Lower Michigan got the heaviest rain from showers and
thunderstorms associated with the remnants of Hurricane Chantal.
Tuscola County, in the ``thumb'' of the mitten-shaped state, got
over 3{ inches in over four hours, the National Weather Service
said. In west-central Lower Michigan, Grant got 5 inches of rain in
the morning and Sparta reported 4{ inches.
   In the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT, 1.44 inches of rain fell at
Muskegon, Mich., and in Wisconsin 1.45 inches fell at Milwaukee.
   More thunderstorms associated with Chantal developed from
southeastern Ontario across Lake Erie into northeastern Ohio.
   Heavy rain that moved through the Chicago area early in the
morning made Salt Creek rise 4 feet above flood stage and caused
flooding in the northwest suburb of Rolling Meadows, the weather
service said.
   Thunderstorms also developed in very unstable, humid air over
southern Minnesota. These storms formed ahead of a cold front that
was pushing through the upper Mississippi Valley and the central
Plains.
   Elsewhere, thunderstorms with a potential for heavy downpours
developed in very humid air over southern Arizona.
   Out in the open Atlantic, Hurricane Dean was 210 miles northeast
of San Juan, Puerto Rico, moving slowly towards the north.
   A large upper-level high pressure system anchored over the
southern half of the nation produced warm weather across much of
the nation. Temperatures rose into the 90s from the middle and
southern Atlantic Coast across the Ohio and Mississippi valleys to
the central and southern Plains, where northern Kansas climbed
above 100.
   Around the Great Lakes, Marquette, Mich., hit a record high of
90 and Duluth, Minn., tied its record of 92.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 59
degrees at Everett, Wash., to 105 at Hill City, Kan. Friday's low
in the Lower 48 states was 35 at Truckee, Calif.
   For Saturday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from the upper and middle Mississippi Valley across the Great Lakes
and the upper Ohio Valley to the northern and middle Atlantic
Coast. Scattered thunderstorms also were forecast over the Florida
Peninsula.
   Highs in the 70s were predicted along the Pacific Coast, over
northern Maine, and from eastern Montana across North Dakota into
Upper Michigan; in the 80s from the Pacific Northwest across the
northern and central Rockies, South Dakota and Nebraska, much of
the Great Lakes and upper Ohio Valley into New England; above 100
across southwestern Texas, the desert Southwest and inland valleys
of California; and in the 90s over much of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
