<FIRST>r a AM-TroubledMayor     08-04 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Troubled Mayor,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Embattled Bradley Weeks Late in Providing Financial Statements, Paper
Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Tom Bradley has missed a deadline to
correct what state officials said were four years' worth of
omissions in his financial disclosure statements, according to a
published report.
   The state Fair Political Practices Commission told the mayor,
whose financial dealings are under investigation by state, local
and federal officials, in a June 23 letter to provide the
information within 20 days, the Los Angeles Herald Examiner
reported Friday.
   Among the information requested were exact dates and details
involving stock transactions with which the five-term mayor was
involved.
   The commission first asked Bradley to amend his financial
disclosure forms in May.
   ``They keep saying soon,'' commission spokeswoman Sandra
Michioku said of the delay by Bradley's people.
   Mark Fabiani, one of Bradley's attorneys, said amending the
financial statements has taken longer than was expected. He said
the commission would have the forms by next Friday.
   ``We have simply been trying to reconstruct the last four years
of the mayor's financial life, and that has involved a search for
original source material, including account and bank statements,''
Fabiani said.
   Bradley has scheduled a meeting of close political advisers
Saturday at his Hancock Park home to discuss the mounting legal
bills he faces as a result of the various probes.
   Fabiani said the group would look into ways of raising money for
the newly formed Bradley Officeholder Committee, which could use
the funds it collects to pay Bradley's legal bills.
