<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 2037EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Turtles-Shrimpers     08-04 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turtles-Shrimpers,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Proposed Temporary Regulations Completed by Mosbacher</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shrimpers could abandon turtle excluder
devices in favor of limited trawls to keep endangered sea turtles
from drowning in their nets under proposed temporary Commerce
Department regulations completed Friday and scheduled to take
effect Tuesday.
   Department spokesman Reed Boatright said Secretary Robert A.
Mosbacher finished the proposal Friday and would submit the plan
limiting trawl times to 105 minutes to U.S. District Court Judge
Thomas Hogan on Monday.
   In a court hearing Thursday, Hogan gave Mosbacher until Monday
to draft a plan to protect endangered sea turtles from becoming
entangled in shrimpers' nets.
   Environmentalists, however, said Friday that the Kemp's ridley
sea turtle faces quick extinction if the government abandons turtle
excluder devices in favor of limited shrimp-fishing trawl times.
   The Center for Marine Conservation and other organizations want
Mosbacher to require shrimpers to use turtle excluder devices.
Shrimpers, however, say the devices reduce their catch and threaten
their livelihood.
   The center's Marydele Donnelly said limited trawl times
``condemn the Kemp's ridley sea turtle to extinction within this
century.''
   ``A major confrontation looms ahead on sea turtle protection,''
Ms. Donnelly said. ``Secretary Mosbacher needs to move swiftly to
enforce federal environmental laws protecting endangered species.
Restricted tow times, unlike TEDs, will hasten the day when sea
turtles will no longer exist in American waters.''
   Uhder Mosbacher's proposal, shrimpers would have about 7{
minutes to get their nets in, and 7{ minutes to get them out, with
actual trawl time limited to 90 minutes, Boatright said.
   While the Commerce Department contends that sea turtles can
survive submerged for 90 minutes, conservationists argue limited
trawl times are ineffective in reducing turtle mortality and cannot
be enforced.
   The center said the government's most recent analysis found that
one in four sea turtles will drown during a tow time of 105 minutes.
   It said gulf shrimpers normally leave their nets in the water
for two to 10 hours.
   Mosbacher suspended enforcement of the turtle excluder device
regulations July 24 after shrimpers protested the law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
