<FIRST>r i AM-Argentina-Texaco     08-04 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina-Texaco,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texaco Returns To Argentina After 36-Year Absence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Texaco oil company signed an
agreement with the government Friday to explore and possibly
develop deposits as part of an investment that could total several
hundred million dollars.
   The initial investment calls for $25 million over five years to
search for oil in fields located near Argentina's hot, dry northern
border with Paraguay. The company also reportedly wants to buy
about 250 gas stations.
   Company vice president Robert Black said Texaco eventually might
invest ``hundreds of millions of dollars'' in the South American
nation.
   Texaco Inc. helped develop Argentina's reserves after oil was
discovered accidentally in southern Chubut Province in 1907.
   The company left the country in 1953 when profits dropped,
government regulation increased and the state oil company YPF took
greater control of the petroleum program.
   President Carlos Menem, who took office July 8, has announced
that he wants to sell off inefficient state industries and attract
foreign investment.
   YPF is projected to lose $1 billion this year.
</TEXT>
