<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 2116EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-OldNewspapers     08-04 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Old Newspapers,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>At British Auction, American Civil War Newspapers Hottest Sellers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American newspapers that recorded events from the
Civil War were the hottest sellers Friday at an auction of old
newspapers, the auctioneers Bonhams said.
   The newspapers were sold by an anonymous English collector who
said his family was ``being driven bananas by all my newspapers all
over the house,'' but that he was so avid he was keeping newspapers
mentioning the auction.
   About 300 newspapers were sold for a total of about $5,000, said
auctioneer Duncan Chilcott.
   ``The trend from the sale would suggest that there's a great
market for 17th century and 18th century newspapers and an even
better market for American newspapers,'' Chilcott said.
   ``American newspapers describing the Civil War, they were most
eagerly sought after, they were the ones we had the most
competition for from the bidders,'' he said.
   The oldest newspaper in the sale, The Perfect Diurnall, of Aug.
28, 1648, fetched the highest price, about $246.
   The newspaper, which reported Oliver Cromwell's new model army
capturing the town of Colchester, was produced by Parliament and
was principally a record of parliamentary debates.
   The older newspapers were generally in better condition because
the quality of modern paper is such that a newspaper exposed to
light can turn yellow within a week.
   The most modern newspapers for sale _ recording the Falklands
War and the wedding of Prince Charles and Diana _ didn't sell,
Chilcott said.
</TEXT>
