<FIRST>u i AM-CentralAmerica 1stLd-Writethru a0696 08-04 0750</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Central America, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0696,0768</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sandinistas, Opposition Agree Contras Should be Disbanded</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 4th pvs, `Ortega talked...' ito UPDATE
with Contra reaction; picks up 5th pvs, `In the...' with minor editing
to TRIM.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MGA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega signed an
accord with opposition leaders Friday urging that the Contra rebels
be disbanded, and he said he would press for the breakup at a
summit of Central American leaders.
   ``I hope the U.S. government will respect this sovereign
decision of the Nicaraguan people and change U.S. policy toward
Nicaragua, and that it puts an end to the (1985) economic
embargo,'' Ortega said before leaving for the weekend conference in
Tela, Honduras.
   The United States wants the rebels to stay organized until after
Nicaragua holds general elections next year.
   Ortega talked to reporters shortly after he signed the
agreement, worked out during 22 hours of talks between the leftist
Sandinista government and leaders from 20 opposition parties.
   Contra spokesman Bosco Matamoros said in Washington that the
rebels support the same principles that were laid out in Friday's
agreement, adding: ``We are not opposed to the question of
reintegrating ourselves into Nicaragua under democratic conditions.
But those conditions have to be negotiated.''
   In the accord, the Sandinistas pledge to hold free and fair
elections Feb. 25, without any restraints on campaigning or news
censorship. They promise to suspend the military draft from
September until after the balloting to prevent it from interfering
with electoral activity.
   The Sandinistas initiated the negotiations to defuse complaints
by opposition leaders that their candidates were harassed in
earlier elections, their movements constrained and their exposure
to the public restricted by news censorship.
   The presidents of Honduras, El Salvador, Costa Rica and
Guatemala will join Ortega in Tela.
   Adolfo Calero, a member of the rebel political directorate,
already has expressed his determination to keep the Contras
operating.
   Opposition leaders told reporters they were generally satisfied
with Friday's agreement, even though it was not all they wanted.
   ``No country, however powerful, has the right to interfere in
the Nicaraguan electoral process,'' Jaime Bonilla of the
Independent Liberal Party said, speaking for a coalition of 14 of
the 20 parties.
   ``Even though the opposition is not completely satisfied, the
electoral process is being channeled toward what the opposition
wants. The accord reflects the common will to contribute toward the
peace process at the summit.''
   The Tela summit Saturday and Sunday will be the fifth held under
a peace plan that President Oscar Arias of Costa Rica drafted in
August 1987 to negotiate an end to Nicaragua's civil war and
leftist insurrections in El Salvador and Guatemala.
   The focus will be on Nicaragua and the 12,000 Contras, now
living with their dependents in base camps in southern Honduras.
   The United States provided the Contras with military aid until a
year ago. It now sends them only non-lethal aid such as clothing
and food.
   President Jose Azcona Hoyo of Honduras says the Contras are an
economic burden and that he wants them out of his country.
   Ortega said he hoped ``the Honduran government feels stronger
now to push for the demobilization of the Contras in Honduran
territory.''
   Friday's accord also calls for undercover activities to halt
during Nicaragua's electoral process. The Sandinistas also promise
to grant unconditional amnesty to all political prisoners, a move
that will benefit 1,605 rebels in Nicaraguan jails.
   The United States began supporting the Contras in 1982 and
declared an economic embargo on Nicaragua three years later,
arguing that Sandinista efforts to impose a leftist government and
the Sandinistas' close military ties with Moscow and Havana
threatened security in Central America.
   The Bush administration supports the Arias peace plan but says
the Contras should not be disbanded until after the elections.
Bernard Aronson, assistant secretary of state for inter-American
affairs, visited Guatemala this week to press that point.
   A senior State Department official in Washington, briefing
reporters on the Aronson trip on condition of anonymity, cited
complaints that the Sandinista government is mounting raids on
suspected Contra sympathizers in northern Nicaragua and failed to
create fair conditions for political opponents.
   The Contras' Calero said he was ``elated that President Bush has
come out unequivocally in favor of having the resistance remain as
a viable force.''
   He said the process of democratization in Nicaragua remain only
promises by the Sandinista government, adding, ``You do not take
down the scaffold before the building is finished.''
</TEXT>
