<FIRST>r a AM-InfotechSuit     08-04 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Infotech Suit,0374</SECOND>
<HEAD>Infotechnology Executives Sued Over Stock Transactions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman and directors of Infotechnology
Inc., which controls United Press International, have been accused
in a civil lawsuit of making illegal stock transactions to ward off
possible takeover bids.
   Infotechnology said Friday that it had not yet reviewed the
complaint, but ``there was no basis whatsover for claims''
contained in a news release which announced the filing of the
lawsuit.
   The accusations were made Thursday in a lawsuit filed in
Delaware Chancery Court by Avacus Partners LP, which owns 7.8
percent of Infotechnology stock and indicated in March it might
launch a takeover bid.
   Avacus said Chairman Earl Brian engineered stock transactions
involving Infotechnology and two other companies it controls in an
effort to frustrate takeover interest in Infotechnology and
entrench current management.
   It said Infotechnology received inadequate consideration in the
deals, and that the transactions enabled Brian and his allies to
boost their interest in the company to 32 percent from 13 percent.
   In addition to Brian, the lawsuit named Infotechnologies' four
other directors as defendants.
   The lawsuit asked that the court rescind the stock transactions
in question and place Infotechnology under control of a receiver.
   ``Infotech is confident that the lawsuit is entirely without
merit,'' Friday's statement read.
   The lawsuit stated that Infotechnology agreed in late February
to issue 1.5 million shares of its common stock valued at $16.15
million in exchange for the stock of WNW Group Inc., a privately
held company set up and managed by Brian.
   WNW's main assets are the right to control UPI wire service,
which has not been profitable in the last decade and continues to
report losses since emerging from bankruptcy law protection in 1986.
   Avacus said Brian had obtained those assets for WNW a year
earlier for $110,000, and noted that Infotechnology paid 150 times
the price he paid the previous year.
   The lawsuit also said Brian had Infotech provide unspecified
millions of dollars in loans to underwrite UPI's losses in 1988 and
1989.
   Avacus Partners is based in Washington and consists of several
limited partners, the largest of which is the Dutch investment firm
Reiss &amp; Co.
</TEXT>
