<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 2117EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Cuba-Drugs     08-04 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuba-Drugs,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuban Government Releases Evidence in Drug Scandal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuba has released its first report of the
evidence against high-ranking military officials who were executed
or imprisoned for dealing in drugs, the Mexican government news
agency said Friday.
   In a dispatch from Havana, the Notimex agency said the evidence
was published in a 480-page book called ``Case 1-89, the End of the
Cuban Connection.''
   It did not describe the contents. Although parts of the trials
and appeals were televised, the evidence was kept secret.
   ``Case 1-89'' includes court records and other materials from
the military trials that resulted in four executions and the
imprisonment of 10 officers, the report said.
   Cuba's government publishing company said the book was intended
to counter what it described as a U.S. disinformation campaign
linking the prosecutions to an alleged crackdown on political
dissidents, Notimex reported.
   Notimex quoted Felix Sautie, head of the publishing company, as
saying: ``The revelations were made so that the foreign reader can
interpret the facts with precise information about the legal
procedures followed in the military trial.''
   The scandal embarrassed President Fidel Castro, who had said for
years that U.S. accusations of drug trafficking by Cuban officials
were propaganda.
   Four officers, including a highly decorated general, were
executed for their roles in the ring, which the government said
also dealt in diamonds, furs, rare woods and other contraband.
   Several officials, including the interior minister, were
dismissed for failing to detect or prevent the smuggling.
</TEXT>
