<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-Mafia     08-04 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Mafia,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Say Head of Camorra Crime Organization Arrested</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN LEHMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man identified by authorities as the
``supreme boss'' of the Naples-based Camorra crime organization has
been arrested and charged with drug trafficking, federal police
announced Friday.
   Marco Antonio Veronezzi, the head of federal police in Sao
Paulo, told reporters that Francesco Toscanino ``coordinated, from
Brazil, the Camorra's distribution of cocaine and heroin to Europe
and the United States.'' The Camorra in Naples, Italy, is similar
to the Mafia elsewhere.
   Veronezzi said Toscanino, 54, has been in Brazil since 1986 and
directed a drug smuggling network with branches in the United
States, Mexico, Peru, Argentina, France, Italy, Thailand and Canada.
   Working with information supplied by Italian authorities,
federal police determined that Toscanino had a luxurious house in
the city of Jundiai, 37 miles north of Sao Paulo, according to
Veronezzi.
   He said that in a search of the house police confiscated $41,000
in U.S. currency and Italian bank certificates worth the equivalent
of $350,000.
   On July 19, three Italian police agents arrived with documents
and photographs ``for the positive identification of Toscanino''
and the suspect was arrested Wednesday at his seaside residence in
Guaruja, 47 miles south of Sao Paulo, Veronezzi said.
   He said Toscanino claimed he was a real estate broker and denied
any knowledge of the Camorra.
   Italy has requested Toscanino's extradition but if convicted in
Brazil he might have to serve up to 10 years in prison before he
could be sent back to Italy.
   Toscanino has been charged here with illegal entry and the use
of false documents along with drug trafficking. He is being held in
a cell at federal police headquarters in Sao Paulo.
   Veronezzi said Toscanino was arrested in Brazil in 1973 and
extradited to the United States where he was convicted of drug
trafficking and served 11 years of a 20-year sentence.
   Toscanino re-entered Brazil illegally in 1986 and began
``commanding the Camorro's drug distribution network from his
mansion in Jundiai,'' Veronezzi said.
   He told reporters he did not know why Toscanino decided to
establish his headquarters in Brazil.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890804-0099 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 2119EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Peru     08-04 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Kill Guard On Peruvian Train; Mother Teresa Asks For Peace</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven gunmen believed to be Shining Path
guerrillas mingled with passengers boarding a train and killed a
police guard after the train was under way, authorities said Friday.
   The attack occurred on Thursday, 155 miles east of the capital
city of Lima on the rail line that connects Lima with the Andean
city of Huancavelica, according to the government newspaper La
Cronica.
   Since 1980, Peru has been bled by the leftist insurgency of the
Mao-inspired Shining Path. The government says more than 15,000
people have died in the fighting.
   Nobel laureate Mother Teresa of Calcutta, who is in Lima
attending a religious conference on poverty and violence, pleaded
with people to forgive and pray for those who take up arms ``that
they realize their profound error and the injury they cause
others.''
   ``Begin with forgiveness, because when you forgive there is
peace, love and happiness,'' she told reporters at a news
conference Thursday.
   The report on the train attack said the seven rebels boarded the
train in Huancavelica, concealing their weapons and mixing with the
passengers. When the train entered a tunnel 15 miles from Huancayo,
the seven went to the first car of the train and shot the guard,
identified as Victor Serpa, sergeant in Peru's security police
force.
   They then went to the locomotive and forced the engineer to stop
the train. They tied up the engineer and fled into the countryside,
the report said.
   Peru's Central Railroad line is the world's highest normal gauge
railroad, rising to more than 13,000 feet from Lima on the coast.
It is a popular scenic route with tourists. It also is an important
link between Lima and the rich farming and mining areas of the
sierra. The Shining Path frequently targets the line as part of its
strategy to cut the capital off from the rest of Peru.
   Two weeks ago the rebels dynamited the tracks under a train
carrying copper ore, derailing all 18 cars.
   The Shining Path began its insurgency near Ayacucho, 235 miles
southeast of Lima. The violence has spread through most of the
Andean highlands, parts of the Pacific coastline and into the
coca-producing jungles of the northeast.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
