<FIRST>r a AM-SickTwins     08-04 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sick Twins,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Girls With Rare Blood Disease Lose Chance For Operation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG TUCKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twin girls suffering from a rare blood
disease lost a chance at the transplants they desperately need when
their insurance company went bankrupt, and their family is
struggling to raise money for the surgery.
   If the $60,000 needed for bone marrow transplants can't be
raised in a few weeks, 5-year-old Anna Marie and Mary Beth Heinz
will be hooked up to transfusion needles eight hours a day, five
days a week, said their uncle, Andy Willoughby.
   ``These kids have gone through so much already,'' Willoughby
said Friday.
   The girls, who suffer from congenital anemia and cannot produce
enough red blood cells, have already undergone 72 transfusions,
which are causing spleen and liver damage.
   The twins' older brother and sister have tissues that match
perfectly with their sisters', and an operation was set for July 5
at the University of Nebraska Medical Center at Omaha.
   But on July 3, the family's insurance company, Amalgamated Labor
Life Insurance Co., went bankrupt. The hospital would not admit the
twins without insurance.
   ``They urgently need to have something done,'' said the twins'
doctor, who asked that her name not be used.
   The girls' father, Dan Heinz, had lost his job as a meat cutter,
and was working two jobs _ delivering newspapers and hauling trash
_ to pay insurance premiums.
   ``Last winter he went into the country and chopped wood to save
money on heating bills,'' Willoughby said. ``Basically, he's been
working 16-hour days for five years. In all that time, I don't
think he's taken more than five days off.''
   After Amalgamated Labor Life went bankrupt, the Missouri Life
and Health Insurance Guaranty Association said it would provide up
to $100,000 for each girl's operation.
   The medical center said it would admit the girls and begin the
operation, but only if it was guaranteed payment of $130,000 per
child.
   The insurance money is available only through September, meaning
the family will have to raise the $60,000 and have the transplants
performed before the end of next month.
   The family has raised about $23,000 by Thursday, Willoughby said.
   ``The real time pressure is that we need to get the girls in the
hospital immediately,'' he said. ``If the transplants are
successful, then the girls will be able to manufacture their own
red blood cells, and they should have a healthy, normal life ahead
of them.''
   The cost of the transplants will go far beyond $130,000 per
child, Willoughby said.
   ``Dan said the other day that he knows he is financially ruined
no matter what happens,'' Willoughby said. ``He told me, `I'm done
for the rest of my life. It would be like paying for a car or a
house as long as you live. But it would be worth it.'''
</TEXT>
