<FIRST>r i AM-SovietSoldiersUnion     08-04 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Soldiers Union,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet, Hungarian Soldiers Planning To Set Up Draftees' Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet and Hungarian draftees plan
to set up a trade union within the military and asked the Dutch
Conscript Association for guidance, the founder of the Dutch union,
Loebas Oosterbeek, said Friday.
   Oosterbeek said Soviet and Hungarian delegations met with his
union on the fringes of last week's European Conference of
Conscript Organizations in Helsinki, Finland, which they were
attending for the first time.
   Founded in 1966, the Dutch group is the oldest of its kind in
Europe. It won Dutch soldiers the right to wear long hair, go home
after hours and work a 38-hour week.
   According to Oosterbeek, the East bloc delegates asked Dutch
union officials dozens of questions about how they ran their
organization, which he said has served as an example for several
draftees' groups in Europe.
   The delegates plans were afoot to set up similar unions of their
own in line with the political and economic reforms initiated by
Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev, Oosterbeek said.
   The Soviet delegation at Helsinki consisted of a 19-year-old
conscripted army sergeant; a 21-year-old cadet of the Frunze
Military Academy in Moscow, and an official of the state-controlled
Committee for the Defense of Peace who Osterbeek said was sent
along as a security agent.
   Two army privates represented Hungary, and Osterbeek quoted them
as saying that Hungary will form a conscript organization within a
year.
   There was no immediate word whether the new draftees' unions
would have official status.
   According to the London-based International Institute for
Strategic Studies, the Soviet Union's armed forces amount to 5.1
million soldiers on active duty and 6.2 million reservists, but
there are no estimates on how many of those are conscripts serving
a two-year stint.
   The Netherlands' 45,000 draftees serve from 16 to 18 months, and
their union claims a membership of 14,000.
</TEXT>
