<FIRST>r a AM-MurderMystery     08-04 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Murder Mystery,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guests for Murder Mystery Weekend End Up Crime Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANK BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mystery fans expecting to help solve a mock
murder at a seacoast restaurant this weekend now have to untangle a
real crime: who took the money that was supposed to pay for the
weekend fun.
   A woman posing as the organizer of the mystery weekend put out a
brochure advertising the fake murder and got people to pay up to
$500 for rooms, meals and the staged mystery, the attorney
general's office says.
   Luka's Greenhouse Restaurant in Hampton Falls never scheduled
the event because the woman failed to make a down payment on a
room, said Attorney General John Arnold. He is urging people who
paid for the weekend to notify his office.
   Mock murders are a relatively recent phenomenon. People pay
hundreds of dollars to take a cruise, stay at a hotel or ride a
train where a fake crime takes place. They are given certain clues
by the mystery organizers and then have to solve the puzzle,
usually a murder, using only the clues and their ingenuity.
   The management at Luka's is trying to come up with some clues to
the whereabouts of ``Maria,'' who told the restaurant she wanted to
rent a room for a murder mystery.
   Tracy Foster-Hill, functions sales manager at Luka's, said she
talked to the woman several times.
   The woman never gave her last name, Foster-Hill said, but left a
telephone number for a Beverly, Mass., residence. She said Maria
was told she would have to send in a deposit before the room could
be reserved for her, and she never did.
   ``I called her a few times and told her we had to have the money
before we could give her a room,'' Foster-Hill said. ``She kept
saying she wouldn't send any money until we sent her a menu so she
could see our food selection. We sent her at least four menus but
never got any money.''
   Foster-Hill said the last time she called the Beverly number,
about three weeks ago, the line was disconnected.
   Assistant Attorney General Donald Feith said he has talked to
three people, all from out of state, who mailed checks to a post
office box in Plaistow and received confirmation letters for the
mystery weekend.
   Feith said the Plaistow Post Office has told him no one has been
checking the box lately and that, when it was opened by
authorities, it was empty.
   Feith said the people he has spoken with don't seem to realize
that the mystery weekend is off and won't be held at a later date.
   ``Our fear is that Luka's will be visited by a number of people
this weekend expecting to see some kind of show,'' Feith said. ``We
expect to be pretty busy with calls from the people on Monday or
Tuesday.''
   Foster-Hill said a man called Luka's last week to find out where
he was staying for the weekend and was told there would be no mock
murder.
   ``He wasn't too happy,'' Foster-Hill said.
   Foster-Hill also said she was contacted recently by a hotel in
Gloucester, Mass., that had paid $600 to advertise in Maria's
mystery brochure.
</TEXT>
