<FIRST>r a AM-MissingToes     08-04 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missing Toes,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Refuses To Order Exhumation in Preserved Toe Mystery</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents may be offensive to some readers.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER MATTIACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANA, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge refused Friday to let state police
exhume a teen-age boy's body in their search for the source of six
toes found preserved in the home of a man apparently obsessed with
feet.
   ``So many people would like to know what happened,'' said
Jefferson County District Attorney A. Ted Hudock.
   State police found two big toes, two middle toes and two little
toes in a glass jar when they searched the mobile home where farm
worker John Reed, 57, lived alone outside Brookville, nearly 40
miles north of this western Pennsylvania county seat, authorities
said.
   Trooper Franklin Duddy said Reed told him he cut one toe from
the body of Brian Joseph Pearce, 15, of Rossiter at a funeral home
in the Brookville area. The boy was killed in a 1985 hunting
accident, Duddy said.
   Reed wouldn't say where he got the other toes, Duddy told
Indiana County Common Pleas Court Judge Robert Earley at a
45-minute exhumation hearing.
   Duddy said police wanted permission to open the grave to
determine whether more than one toe was taken from the boy.
   Pearce's family objected. Earley said the most severe charge
police could file against Reed is mutilation of a corpse, a
second-degree misdemeanor with a two-year statute of limitations,
which has passed.
   Police said they were led to Reed by a neighbor who told them
Reed proposed that the two of them pick up an unidentified
17-year-old girl, have sex with her, kill her and mutilate her body.
   Hudock said the neighbor introduced Reed to an undercover state
trooper posing as a professional killer. Duddy said he arrested
Reed on July 16, when he joined the undercover officer in a barn
where Reed allegedly expected the girl's slaying to occur.
   Reed was being held in the Jefferson County Jail in lieu of
$100,000 bond on charges of conspiracy to commit homicide, criminal
solicitation and attempted homicide, Hudock said.
   Troopers found the toes in a glass jar hidden in a basket of
wild nuts, Duddy said.
   Allegheny County Coroner's Office officials said they were
unable to determine whether the toes came from the same body.
   The search of Reed's home yielded numerous photographs of
people's feet and films of marchers in parades with the camera
zooming in on the marchers' legs and feet, Hudock said. Police said
they could not tell who took the pictures.
   One photograph showed an unidentified barefoot boy ``lying in
high grass'' with his bare feet above the grass, Duddy said.
Another showed the bare feet of a ``tall, thin man'' standing in
dirt with his shoes on the ground beside him, Duddy said.
   Duddy told Earley that police wanted to know if any harm came to
those in the photographs.
   Police said they also found 65 memorial cards from Jefferson and
Armstrong county funeral homes. Hudock said he suspected Reed
attended dozens of funerals of people he did not know.
   The prosecutor said Reed is not a suspect in any homicide and
has no psychiatric history or criminal record.
</TEXT>
