<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 2200EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ChristianScientist     08-04 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Christian Scientist,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Christian Science Couple Found Innocent on Involuntary Manslaughter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ROSA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Christian Science couple were
acquitted Friday of involuntary manslaughter but convicted of child
endangerment for relying on prayer instead of medical treatment for
their dying infant daughter.
   Mark Rippberger, 35, and Susan Middleton, 39, members of the
Church of Christ, Scientist, face up to four years state in prison
for the 1984 meningitis death of their 8-month-old daughter Natalie
Susan.
   Sentencing is set for Oct. 12.
   Rippberger and Middleton belong to a church founded by visionary
Mary Baker Eddy, who believed disease is a physical manifestation
of ``errors of the mind.''
   ``The jury showed remarkable intelligence in handing down this
verdict,'' said prosecutor David Dunn outside court. The family's
attorney, David Mackenroth of Sacramento, said he will appeal.
   During the seven-week trial before Sonoma County Superior Court
Judge Lloyd von der Mehden, the president of the American Academy
of Pediatrics testified that there is a 95 percent survival rate
when the infection is treated by a drug called defuroxime.
   The 12-member jury began deliberating the case Wednesday.
   Rippberger and Middleton were charged with two felonies,
involuntary manslaughter and child endangerment. Mackenroth
contended the couple were guilty only of following their religious
beliefs in seeking a cure through spiritual healing.
   Dunn said the couple may have acted correctly according to the
tenets of their religion, but their actions must be evaluated
against the standards of conduct established by law, that of an
``ordinarily prudent, careful person.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
