<DOCNO> AP890804-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 2128EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-SupremeCourt-Congress     08-04 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Supreme Court-Congress,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice White: Clearer Laws Could Lighten High Court's Load</HEAD>
<HEAD>Embargoed for release until 2:30 a.m. EDT Saturday; time set by source.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress could make the Supreme Court's job
easier by writing laws clearly, eliminating the need for
time-consuming court interpretations, Justice Byron R. White said
in a speech Friday.
   In the speech prepared for delivery at the American Bar
Association's convention, White said fellow Justice Antonin Scalia
has revived the debate over statutory language vs. legislative
history.
   In the past 50 years, courts trying to determine congressional
intent have looked at the legislative history of laws as well as
the wording of the statutes, White said.
   Such history includes committee hearings and reports, floor
debates and conference committee actions.
   White said a nearly 100-year-old high court decision _ Holy
Trinity Church vs. United States _ which allowed the interpretation
of even a clear statute based on legislative history, ``barely''
survived the Supreme Court's last session.
   In their interpretations, the courts begin with the statutory
language, which if thought clearly to relect legislative intent, is
followed, he said.
   However, ``most statutory cases involve not plain, but ambiguous
language, and in these cases resort to legislative history has been
the usual course,'' White said. ``This is often a very large
undertaking, taking hours and hours of effort by judges, law
clerks, and librarians, to say nothing of the time lawyers spend
and charge for seeking to present the materials that the judiciary
has indicated are relevant to decision.''
   With the ever-increasing complexity of subjects considered by
courts, more people, including Scalia, advocate a return to
interpreting statutes based almost wholly on the legislation's
text, White said.
   ``The statute as it is written, it is said, is what Congress
enacted, not statements in hearings, not discussion of statutory
terms contained in committee reports, and not statements on the
floor,'' said White, who was appointed to the court by President
Kennedy in 1962.
   White said Scalia, Reagan appointee, would confine the review of
legislative history to cases where the statuatory language itself
``produces an absurdity.''
   The debate over how statutes should be interpreted ``is
extremely important since it involves how the courts may best carry
out the will of Congress,'' White said, adding that in some cases
Congress may be vague on purpose, to force court decisions.
   White mentioned several other areas where Congress, as the major
source of changes in federal law, could ``simplify our work and at
the same time make its intent known..''
   _ When enacting laws, Congress should include a statute of
limitations, he said.
   _ Congress sometimes creates what seems to be a right, but fails
to provide a remedy, creating a recurring legal issue over whether
the seeming beneficiary of the right has a private remedy in
federal court, he said.
   _ Regarding conflicts between federal and state laws, White said
Congress should make its intentions clear when it plans to
supersede state law.
   _ White said Congress should clarify ``obvious uncertainties''
over statutes mandating the payment of lawyers' fees by losing
defendants.
   More than 8,000 lawyers are attending the convention, which
continues through Wednesday. The dinner was sponsored by the
American Judicature Society.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890804-0110 </DOCNO>
