<FIRST>r w AM-NorthPension 2ndLd-Writethru a0762 08-04 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-North Pension, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0762,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Helms Proposal Restoring North's Pension Snarls Senate</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf to delete extraneous word; picks up 5th graf,
Helms complained</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate debate over a routine spending bill was
halted temporarily Friday when conservatives tried using it to
restore Oliver North's $23,000 annual pension, forfeited after his
felony convictions in the Iran-Contra affair.
   The proposal, sponsored by Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., would
exempt the former White House aide from a law denying retirement
pay to officials convicted of destroying government documents, one
of three felonies on which North was found guilty.
   Democrats, reluctant to force a vote on the controversial former
Marine lieutenant colonel, instead delayed consideration of the
spending bill which would provide $18.4 billion for the Treasury,
Postal Service and other agencies for fiscal 1990.
   Senators returned to the spending bill, passing it by voice
vote, only after Senate leaders promised Helms that he would be
allowed action on a separate bill on North after the summer recess
but before Nov. 3.
   Helms complained that the government spent $40 million ``not
only to prosecute but to persecute'' North. He cited North's
service in Vietnam, where he won a Bronze Star, a Silver Star and
two Purple Hearts.
   ``A lot of the pygmies who criticize Oliver North never saw a
day when they were willing to lay down their lives for the
country,'' Helms said.
   Sen. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., countered that North was not
only a Vietnam hero but a convicted felon.
   ``Colonel North is no different than any other citizen,'' said
DeConcini. ``If you're found guilty, you have a right to appeal. If
you're found guilty, you lose certain benefits.''
   The debate eventually pitted a pair of Senate veterans of the
Vietnam War against each other.
   Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., who lost a portion of his leg in
Vietnam, argued that it is wrong for lawmakers to seek exceptions
for otherwise deserving individuals who fail to qualify for
government benefits. He cited a constituent who lost parts of both
legs in Vietnam but who failed to qualify for certain government
payments because the amputations were not severe enough.
   But Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a Navy fighter pilot who was a
prisoner of war in North Vietnam for 5{ years, countered, ``I'll
take up his case.''
   The Navy suspended North's pension when he was sentenced on July
5 by U.S. District Court Judge Gerhard A. Gesell to perform 1,200
hours of community service and pay a $150,000 fine. He was given no
prison time.
   The Navy later reversed itself, arguing that North, a retiree,
should not be considered an officeholder under the terms of the
law. But on Monday, U.S. Comptroller General Charles Bowsher
rejected the Navy's argument.
   North was convicted May 4 on charges of giving false testimony
to Congress during the Iran-Contra hearings, accepting a security
fence for his home, and shredding classified documents. He is
appealing his convictions.
   The former lieutenant colonel has become a popular dinner
speaker, with reports saying he collects up to $25,000 for each
appearance.
   Earlier this week, Sen. Steve Symms, R-Idaho, offered another
proposal to restore North's pension. Democrats watered it down to
instead require the Senate Judiciary Committee to study the
question and report by November.
   On Wednesday, the ranking Republican on the House Armed Services
Committee, Bill Dickinson of Alabama, introduced a separate bill to
restore North's pension.
</TEXT>
