<FIRST>r i AM-Cuba-Planes     08-04 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuba-Planes,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuba: Near Collision Between U.S. Spy Plane and Colombian Jetliner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuba said Friday that a U.S. spy plane nearly
collided with a Boeing 727 jetliner of Colombia's national airline,
according to Cuba's official news agency. U.S. and Colombian
aviation officials said they knew nothing about the purported
incident.
   Cuba's Civil Aviation Agency reported the pilot of the Colombian
jet told the aviation agency that on Wednesday he saw a
``silver-blue plane'' flying from east to west at the same altitude
as that of Avianca's Flight 63, the Prensa Latina dispatch said.
   The news agency reported the pilot said that if the other plane
had been flying at a greater speed a collision would have been
inevitable.
   The news agency said at the same time that the incident occurred
a U.S. RC-135 spy plane was flying over Cuba engaged in ``espionage
activities.''
   It reported the Avianca pilot filed complaints with air traffic
control authorities in Colombia, Cuba and Miami. The dispatch was
monitored in Mexico City.
   Arlene Salac, spokesman for the Federal Aviation
Administration's regional office in Atlanta, said it had not
received such a report and if one had been made with the Miami
control center the Atlanta office would have been notified.
   In Miami, airport officials and the local Avianca office said
they had not heard of such a report.
   FAA spokesman Fred Farrar said in Washington that he had checked
with several FAA offices about the Cuban account and ``I can't find
anyone who knows about it.''
   Colombian civil aeronatic officials in Bogota said the only
information they had was a report from Havana carried in the local
newspapers.
</TEXT>
