<FIRST>r a AM-StrippersSue     08-04 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Strippers Sue,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rejects Strippers' Age Discrimination Claim</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state judge on Friday ruled against three
French Quarter strippers who are challenging a new city ordinance
that bars striptease dancing by those under 21.
   Shannon Arendt, Josette Barry and Laura Folks contend that the
city is unconstitutionally denying them employment because of their
age, and they sought an injunction against enforcing the ordinance.
   State District Judge George C. Connolly Jr. set an Aug. 9
hearing on the lawsuit. The women, who are over 18 but under 21,
said they ``chose their profession or occupation because they enjoy
being entertainers and dancing.''
   The law went into effect July 26. No arrests had been made as of
Friday, an assistant city attorney said.
   In their lawsuit filed Thursday, the women said the ordinance is
``based on a request and false representations of an entity which
is trying to impose its religious views and values on plaintiffs
and other citizens of New Orleans.''
   The City Council passed the ordinance last month after James
Kelly, director of Covenant House, which cares for runaways and the
homeless, charged that stripping could lead to prostitution and
drug use.
   Kelly said he had to compete with ``drug dealers and flesh
peddlers'' in trying to find jobs for young drifters. However, many
club operators say the job of striptease dancing gives young people
a haven from street life.
   Deputy City Attorney William D. Aaron Jr. said he believes the
ordinance is on solid legal ground.
   ``The law says you've got to be 21 to buy an alcoholic drink in
a bar,'' he said. ``It just seems inconsistent for (people under
21) to work in that environment when the obvious intent of the
(drinking age law) is not to have them in that environment in the
first place.''
</TEXT>
