<FIRST>r a AM-Drownings     08-04 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drownings,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Children Drown In Car Plunge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WYANDOTTE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car in which four children drowned was
pulled from the Detroit River on Friday, as police waited to
interview the distraught parents about what caused the accident.
   The car carrying the family of six broke through a barrier and
plunged into the river about 9:30 p.m. Thursday in this Detroit
suburb.
   Susan Delisle, 32, and her husband, Lawrence, 28, escaped from
the car, but their four children were trapped inside, said police
Chief Edward Rothermal. He identified the victims as Brian, 8;
Melissa, 4; Kadie, 2, and Emily, 8 months.
   The parents were in stable condition Friday at Wyandotte General
Hospital, said Justine Kimbler, assistant director of nursing. The
family was from nearby Lincoln Park.
   The car was traveling at about 45 mph in a 25 mph zone when it
went out of control on a road that ended with a barricade at the
river, Rothermal said.
   He said the car smashed through the barricade and hit the water.
   Lawrence Delisle was questioned by police Thursday night, but
``was in shock and incoherent,'' Rothermal said.
   Susan Delisle said the family had left a restaurant with her
husband at the wheel when his leg cramped, and he lost control of
the car as it pulled out of the parking lot, said police Sgt.
Daniel Galeski.
   She tried to gain control of the car but could not, he said.
   Investigators planned to interview the parents over the weekend,
Deputy Chief Robert Schrader said Friday.
   After the car hit the water, the parents managed to climb out,
and passing boaters tossed life jackets to them.
   ``The man was so exhausted and the woman was hysterical,'' said
Rick Stoneburner, who said he and a companion threw the flotation
devices to the couple from their boat. ``She said, `I am not
leaving without my children. Save my children, they are
underwater.'''
   Police officers were at the scene almost immediately, Rothermal
said. One child was pulled out of the car within 15 minutes, and
all four were removed within an hour, he said.
</TEXT>
