<FIRST>u i AM-China-Deng 1stLd-Writethru a0627 08-04 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Deng, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0627,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Denies Report Deng is Ill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with official denial that Deng is
seriously ill, talk of ``ulterior motives.'' No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Foreign Ministry issued a terse statement
Saturday denying a Japanese news report that 84-year-old senior
leader Deng Xiaoping is seriously ill.
   ``The report is sheer fabrication with ulterior motives,'' the
statement said in full.
   The ministry rarely comments on news reports about major Chinese
leaders, particularly Deng, who repeatedly has been rumored ill,
dying or dead over the last few years. However, the latest report
came weeks after Deng purged his No. 2 man, Communist Party General
Secretary Zhao Ziyang, setting the stage for a power struggle after
his death.
   The report by Japan's Jiji Press quoted unidentified Chinese
sources as saying Deng's health deteriorated seriously a few days
ago and emergency medical personnel were sent to care for him at a
coastal resort east of Beijing.
   It quoted doctors as saying they were discussing whether Deng
was too ill to be moved to Beijing, where better medical facilities
are available.
   The report sent Hong Kong's stock market plunging 55.51 points.
   The only official comment Friday came from the Hong Kong office
of the official Xinhua News Agency, which called the report a mere
rumor.
   No signs emerged of special activity Friday night inside
Communist Party headquarters, Zhongnanhai, although lights burned
late into the night at the Great Hall of the People. Soldiers
stationed around Beijing to enforce martial law were not increased
in number.
   Deng was last seen in public on June 9, when national television
showed him meeting with top army officers and congratulating them
on having ended student pro-democracy protests in Beijing.
   The official Xinhua news agency has said nearly 100 soldiers and
police died on June 3-4 in quelling the protests and that thousands
were injured, while about 100 civilians died and nearly 1,000 were
injured. Chinese witnesses and Western intelligence sources said
the death toll may have been as high as 3,000.
   At that time, Deng spoke in a strong voice and appeared more
alert and healthy than he has for months. He is widely believed to
suffer from prostate problems, and over the past few years, there
have been periodic reports that he is seriously ill or dying.
   Chinese sources long have reported that he has little energy and
is able to work only a few hours each day.
</TEXT>
