<FIRST>u w AM-QuayleResidence     08-04 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle Residence,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Veep's Home to be Overhauled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate on Friday night approved an $18.4
billion spending bill including $200,000 to remodel the vice
president's official residence to accomodate the young family of
Dan Quayle.
   The appropriations bill for the Treasury, the Postal Service,
the Office of the President and other smaller agencies for the
fiscal year beginning Oct. 1 was approved by voice vote after the
Senate put aside a controversial amendment to restore Oliver
North's military pension. That issue will be taken up as a separate
bill later this year.
   The House version of the spending bill, approved July 28, also
provides money for the renovations to the vice presidential mansion
_ work that the family had previously said would be done with
private funds.
   The money would go toward work on the third floor of the 19th
Century mansion on the Naval Observatory grounds in an exclusive
Washington neighborhood.
   The three Quayle children, ranging in age between 15 and 10,
live on that level. When President Bush lived in the home as vice
president, the third floor was used for Barbara Bush's office, a
maid's bedroom and for storage.
   The Quayles have raised $200,000 but intend to use it for
furnishings instead, according to Denise Balzano, aide to Quayle's
wife, Marilyn.
   The overall bill contains $5.5 billion for the Internal Revenue
Service, $300 million more than this year, and $1.3 billion for the
Customs Service, $100 million above 1989 spending. Both are
Treasury agencies.
   It also cuts $30 million out of Postal Service funds used to
allow charities and institutions to enjoy low mailing rates. The
provision is aimed at preventing credit card companies from joining
with charities to seek business, and thus taking advantage of
subsidized mail rates.
   Another part of the bill would suspend enforcement of a tax law
for one year that encourages companies to bestow health insurance
on low-level workers and discourages greater benefits for
high-level executives than for other employees. Business groups
have complained that the requirement is expensive and
time-consuming.
   Like all annual spending bills considered by Congress, the
Treasury measure is riddled with special projects for certain
lawmakers.
   Thus, it orders Treasury to transfer an aircraft it has seized
to the Arizona Health Sciences Center in Tucson, Ariz. The chairman
of the Senate Appropriations treasury subcommittee is Dennis
DeConcini, D-Ariz.
   The Senate also eliminated money to keep a post office
functioning in Holly Springs, Miss.
   Holly Springs happens to be in the district of Rep. Jamie
Whitten, D-Miss., chairman of the House Appropriations Committee.
Rejecting the money for a project of interest to the other chamber
is a favorite tactic in Congress to enhance one's bargaining
position when a compromise bill is fashioned.
   The two chambers will have to work out compromise legislation
after Congress returns from its recess in September before sending
it to President Bush for his signature.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
