<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 2253EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Sakharov     08-04 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sakharov,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sakharove Calls For Faster Change, Warns of Dire Possibilities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev's gradual approach
to change in the Soviet Union may lead to economic or political
disaster, Soviet human rights activist Andrei Sakharov told
scholars at Harvard University.
   ``Waiting longer for the radicalization of perestroika is out of
the question,'' the 68-year-old physicist said Thursday at a
luncheon with Harvard officials and Soviet affairs specialists
hosted by Derek Bok, the university's president.
   ``If we allow this to go on, we are threatened with chaos,''
Sakharov said after giving a critical review of his country's
problems. ``We may be threatened with a military coup. We may be
threatened with famine.
   ``This state is now at a historic moment. It could tip left or
right. We have to find a way to hold our course.''
   Sakharov said the most immediate danger is the economy, and he
joked that ``a good way to tell whether someone is an optimist or a
pessimist'' is to ask whether he thinks economic disaster will
strike in ``one, two or five years.''
   The luncheon, also attended by Sakharov's wife, Elena Bonner,
was held at the residence of Harvard President Derek Bok. Sakharov
spoke through a translator.
   Ms. Bonner, who has also been a longtime critic of Soviet
policies, urged Western nations not to get carried away with
uncritical applause for Soviet reforms and not to stop pressing for
change.
   ``The Soviet people are overjoyed to find that, in fact, our
country is a living entity,'' she said, recalling the recent
Congress of People's Deputies, where open debates kept the nation
riveted to its television screens.
   ``The whole country was amazed and enthusiastic to see that we
are alive, that we haven't lost our reason because of the hunger,
the trials, the falsification that we've suffered,'' she said. ``If
only the West can keep itself from lousing things up.''
   Sakharov, who won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1975, was banished to
internal exile in the city of Gorky for seven years after
criticizing the Soviet intervention in Afghanistan. He was released
in 1986 by Gorbachev and has since been allowed to speak out and
travel freely.
   He is a deputy in the new, 2,500-member congress and has emerged
as one of the leaders of an independent bloc of about 400 delegates
calling for speedier reforms aimed at democratizing the country and
decentralizing the economy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
