<FIRST>r i AM-Honduras-Guns     08-04 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honduras-Guns,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Honduran Army Captures Salvadoran Rebel Gunrunners</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Central America</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The armed forces said Friday it
broke up a ring of leftist rebels smuggling guns from Nicaragua
into El Salvador.
   It said it killed one guerrilla, captured five and confiscated
60 Soviet-made AK-47 assault rifles in operations that began in
central Honduras on July 28.
   ``All the arms were new,'' spokesman Col. Manuel Suarez told a
news conference.
   He called the group ``a subversive cell of the FMLN'' and ``part
of the logistics system organized by the FMLN in Honduras over the
past eight years to obtain arms from Nicaragua.''
   The FMLN is the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, the
leftist rebel army that has been at war with a succession of
U.S.-backed governments in El Salvador since 1980.
   He said the gunrunners brought weapons in from Nicaragua at El
Codito, 155 miles east of Tegucigalpa in El Paraiso province on the
Nicaraguan border.
   Clandestine routes were used to transfer the arms into
Salvadoran refugee camps in Honduras and then across the border
into El Salvador, Suarez said.
   He said camps near Colomoncagua, where about 10,000 refugees
live, were often used by Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government
``to send arms to the FMLN.''
   Suarez identified the slain guerrilla as Manuel de Jesus Larin,
a 36-year-old Salvadoran who belonged to the Central American
Revolutionary Workers Party, a guerrilla group with members from
all over Central America.
   He said Larin died in a confrontation with soldiers July 28
while transporting arms to the FMLN. The AK-47s were found in
Larin's vehicle, he said.
   Suarez said two other Salvadorans and three Hondurans were
captured in subsequent operations.
   Nicaragua has long denied providing arms to the FMLN. It
describes its support for Salvadoran rebels as moral and logistical.
   The 9-year-old civil war in El Salvador has killed an estimated
70,000 people, mostly civilians.
</TEXT>
