<FIRST>r i AM-China-Kenya     08-04 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Kenya,0205</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kenyan Students Stage Embassy Sit-in To Demand Plane Tickets, Stipends</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty Kenyans studying in China have staged a
sit-in at their embassy in Beijing, demanding plane tickets home
and higher stipends, the students said Friday.
   The Kenyans are the second group of African students in China to
invade their embassy this summer. About 40 Zairean students staged
a 10-day sit-in that ended last week, demanding payment of
thousands of dollars in overdue stipends.
   The Kenyans said they were not in touch with the Zaireans and
said their situations are not identical.
   The Kenyans want plane tickets home for three students who
graduated this year and one who withdrew, a substantial increase in
their living allowance and better communication between embassy and
students.
   They went to the embassy Monday morning to discuss their
complaints. They said they stayed on because their government
promised them nothing.
   They have camped out in the embassy library, sleeping on the
floor and sofas, and eating bread and milk.
   The students spoke on condition of anonymity because they feared
reprisals from their government.
   No one at the embassy was immediately available for comment, and
later calls were unanswered.
</TEXT>
