<FIRST>r a AM-CapsizedRig     08-04 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Capsized Rig,0190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chevron And Coast Guard Abandon Search For Missing Oil Rig Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coast Guard and Chevron on Friday
abandoned the search for six workers missing from a capsized rig in
the Gulf of Mexico on Friday.
   ``Chevron has exhausted all efforts for the search for the
missing people by divers,'' the oil company said in a statement.
Avis Bourg Co., which owns the rig, will salvage it and continue
the search for the workers, Chevron said.
   Avis Bourg officials did not return repeated telephone calls to
their office.
   The Coast Guard on Monday will open hearings into the accident
Monday which killed at least four men when the rig capsized Monday.
Four crewmen were rescued immediately after the accident.
   The lift boat, or ``jackup rig,'' with legs that can be moved up
while traveling or down while working, remains on its side in 30
feet of water. It overturned while heading for shore while
Hurricane Chantal approached.
   Divers for Chevron, which had contracted the rig and workers,
searched through Thursday night and recovered four bodies from the
rig.
