<FIRST>r a AM-IllinoisWeather     08-04 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Illinois Weather,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Knock Out Power, Cause Flooding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A thunderstorm doused sections of northeastern
Illinois with up to 5 inches of rain Friday, flooding roads,
causing widespread power outages and forcing the evacuation of
hundreds of patients from a flooded hospital.
   Doctors, nurses and ambulance crews worked Friday night to
discharge or transfer to other hospitals about 300 patients from
Resurrection Medical Center, a 434-bed hospital on Chicago's
Northwest Side.
   The hospital's basement was flooded and the ground floor was
ankle-deep in water at one point, officials said. Patients had no
hot water or hot food because of the flooding.
   Firefighters were working to pump out water from the basement
and sub-basement, said hospital spokeswoman Janice Youngwith.
   More than 50,000 Commonwealth Edison customers lost electricity
at the storm's peak between 4 a.m. and 4:30 a.m., said utility
spokesman Mike Kelly. By early afternoon, all but 100 or 200 had
power back.
   ``We're down to just a mop-up operation,'' Kelly said.
   In the area near O'Hare International Airport, ``we got just
about our entire total normal monthly rainfall for August,'' in the
downpour, said Richard Koeneman, a forecaster with the National
Weather Service in Chicago.
   O'Hare got 3.45 inches of rain between 1:30 a.m. and 6:30 a.m.,
he said. The total normal rainfall for August in the area is 3.53
inches.
   Flash flood warings went up for northern Kane, Du Page and Cook
counties, as well as De Kalb County.
   The Edens Expressway was closed near Winnetka after 6 a.m. and
remained closed until about 10:30 a.m., frustrating commuters, said
Illinois Department of Transportation dispatchers.
   Public safety officers used an inflatable dinghy to rescue a man
who was stranded knee-deep in water on the top of his submerged car
on the expressway under an overpass in suburban Northfield, said
Paul Harlow, deputy chief of public safety in Glencoe.
   Power outages hit the northern suburbs the hardest, followed by
Chicago's north side and the western suburbs, said Commonwealth
Edison spokesman Jose Andrade.
   Crews in trucks were hampered by street flooding, he said.
   The heaviest part of the storm swept a 20-mile-wide band on a
line from Elgin through Arlington Heights to Evanston, Koeneman
said.
   Three to five inches of rain fell in the hardest-hit areas, he
said. But the rains hit a relatively small region, and ``people who
live to south are certainly probably wondering what all the
excitement is about.''
</TEXT>
