<FIRST>r a AM-GayAttack     08-04 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gay Attack,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Review Gay Attack Evidence in Light of Victim's New Story</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lesbian minister who said she was the
victim of two anti-gay attacks last month changed her story when
police confronted her with evidence some of her injuries were
self-inflicted, authorities said Friday.
   Lynn Griffis, an assistant pastor at the Metropolitan Community
Church of San Francisco, resigned from her duties two hours after
being placed on administrative leave Thursday night, said Rev. Jim
Mitulski.
   ``As a church, we have a lot of compassion for Lynn, and
whatever the truth is, we want to know what the truth is,''
Mitulski said. Griffis has left town and he doesn't expect to hear
from her again, he said.
   Griffis said she was attacked first on July 12, hit on the head
with a shovel after surprising an assailant who broke into her
garage and scrawled anti-gay graffiti on the wall. She received
eight stitches.
   She later alleged that she was abducted July 27 in the
Haight-Ashbury area by two so-called ``skinheads'' who threw her
into a car, beat her up and threatened to kill her before releasing
her.
   Police Chief Frank Jordan said her account of the first attack
was consistent with the evidence, but the medical examiner said
physical evidence failed to match her account of a second attack.
   Jordan declined to detail the inconsistencies, but a source
close to the case told The Associated Press that Medical Examiner
Boyd Stephens determined the injuries she allegedly suffered from
the skinheads were self-inflicted.
   Jordan also said damage to Griffis' clothing and a subsequent
description of how her injuries were received were inconsistent
with the evidence or even her account. ``There was no attack as
described,'' he added.
   Stephens did not return telephone calls made Friday evening by
The AP.
   When police presented the inconsistent evidence to Griffis at a
meeting with members of the gay community on Thursday, Griffis
described a different series of events and said she had been
sexually assaulted, Jordan said.
   Police have referred the case to their sex crimes unit and will
reconsider all of the evidence, Jordan said.
   Griffis has worked at MCC for about 18 months, Mitulski said.
``She did good work with people with AIDS,'' he said. ``She helped
a lot of people. This doesn't change that ... I can't understand
why this would happen.''
   The church had received a written death threat against Griffis
and Mitulski the night before the first attack, and Mitulski said
he has received subsequent death threats over the phone.
   The alleged attacks, coupled with the recent defacing of a gay
man's home, prompted local gay leaders to organize self-defense and
gun-handling classes.
   Reports of inconsistencies in Griffis' case prompted fears among
gay advocates that subsequent reports would not be taken seriously
by officials or the public.
   Jordan and others said that regardless of the outcome of the
Griffis case, hate crimes will not be tolerated. He said police
receive about 10 reports of hate crimes per month, and that other
community organizations receive more.
</TEXT>
