<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Train     08-04 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Train,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two `Great Train Robbery' Gangsters Jailed In Drug Case</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   LONDON (AP)_ Two men convicted 25 years ago in Britain's ``Great
Train Robbery'' case were back in prison Friday after pleading
guilty to drug-trafficking charges.
   Thomas Wisbey, 59, was sentenced to 10 years in prison and James
Hussey, 56, was given a 7-year sentence for drug dealing.
   Both men had been convicted of participating in the Great Train
Robbery of Aug. 8, 1963, when a gang of 15 men stole $7 million
from a mail train.
   ``You are both old enough and experienced enough to know exactly
what you were doing and your motive was greed in each case,
regardless of the welfare of your fellow citizens,'' Judge Roger
Sanders told the defendants at Snaresbrook Crown Court in east
London before sentencing them Friday.
   Hussey and Wisbey were each sentenced to 30 years in jail in
1964 for their part in the train robbery. Hussey was released in
December 1975 and Wisbey the following year.
   At a hearing in the drugs case police testified that they saw
the two men exchanging bags containing cocaine in a park.
   Detective Sgt. Martin Gill told the court police seized 5.3
pounds of drugs with a street value of more than $930,000.
   Sanders ordered confiscation of about $76,000 found by police at
two addresses and with Wisbey's wife Irene.
   Wisbey, who pleaded guilty, was sentenced to 10 years for
supplying 2.2 pounds of cocaine to Hussey. He also was sentenced to
10 years for possession of cocaine with intent to supply and three
months for possessing marijuana. The sentences are to run
concurrently.
   Hussey pleaded guilty of possessing 2.2 pounds of cocaine with
intent to supply.
   The Great Train Robbery was planned with military precision and
at the time was Britain's biggest robbery.
   Faking a railroad signal in the countryside northwest of London,
the gang stopped a mail train traveling from Glasgow to London.
   They broke into the mail van, overpowered the crew and stole
more than 120 bags full of used banknotes. Less than $980,000 was
recovered.
   All 15 members of the gang were caught. One, Ronald Biggs,
received a 30-year prison sentence, but escaped from London's
Wandsworth prison on July 8, 1965. He now lives in Brazil, immune
from extradition because of legal technicalities.
</TEXT>
