<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 2323EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Israel-Poll     08-04 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Poll,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Half Disapprove of Kidnapping</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Half of Americans questioned in a poll
disapprove of Israel's kidnapping of a Shiite Moslem cleric,
according to results released Friday.
   A similar proportion thought President Bush had been ``not tough
enough'' in handling the hostage crisis, according to the ABC
News-Washington Post poll of 711 adults on Wednesday and Thursday.
   Still, almost as many approved Bush's handling of the situation.
   The proportion considering Israel a ``reliable ally,'' or one
that can be trusted to cooperate with the United States ``in almost
any circumstances,'' fell to the lowest level in the eight years
that question had been asked, 29 percent.
   Forty-eight percent said Israel should return the kidnapped man
and 35 percent said he should not be returned. The rest had no
opinion.
   Thirty percent approved of the kidnapping in the first place and
51 percent disapproved.
   Fifty-one percent said Bush had not been tough enough, 35
percent said his reaction had been ``just about right'' and 1
percent said he had been too tough.
   When asked to approve or disapprove the president's handling of
the crisis, 47 percent approved and 35 percent disapproved.
   Forty-eight percent said Israel should return its captive and 35
percent said it should not.
   The proportion characterizing Israel as ``not reliable'' rose to
53 percent from 46 percent giving a similar response in April,
while those judging Israel reliable fell from 51 percent to 29
percent.
   Since 1981, the proportion applying the term ``reliable'' to
Israel had fluctuated from 40 percent to 64 percent. Those
returning a judgment of ``not reliable'' had ranged between 24
percent and 56 percent.
   In a sample of 711 people, the margin of error is 4.5 percentage
points either way, the poll said.
</TEXT>
