<SECOND>AM-Bush-Bush,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Returns HUD Figure's Nomination to Administration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate returned three of President Bush's
nominations to the White House on Friday for him to reconsider _
including one whose name has cropped up in connection with the
influence-peddling scandal in the Department of Housing and Urban
Development.
   Voting just before leaving for their August recess, senators
also approved several of the president's nominations to federal
posts and ambassadorships.
   Among those they returned was that of Fred Bush, no relation to
the president, who was nominated to be ambassador to Luxembourg.
   Fred Bush was a prominent fundraiser for President Reagan's 1984
re-election campaign and then-Vice President Bush's 1988 race who
has since worked as a consultant on housing projects.
   Fred Bush was paid $215,000 to help land HUD funds for
developers on a Puerto Rico project. He has testified before
congressional investigators, telling them he ``did not bring very
much'' to the project.
   Along with Fred Bush, the Senate returned to the president the
nominations of Diane Morales, who was nominated for assistant
secretary of energy for Environment, Safety and Health, and Vaughn
Walker, the president's choice for the U.S. District Court for for
the northern district of California. Walker has been criticized for
belonging to segregated clubs.
   The Senate action was not a formal rejection. The president can
submit the names again or find new nominations.
   The Senate approved John Betti, a former official with the Ford
Motor Company, as the new acquisitions chief at the Pentagon, and
Michael Stone as Secretary of the Army.
   Three Bush nominees for the Federal Communications Commission
were approved: Sherrie P. Marshall, Andrew C. Barrett, and Alfred
C. Sikes, who will become chairman.
   Richard Clarke and Raymond Seitz were approved as assistant
secretaries of state, and approval was given to new ambassadors to
Nepal, Ghana, Greece, Ireland, South Africa, and Norway.
