<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 1331EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-NorthernIrelandToday Adv13-2Takes   08-04 0774</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Northern Ireland Today, Adv 13-2 Takes,0795</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Aug. 13 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Northern Ireland Today _ 20 Years After Strife Began</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note anniversary is Aug. 14</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Northern Ireland erupted into violence on Aug.
14, 1969. Twenty years and 2,740 deaths later, the violence
continues. But much has changed in recent years and some in the
British province are beginning to see the foundations of a
solution. Here is a report by an Associated Press correspondent who
covers Northern Ireland regularly.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By MARCUS ELIASON</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All Mrs. Murphy's neighbors are
gone.
   The house she and her husband bought on Roe St. stands alone in
a no-man's land, its windows protected by steel mesh and a tall
corrugated wall separating the Roman Catholic couple from
Protestant families 200 yards down the street.
   Susan Murphy's neighborhood once was mixed, with Protestants and
Roman Catholics living side by side. But Northern Ireland's
violence came to Roe St. and the stonings and firebombings proved
more than Mrs. Murphy's neighbors could bear.
   They went off to live among their own and authorities tore down
their houses.
   But the Murphys held out.
   It all happened not 20 years ago, when ``The Troubles'' were at
their worst in the British province, also known as Ulster, but just
five months ago, and the houses razed were not hovels but new
showcases of a Belfast rising from the Victorian slums.
   ``It's something of an indictment of society here,'' says Ivan
Maginnis of the Housing Executive that had to make the decision.
``It's an awful tragedy.''
   It's easy to conclude from this million-dollar exercise that
little has changed in Northern Ireland since British troops arrived
Aug. 14, 1969 to separate rioting Protestants from their Catholic
neighbors.
   The death toll is over 2,740 and rising almost week by week. The
Catholic unemployment rate is 2{ times that of Protestants. A
political solution still looks far off.
   And yet one finds a glimmer of optimism in Northern Ireland
today.
   Violence has diminished from a peak of 467 killings in 1972 to
an average of 80 a year in the 1980s.
   Recent elections suggest a weakening of the hard-liners on both
sides of the divide and a boost for the moderates.
   In the Irish Republic to the south, the political mold shaped in
the country's 1921-23 civil war has cracked and opened new
possibilities for a solution that can accommodate both Unionist and
Nationalist in Northern Ireland.
   The Unionists are the majority Protestants intent on retaining
union with Britain, and Nationalists are the 40-percent Catholic
minority whose aspirations lean to the Irish Republic.
   The Irish government in Dublin has not renounced its claim to
Northern Ireland. It simply doesn't state it too loudly. It is in
consensus with the British government that nothing can change
without Protestant consent.
   In a half dozen of Northern Ireland's 26 district councils,
moderate Catholics and Protestants have joined in coalitions to
shut out the extremists on both sides.
   Dungannon, a town of 15,000 in the center of the province, was
once a bastion of Unionist supremacy and discrimination. Now its
mixed council has a committee to promote cross-community
understanding and sends Protestant and Catholic children on
vacations together.
   The whole island, north and south, is in intellectual ferment
over the prospect that a united Europe _ beginning with the
lowering of trade barriers in the European Economic Community in
1992 _ will subsume old nationalist rivalries in Ireland.
   ``National sovereignty is changing its whole meaning in European
terms,'' says John Hume, leader of the Social Democratic and Labor
Party, the province's main Catholic nationalist party. ``The nation
state is disappearing. So the fundamental reason for the quarrel
between Britain and Ireland is now gone.''
   A backwater 20 years ago, Northern Ireland now has air links to
European resorts. A burgeoning Catholic middle class hungers for
stability. A retail boom has transformed the bombed-blackened city
centers of Belfast and Londonderry.
   Aidan O'Reilly's family was driven out of their home in 1973 by
Protestant mobs. Married now with a baby son, O'Reilly owns a house
in a quiet Belfast suburb. He is one of the thousands who look back
on the old days and pray they'll never return.
   By pouring some $2.25 billion a year into the province, Britain
can actually buy pockets of stability. Councilor Anthony McGonnell,
a 40-year-old schoolteacher, says Dungannon's new approach is
helped along by the knowledge that ``if a council is seen to be
trying to work together, central government is much more
sympathetic towards it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890804-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 1332EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s i BC-NorthernIrelandToday Adv13-1stadd   08-04 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Northern Ireland Today, Adv 13-1st add,0676</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Aug. 13 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>BELFAST: towards it.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Ralph Brown, a 52-year-old Unionist councilor whose appliance
store on Dungannon's main street has been damaged 11 times by Irish
Republican Army bombs, strongly backs municipal power-sharing.
   ``A lot of trust has been built up,'' he says. ``People are
really bending over backward at the moment to try and ensure that
nothing major goes wrong.''
   Paul Bew, an analyst at Queen's University in Belfast, was
deeply pessimistic in the mid-1980s. Now he feels things are
looking up.
   ``I am more modestly optimistic about some kind of accommodation
in Ireland than I have been for a long, long time,'' he says.
   Hume suggests a round-table conference of all the parties _ the
Irish in Dublin, the British and the Northerners _ to define the
problem, then solve it.
   Unionists prefer some sort of power-sharing arrangement with
Catholics, provided the Irish government is not involved. That
distance between the two positions is great, but at least the two
sides are talking about solutions.
   The trouble is that life is not improving in the blue-collar
ghettoes, where pockets of 80-percent unemployment provide recruits
for the IRA and Sinn Fein, its political backer in the campaign to
end British rule in Ulster and unite it with the southern republic.
   Sinn Fein's Francis McCann, a Belfast city councilor, says none
of the prosperity of recent years has reached his constituency. And
the Dungannon spirit hasn't reached Belfast, whose
Unionist-dominated council hasn't given a single committee seat to
a Nationalist.
   McCann, a 36-year-old man with ``IRELAND'' tattooed on his arm,
says he has endured jailings, internment without trial, countless
arrests and house searches, and all because ``I believe that Irish
people have a right to resist British rule in this country.''
   Hume, the voice of Catholic moderation, denounces the IRA,
producing statistics indicating that two-thirds of those killed
since 1969 were Catholics, and 44 percent of them victims of the
IRA.
   ``The IRA have killed six times more people than the British
army and 30 times more people than the RUC (Royal Ulster
Constabulary). ... Those figures alone would force anybody to say
to themselves, `Hold on a minute, where are our methods leading
us?'''
   Northern Ireland was set up in 1921 as a British enclave when
the rest of Ireland won independence and became a Protestant
fiefdom rife with gerrymandering, police brutality and
discrimination in housing and jobs.
   In 1968, Catholics began demanding civil rights. Violent
Protestant reaction brought in the British army, which soon found
itself at war with the IRA. In 1972, the government in London
closed Northern Ireland's Parliament and assumed direct rule.
   In 1985, Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher signed the Anglo-Irish
Agreement giving Dublin a say in the running of the province.
Outraged Unionists, who regard Ireland as a hostile Catholic state,
reacted violently.
   But their protests were ignored, and they are finally beginning
to talk about negotiating a solution.
   Meanwhile, some Catholics concede that many of the grievances of
the 1960s have been rectified. Gerrymandering and housing
discrimination have been swept away by decree from London. Under
new fair-employment laws, employers guilty of discrimination face
fines the equivalent of $48,000 and the loss of government grants
and contracts.
   But unemployment is around 18 percent, Britain's highest, and
violence drives away investment and jobs.
   Policing remains a thorny problem. The Royal Ulster Constabulary
went some way toward evenhandedness by standing up to the riots
against the Anglo-Irish Agreement. But every Catholic, moderate or
militant, has a story to tell of physical or verbal abuse by the
mostly Protestant security patrols.
   McGonnell says security-force misbehavior is one of the major
reasons why the vote for Sinn Fein, the political wing of the IRA,
still hovers around 11 percent. Bew, the Queen's University
analyst, believes that only massive aid for Catholic west Belfast
can eat into Sinn Fein's support there.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday, Aug. 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
