<DOCNO> AP890804-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 1317EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s w BC-WalterMears Adv06   08-04 0807</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Walter Mears, Adv 06,0823</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv06</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Aug 6 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Washington Sights, Sites the Guidebooks Won't Tell You About</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: This stands for the regular column by Walter R. Mears, vacationing.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It is 9:45 on a Tuesday, Wednesday or Thursday
morning and you are standing by the driveway outside the Rayburn
House Office Building. Up draws a limousine and out pour the
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff and a squad of
briefcase-toting colonels.
   Here comes another and out comes the secretary of agriculture.
Then the chairman of the Federal Trade Commission, the director of
the Office of Management and Budget, the surgeon general in starchy
white.
   It is something to see, the arrival of officialdom at Congress'
doorsteps to appear before committees and subcommittees, to ask, to
explain, to defend, to dodge, to woo _ and to demonstrate that the
checks and balances concept is alive and well in Washington.
   Officials arrive at other congressional buildings and the
Capitol itself, but because all going to Rayburn use a single
entrance, it is a fine place to behold the phenomenon. Tuesdays,
Wednesdays or Thursdays are best, because those are Congress' three
full workdays.
   Every town has a few places, people or phenomena that are
uniquely its own _ just as the waltz of arriving officialdom is
Washington's alone. Here are a few other Washington institutions:
   _The Billy Goat Trail. It is a hiking trail on the Maryland
banks of the Potomac. If you think of Washington as an effete city
where no work gets done but words get spoken, the terrain's
unexpected roughness, in such proximity to the city, will surprise
you.
   Why, one could fall off the trail and roll down the steep
hillside into the rocks of the Potomac! No OSHA to come to the
rescue.
   Edward Evangelidi, a hiking writer, says of the four-mile Billy
Goat Trail: ``It is shaped by many elements of nature. At times it
is inundated and scoured by rampaging floods of the Potomac. Its
unusual flora barely survives in the hot, dry relentless summer
suns and rocky geography.'' He suggests you watch out for snakes.
There are places where you'll find yourself hiking on all fours, or
grabbing hold of a wedge of rock. You might as well be in Wyoming.
   _Red Lion Row. This is quintessential Washington architecture:
the architecture of compromise. The owners wanted to tear down the
late Federal and Greek Revival and Victorian houses along the 2000
block of Pennsylvania Avenue, four blocks west of the White House,
to make room for yet another block-long behemoth office building.
Preservationists said no, those little houses are vital reminders
of the scale and style of the city as it was when Lincoln paced the
streets.
   A bargain was reached. The old two-story buildings were saved
and converted to stores and offices; the behemoth rose attached to
and behind them. The old houses, not just their facades, were
retained; this was not just another face-saving gesture. Like most
compromises, what results is not entirely satisfactory to everyone.
   _Stephen Wade. This entertainer came here about the same time
Ronald Reagan did but outlasted his fellow showman. Wade came from
Chicago to play the banjo and tell tall tales for a few weeks' run
in a basement theater at at Arena Stage. Washington, charmed, won't
let him go.
   A man of beguiling passion, Wade reminds people of their human
commonality. He has revised his act, but the title of his first
show best gives the flavor: ``Banjo Dancing, or the 48th Annual
Squitters Mountain Song Dance Folklore Convention and Banjo Contest
and How I Lost.''
   _Rock Creek's Meadows. Washingtonian Peggy Fleming is a citizen
nature-lover who by dint of determination became a National Park
Service ranger. Then she persuaded the authorities to stop mowing
the grass in a few swatches of Rock Creek Park, which runs through
the city.
   Controversy, as you can imagine, ensued. Some people think
unmowed grass is mayhem, and even a park needs discipline, but
Peggy Fleming prevailed. Twenty-three of the park's 3,000 acres
were allowed to go wild. They are mowed once a year to keep them
from becoming forests.
   The result: not lawn, not woods, but something in between. The
next result: new flora and fauna that flourish only under such
circumstances.
   Voila! Goldfinches, short-tailed shrews, purpletop grass,
six-feet tall bull thistles, owls, the pearl crescent butterfly _
all thriving where they otherwise hadn't and wouldn't.
   Like Stephen Wade's banjo, Peggy Fleming's Meadows are a
Washington miracle, the unexpected pleasure; like the high-stepping
colonels, the short-tailed shrews are a sight to behold.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Mike Feinsilber has been taking in the sights of
Washington for 20 years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 6</NOTE>
</DOC>
