<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 0045EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-S&amp;Ls 9thLd-Writethru   08-04 0939</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls, 9th Ld-Writethru,0965</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agreement Reached on S&amp;L Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 11th graf, `With S&amp;L ...,' to CORRECT daily losses to $20
million sted $20 billion.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration and congressional
negotiators reached agreement Thursday night on financing a
sweeping $159 billion bailout of the savings and loan industry
after Senate Republicans torpedoed a Democratic plan.
   The compromise was reached after a series of fast-paced
developments in which President Bush threatened to veto the bill,
the Democratic-controlled House ignored him in on a 221-199 vote in
favor of it and Senate Democrats fell six votes short of mustering
the 60 needed to complete action.
   That automatically tossed the bill back into a House-Senate
conference committee, which locked up the deal after 11 p.m..
Approval is expected by the full Senate, and then the House, on
Friday, the last day before the August colngressional vacation.
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady and White House Budget
Director Richard Darman accepted a compromise proposal splitting
the cost of the bailout so that only 40 percent of the $50 billion
needed immediately would balloon the federal deficit.
   The deal calls for the Treasury to borrow $20 billion this year,
raising the estimated deficit from $149 billion to $169 billion,
and borrowing by a new agency to raise the $30 billion balance next
year and the year after without counting that in the official
deficit.
   ``Obviously we've only had an opportunity to make a quick
review, but based on that review ... in the spirit of which the
president sent us here, which was one of compromise, we accept,''
Brady said.
   The compromise was approved on a 26-22 vote among House members
of the conference committee despite vehement objections from Rep.
Dan Rostenkowski, chairman of the tax-writing House Ways and Means
Committee. Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., was the only one of the five
Senate negotiators to vote against the deal.
   All of the money would be used to close some 500 insolvent S&amp;Ls
_ the bulk of them in Texas _ and pay off savers whose federally
insured deposits were lost through failed an often fraudulent loans.
   The administration and Congress had reached agreement long ago
on the bulk of the legislation directing a massive overhaul of the
industry's structure and regulation in an effort to prevent a
recurrence of the cisis.
   But a confrontation over the financing which one Democrat
characterized as a ``game of chicken'' had threatened to blow the
deal apart.
   With S&amp;L losses mounting at a rate of $20 million to $30 million
a day, both the administration and congressional leaders were
adamant in their demands that the fix be approved before the
vacation recess.
   ``Ninety percent of the people want to get out of here,'' said
Rep. Joe Moakley, D-Mass., chairman of the House Rules Committee.
``They have reservations for vacation.''
   Darman earlier had called the $20 billion-$30 billion,
on-budget-off-budget split ``conceptually sound'' but declined to
give it a blanket endorsement without a vote on it among the
congressional negotiators.
   Prior to Thursday night, the administration has steadfastly
demanded that all of the bailout's costs be raised 30-year bonds
issued outside the normal Treasury borrowing process, and outside
the official deficit.
   The bill also would institute a major overhaul of the
government's regulation of the nation's nearly 3,000 thrifts and
require their owners to put billions of dollars more of their own
money at risk.
   ``Both of them are turkeys,'' Sen. Jake Garn, R-Utah, said of
the alternative Bush and Democratic plans for raising the bailout's
costs. ``It's a question of the lesser of two evils.''
   Democrats contended Bush's plan would increase the cost by $150
million a year over the next three decades because the bonds would
carry higher interest rates than normal U.S. Treasury obligations.
   Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., described the dispute as
``politics, plain and simple.''
   ``The only difference now is they (Republicans) do not want the
deficit number to go up the first year of the Bush
administration,'' he said. ``If it did not cost any money to not
tell the truth, that would be fine. But not telling the truth is
going to cost $4.5 billion to $60 billion.''
   Bush issued his veto threat early in the day, shortly before the
House began debating the bill that has been months in the drafting.
   ``If the conference report is presented to me in its current
form, I will veto the bill,'' he said. ``While
Gramm-Rudman-Hollings is not perfect, it represents the only
available institutional requirement for fiscal discipline by the
Congress and the executive branch.''
   Over the next 10 years, the costs, including interest, would
rise to $159 billion, according to the latest administration
estimates. The interest costs over future years push the
three-decade total for the rescue to more than $285 billion _ $157
billion of it from taxpayers.
   S&amp;Ls would have to devote more of their lending to home
mortgages. Their investments in risky real estate ventures would be
curtailed and their purchases of junk bonds would be outlawed.
   It also would remove five decades of prohibitions on bank
ownership of S&amp;Ls, enabling banks to buy out their most competitive
lending market rivals in many communities.
   A new government agency, the Resolution Trust Corp., would be
established to dispose of between $100 billion and $400 billion in
real estate and other property falling into the government's
custody.
   The property was used as collateral behind loans that defaulted
when real estate markets _ particularly in the Southwest _
collapsed with declining oil prices, contributing to the failure of
more than 200 S&amp;Ls last year alone.
</TEXT>
