<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     08-04 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Retreats in Europe</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: version also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar gained against European currencies
this morning.
   Gold prices retreated from Thursday's peaks in U.S. trading.
   Dealers attributed the dollar's advance during Asian and early
European trading mostly to position-squaring ahead of the release
today of July U.S. unemployment figures. The threat of U.S.
military action in the Middle East is lending additional support to
the currency, they said.
   ``People had been already short, and then came the events in the
Middle East,'' said Manfred Totzauer, a dealer at Citibank AG in
Frankfurt, West Germany. ``The dollar is politically supported, and
the (job) figures are already expected to be very weak, so the
chances for a rise a good.''
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 138.05 yen, up 1.65 yen from
Thursday. Later in London, the dollar declined to 137.85 yen.
   The pound traded at $1.6350, down from $1.6475 late Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday:
1.8763 West German marks, up from 1.8650; 1.6147 Swiss francs, up
from 1.6065; 6.3550 French francs, up from 6.3192; 2.1157 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.0950; 1,351.80 Italian lire, up from 1,338.00,
and 1.1740 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1715.
   Gold opened in London at $371.90 a troy ounce, up from $369.75
late Thursday. At midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers
fixed a recommended price of $371.55 an ounce.
   In Zurich, gold traded at $371.50 an ounce.
   On Thursday, gold for August delivery closed at $373.70 a troy
ounce on the Commodity Exchange in New York.
   In Hong Kong today, gold closed at $372.86 an ounce, up $2.19
from Thursday's figure.
   Silver was trading in London at $5.29 a troy ounce, up from
$5.23 an ounce late Thursday.
</TEXT>
