<FIRST>r f PM-AirlineReport     08-04 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Airline Report,0167</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airline On-Time Performance Slips</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fewer major airline flights are arriving on
time, according to the latest Transportation Department consumer
report.
   The department said Thursday that the 13 largest domestic
carriers reported 72.2 percent of their flights arrived on time in
June, compared with 79.5 percent for May.
   The department said East Coast weather was largely to blame.
Delays caused by mechanical problems are not counted in the monthly
Air Travel Consumer Report.
   The report showed a surge in complaints to the government about
airlines, with 1,119 received in July, a 30 percent increase over
June complaints.
   The overall trend, however, continued to be a decline, with July
complaints down 43 percent from the 1,969 filed for the same month
last year.
   The department keeps a file of consumer data on performance of
specific flights, airlines and airports. Much of the information is
made available through travel agents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
