<FIRST>d f PM-FarmScene     08-04 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Ships High Quality Grain Despite Drought</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says 1988 grain
shipments from the United States remained of high quality even
though drought cut yields.
   The report by the Federal Grain Inspection Service, released
Thursday, compared inspection records from 1988 and previous years
for wheat, corn, soybeans and other grains.
   The report said wheat moisture decreased or remained the same
for all lots, except hard red spring wheat. For hard red spring
wheat, the average moisture was 11.9 percent, up from 11.8 percent
in 1987.
   Wheat represented 36 percent of the total 115.7 million metric
tons of grains and oilseeds exported in 1988.
   Nearly half the 42 million metric tons of exported wheat was
hard red winter wheat; 19 percent white wheat; 15 percent hard red
spring wheat; 14 percent soft winter wheat; 2 percent durum; and
less than 1 percent mixed wheat.
   The report said corn moisture and the amount of damaged kernels
decreased, but there was a small increase reported in broken corn
and the presence of foreign material.
   Corn represented 40.7 percent of the total metric tons of grains
and oilseeds exported in 1988. Except for a fraction, almost all
was yellow corn.
   Soybeans showed an increase in test weight and a decrease in
amount of damaged kernels, but an increase in the amount of foreign
material and split soybeans.
   Soybeans accounted for 15.7 percent of total exports of grains
and oilseeds in 1988, the report said.
   The other products are sorghum, barley, sunflower seeds, rye,
flaxseed and oats.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department has issued its
first permit for the use of genetically altered trees under the
notion that what's sauce for the potato is sauce for the poplar.
   The department said the permit, announced last week, will enable
investigators at Iowa State University in Ames to study a natural
plant defense mechanism that has been transferred from the potato.
   Twenty poplar trees, cloned for uniformity, will be tested to
see if the defense mechanism is ``switched on'' when the trees are
threatened by insects and other pests, thus saving plant energy
when there is no threat.
   The genetically altered trees won't be allowed to bloom or
produce seeds, USDA says.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans cut back on their fresh fruit
consumption in 1988, the Agriculture Department says.
   Per capita fruit consumption was estimated at 211.3 pounds in
1988, compared with the previous year's record of 214.3 pounds.
   ``Most of the decrease was attributed to reduced consumption of
fresh fruit,'' the department said in its outlook and situation
summary for fruit published this week.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture is offering
help to food exporters take part in the premier trade show in the
Middle East in February.
   More than 3,900 buyers and suppliers will attend the sixth
Middle East Food and Equipment Exhibition in Manama, Bahrain, from
Feb. 10-13.
   The department's foreign agriculture service can help with
preparing exhibits, customs and labeling, as well as with hotel
reservations and local transportation.
   Companies that want to exhibit should contact Mark Condon, MEFEX
'90 coordinator, High Value Products Division, FAS, U.S. Department
of Agriculture, Room 4951-S, Washington, DC 20250-1000, Phone:
(202) 475-3417.
</TEXT>
