<FIRST>r f PM-ElfAquitaine-Pennwalt     08-04 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Elf Aquitaine-Pennwalt,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Elf Aquitaine Offer For Pennwalt Expires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   French oil giant Societe Nationale Elf
Aquitaine has ended its $132-a-share offer for Pennwalt Corp. after
purchasing 96 percent of the outstanding shares.
   Thursday's move comes three days after the companies reached an
agreement with the Federal Trade Commission that will permit the
completion of the $1.05 billion acquisition.
   Elf Aquitaine plans to merge Pennwalt, a pharmaceutical company,
with AC Development Inc., an Elf subsidiary in Stamford, Conn., the
companies said in a statement Thursday.
   Under the agreement with the FTC, Elf Aquitaine must sell a
4-year-old Pennwalt plant in Thorofare, N.J., where two chemicals _
polyvinylidene flouride and vinylidene flouride _ are produced. The
company will be allowed to keep a Pennwalt plant in Calvert City,
Ky., which produces the same chemicals.
   The chemicals, which Elf Aquitaine also produces, are used to
coat electrical wires, to line pipes in chemical plants and to coat
buildings.
   The FTC, which reviews takeovers for possible violations of
antitrust laws, originally planned to seek a court order preventing
the combination because it ``could substantially reduce competition
in the production and the sale'' of the two chemicals.
   In March, Philadelphia-based Pennwalt's management accepted the
offer from Elf Aquitaine, an energy and chemical company owned
largely by the French government. Elf's bid won out over a hostile
attempt by Centaur Partners, a New York investment group.
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange Thursday, Pennwalt
closed at $131.87{, up 12{ cents.
</TEXT>
