<DOCNO> AP890804-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 0940EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Mexico-Economy     08-04 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Economy,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>President: Savings Vital to Economic Growth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Convincing Mexicans to keep their
savings inside the country is essential for Mexico's economic
recovery, says President Carlos Salinas de Gortari.
   Salinas inaugurated the Fifth National Banking Meeting here
Thursday with a plea to bankers to ``improve the quality of
attention that customers receive.''
   Increasing savings and providing credit to lower income groups
``is part of your responsibility,'' he told bankers.
   During the past few months Mexicans brought back $2.3 billion
deposited in foreign banks, helping to boost the country's foreign
reserves to $6 billion, said Miguel Mancera, general director of
the Bank of Mexico, the country's central bank.
   Mancera told the nearly 1,500 banking and government officials
from Mexico, the United States and other countries that the first
half of 1989 saw an ``abundant repatriation, lured by high interest
rates.''
   It is estimated that Mexicans have $28 billion in foreign banks,
mostly in the United States.
   To entice more people to bring back deposits, the government
announced this week a plan to only minimally tax repatriated funds.
   ``We Mexicans must finance our own development. We can
accomplish that by saving more and increasing income to the country
through exports of manufactured products,'' Salinas said.
   Mancera said Mexico's balance of payments showed a $585 million
deficit through July, which he called ``relatively modest
considering the circumstances.''
   Mexico paid out $600 million to service its public debt and $700
million on private debt service, he said.
   During the same period, Mancera said, net foreign direct
investments totaled $900 million.
   The two-day meeting, held for the second consecutive year in
this northern industrial capital, follows a July 23 accord between
Mexico and private bank creditors to restructure $54 billion of its
$107 billion foreign debt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
