<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     08-04 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Noon,0307</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market retreated today, responding to
a stronger-than-expected report on the employment situation.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 9.49 to 2,652.12
by noontime on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 5 to 3 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 525 up, 819 down and
510 unchanged.
   Before the opening the Labor Department reported that the
civilian unemployment rate dropped to 5.2 percent in July from 5.3
percent the month before.
   Nonfarm payroll employment increased by 169,000, on top of an
upward-revised 250,000 gain in June.
   The figures were interpreted as evidence of persistent strength
in the economy, suggesting that the Federal Reserve might see
little need to relax its credit policy further any time soon.
   Interest rates jumped in the credit markets. Prices of long-term
government bonds fell more than $10 for each $1,000 in face value,
pushing their yields back above 8 percent.
   The reaction in the stock market was less clear-cut, however.
While the news was a negative for interest rates, brokers said, it
also helped to ease recent worries about a possible recession.
   Walt Disney fell 4 to 117 after climbing 6] points Thursday.
Some analysts expressed skepticism about recent takeover talk
involving the company.
   Other losers among the blue chips included McDonald's, down \ at
30; General Motors, down \ at 44}, and American Telephone &amp;
Telegraph, down \ at 39~.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped .56 to 191.53. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was down .33 at 376.49.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 86.23 million shares at
noontime, against 83.74 million at the same point Thursday.
</TEXT>
