<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 1251EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-Buckwheat Adv07   08-04 0629</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Buckwheat, Adv 07,0651</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, Aug. 7</HEAD>
<HEAD>Hoosier Finds Buckwheat a Hot Commodity Among Japanese</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH HARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gerald LeMaster has never visited Japan,
but this year 75 percent of his income will come from growing
buckwheat used to make Japanese pasta.
   Through a contract with a Japanese trading association, LeMaster
directs the processing and shipment of Midwest-grown buckwheat,
including a crop from his own farm in Indiana.
   He is one of a small group of American brokers with contracts to
produce buckwheat for the Japanese. His one-year deal with the
Buckwheat Millers Association to produce 22,000 acres in Indiana
and Ohio will pay him $9 per 100 pounds.
   It's a growing business. Last year, just 25 percent of his
income came from buckwheat production.
   The Japanese consume about 250,000 tons of buckwheat a year,
mostly in the form of a noodle called soba, a staple in their diet.
   Soba is made from a mixture of 30 percent to 50 percent
buckwheat flour and hard red wheat flour.
   ``They tell me buckwheat flour has more protein, it's a sweeter
flour and gives it an added flavor,'' LeMaster said in an interview
on his farm near Portland, a rural community about 100 miles
northeast of Indianapolis.
   LeMaster started growing buckwheat almost as an afterthought in
1981 when rain threatened to keep him from planting 600 acres of
soybeans.
   ``I just thought we'd feed it to livestock if nothing else,'' he
said. ``But we started marketing it to some flour mills.''
   Buckwheat is an attractive crop to farmers because of its short
growing time and ability to produce a better crop on poor soils,
LeMaster said.
   Its white flowers bloom four to six weeks after planting in
mid-July and the crop matures in about 10 weeks. A farmer's
investment is typically $20-$30 an acre, LeMaster said.
   ``We're not competing with any of the other crops,'' LeMaster
said. ``Not only is it a profit to farmers, it enhances the soil
the following year.''
   As a protein source, nutritionists say, buckwheat is nearly
unbeatable, and unlike other crops, it's mostly free of chemicals.
   Two-thirds of the buckwheat used in Japan is produced in China,
but the recent civil unrest there has caused the Japanese to search
for alternate suppliers, LeMaster said.
   In Canada, a large buckwheat producer, the government subsidizes
freight costs, but the country's cold weather has hurt crops.
   ``The only reason we're getting it instead of them is because we
have a lot less chance of losing a whole crop,'' LeMaster said.
   ``Down here, we're just about guaranteed of a crop every year.
Since 1981, we've only had one year where we've had a total failure
and we were delayed over 45 days at harvest.''
   LeMaster expresses pride in his family run farm, which employs a
handful of outsiders. A Rolex watch on his arm and a seldom-used
pleasure boat in his yard are evidence of LeMaster's success.
   He said he wants to see buckwheat qualify for the federal export
enhancement program, which provides support to make certain crops
more competitive in foreign markets.
   ``We can be more competitive in price, still maintain a good
price to our farmers and we'd probably be looking at 80,000 acres
through the Corn Belt region,'' he said.
   LeMaster said he's been working with representatives of the
Buckwheat Millers Association and the other American brokers to
arrange a meeting with Indiana Gov. Evan Bayh to discuss export
enhancement and crop insurance.
   ``We tell all of our growers how important it is to keep the
buckwheat clean and free from other grains because if we want their
business we have to maintain a high standard of quality,'' he said.
   End adv for Monday Aug. 7
</TEXT>
</DOC>
