<FIRST>u f PM-PrimeComputer 1stLd-Writethru f0093 08-04 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prime Computer, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0093,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whitney Cuts Offer for Prime</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead with 1 new graf and SUBS 6th graf, `Prime, a ...'
with 3 new grafs to UPDATE with Prime accepting new offer. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   J.H. Whitney &amp; Co., under pressure from its
bankers, today cut its bid for Prime Computer Inc. by $74 million
to $1.18 billion, and Prime accepted the new offer.
   The New York venture capital firm said it will pay $20 a share
for the outstanding common stock of Natick-based Prime, down from
its previous offer of $21.50 a share.
   After Prime reported a $19 million quarterly loss last week,
Whitney came under pressure from its main financing sources _ Bank
of Boston and Chemical Bank _ to line up additional funds to ensure
that it could ride out a period of continued losses.
   Whitney said Thursday it had been unable to obtain the
additional financing at $21.50 per share and was entering
negotiations with Prime to reduce the offer.
   Don E. Ackerman, a Whitney partner, said today Whitney has
informed Prime that ``our financing sources have furnished us
financing commitments at $20 per share.''
   In a statement, Prime Chairman David J. Dunn said, ``The board
of directors of Prime is very disappointed that J.H. Whitney and
its financial sources have not completed the $21.50 per share offer
agreed to in the original merger agreement.''
   However, Dunn said, the board believed the amended Whitney offer
remained economically superior to a competing offer from MAI Basic
Four Inc. of Tustin, Calif., and recommended that Prime
shareholders accept it.
   Prime, a manufacturer of minicomputers and computer-aided design
and manufacturing systems, last month agreed to merge with Whitney
while fending off the hostile bid from MAI.
   MAI, a computer firm controlled by New York investor Bennett S.
LeBow, had originally offered $20 a share for Prime but cut its
offer on June 1 to $19.50 a share.
   Whitney's new offer of $20 a share applies to Prime's 49.5
million outstanding common shares, which represent about 79 percent
of the company's stock on a fully-diluted basis. Whitney has
offered to exchange securities with a face value of $22 per share
for the remaining 21 percent of Prime's shares.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
