<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   08-04 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybeans Lead End-of-the-Week Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices closed sharply higher
Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade, rebounding from a week-long
string of losses as traders evened up their positions ahead of the
weekend.
   Grain futures also advanced, partly in sympathy with soybeans
and partly in reaction to a private crop-production estimate
pegging the 1989 corn and soybean harvests slightly below the
Agriculture Department's latest projections.
   Soybeans for delivery in August had fallen a total of more than
85 cents a bushel in the five previous sessions as growing
conditions improved and supplies of newly harvested South American
soybeans increased.
   ``This rally was long overdue,'' said Walter Spilka,
grain-market analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co. in New
York. ``The market was oversold technically and it was just a
matter of which day it would fall on.''
   He said many traders typically even up their positions on Friday
so they have no risk exposure over the weekend. Some of those who
had sold at higher prices earlier in the week may have been buyers
on Friday.
   Another bullish factor was a report Thursday on crop production
estimates by Sparks Commodities Inc., a private analytical firm
based in Memphis, Tenn.
   A financial news service reported that Sparks had pegged the
1989 U.S. soybean harvest at 1.9 billion bushels and the corn crop
at 7.3 billion bushels. Sparks would not confirm the report.
   Both reported estimates were slightly below the Agriculture
Department's latest predictions. The USDA will issue new harvest
projections in a crop report due out on Thursday.
   At the close, wheat was 1 cent lower to } cent higher with
September at $3.87\ a bushel; corn was 1{ cents to 2} cents higher
with September at $2.19} a bushel; oats were 4 cents to 4} cents
higher with September at $1.40\ a bushel; soybeans were 6 cents to
16{ cents higher with August at $5.91 a bushel.
</TEXT>
