<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Staubach     08-04 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Staubach,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Football Star Expresses Concern on Eastern to Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pro football Hall of Famer Roger Staubach has
joined the lineup of those backing Eastern Airlines strikers,
writing a letter to President Bush saying that continued sales of
Eastern assets could bring the airline's eventual demise.
   In a letter to Bush dated Aug. 1, the former Dallas Cowboys
quarterback asked that a meeting be set up as soon as possible
between representatives of the Eastern pilots union and Roger
Porter, Bush's domestic policy adviser.
   Staubach wrote that his interest in the airline stemmed from
personal relationships with many striking Eastern pilots. He said
that group includes the best man at his wedding, football teammates
and classmates at the U.S. Naval Academy, where Staubach also was a
quarterback.
   From his conversations with those friends and from ``all other
accounts,'' Staubach wrote, ``it is obvious that the Eastern
situation is far more than a traditional labor-management dispute.
It goes to the very root of the free enterprise system within our
country.''
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell in Miami said he had no comment
on Staubach's letter or speculation that the former football player
might get involved in making a buyout offer for the company.
   Staubach, who now runs a commercial real estate company in
Dallas, didn't return a call seeking comment Friday. It wasn't
immediately clear whether Staubach's interest in Eastern could
extend to a possible bid for the crippled airline.
   Another sports figure, former baseball commissioner Peter V.
Ueberroth, made a buyout bid for Eastern in partnership with the
unions in early April. But the takeover agreement between Ueberroth
and Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern's parent Texas Air Corp.,
later fell apart over the unions' demand that Lorenzo be removed
from daily control of the airline.
   Eastern pilots, Machinists union members and flight attendants
are in the sixth month of a strike against the Miami-based company,
which has been under Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection from
creditors since March 9.
   The company is reorganizing as a smaller carrier, selling $1.8
billion in aircraft, landing slots and other assets, and hiring new
pilots to replace the strikers.
   Eastern's unions support an alternative buyout proposal by
Joseph Ritchie, a Chicago businessman who has met at the White
House with high-level members of the Bush administration.
   On Thursday, the master executive council of Eastern's pilots
union passed a resolution calling for pilots at carriers nationwide
to undertake a temporary work stoppage to pressure Congress to
investigate Lorenzo's fitness to run Eastern and its sister
carrier, Continental Airlines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890804-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 1718EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     08-04 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Sharply Higher On Employment Figures</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose nearly 2 percent Friday against
major foreign currencies, its biggest gain in months, after a
government report upset expectations of an economic slowdown.
   The dollar's rally was the mirror image of a debacle in the bond
market. The selling binge in bonds drove interest yields higher and
made the dollar-denominated securities more attractive to global
investors.
   Gold prices fell in U.S. trading after finishing higher overseas.
   The dollar remained well below the peaks reached in June in
spite of its one-day surge, which amounted to 1.9 percent against
the West German mark, British pound and Japanese yen and an even 2
percent vs. the Swiss franc.
   The Labor Department triggered the rally by announcing that
nonfarm payrolls rose by 169,000 in July.
   Although the figure was consistent with economists' predictions,
many traders had been betting that payroll growth would be much
smaller. Also, the department revised upward the figure for June
job growth.
   The job statistics renewed fears of inflation, which hurts the
value of interest-paying securities. As a result bond prices fell
and their yields shot up.
   The higher yields on bonds and short-term securities attracted
money into dollars, said Marc Cohen, a vice president at Republic
National Bank of New York.
   Also helping the dollar was heightened tension in the Middle
East, Cohen said. The dollar widely is seen as a safe haven from
political turmoil.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 138.05 yen, up 1.65 yen from
Thursday. Later in London, the dollar was quoted at 139.40 yen. In
New York the dollar rose to 139.85 yen from 137.20 yen late
Thursday.
   In London, the dollar jumped against the British pound, with
sterling falling to $1.6150 from $1.6475 late Thursday. In New York
the pound fell to $1.6060 from $1.6373.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday's rates, included: 1.9070 West German marks, up from
1.8718; 1.6435 Swiss francs, up from 1.6115; 1.1783 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.1733; 6.4555 French francs, up from 6.3395; and
1,370.50 Italian lire, up from 1,348.50.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday,
included: 1.8975 West German marks, up from 1.8650; 1.6353 Swiss
francs, up from 1.6065; 6.4260 French francs, up from 6.3192;
2.1300 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0950; 1,366.00 Italian lire, up
from 1,338.00, and 1.1775 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1715.
   In Hong Kong, gold closed at $372.86 a troy ounce, up $2.19 from
Thursday.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid of $370.75 a troy ounce, from
$369.75 late Thursday. In Zurich, gold rose to close at a bid of
$370.50 from $369.50 an ounce Thursday.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery fell to $367.25 an ounce from $373.30. Later, Republic
National Bank of New York said gold was bid at $367.50, down from
$372.25.
   Silver bullion prices held steady on the London market, where
the metal was trading at a late bid of $5.23 a troy ounce,
unchanged from Thursday. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery fell to $5.168 from $5.296 on Thursday.
</TEXT>
