<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   08-04 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market retreated Friday as a
stronger-than-expected report on employment sent interest rates
sharply higher.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 8.16 to
2,653.45, trimming its gain for the week to 18.21 points.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 4 to 3 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
642 up, 867 down and 492 unchanged.
   Before the opening the Labor Department reported that the
civilian unemployment rate dropped to 5.2 percent in July from 5.3
percent the month before.
   Nonfarm payroll employment increased by 169,000, on top of an
upward-revised 250,000 gain in June.
   The figures were interpreted as evidence of persistent strength
in the economy, suggesting that the Federal Reserve might see
little need to relax its credit policy further any time soon.
   Interest rates jumped in the credit markets. Prices of long-term
government bonds fell more than $20 for each $1,000 in face value,
driving their yields back above 8 percent.
   The reaction in the stock market was less emphatic, however.
While the news was a negative for interest rates, brokers said, it
also helped to ease recent worries about a possible recession.
   Thus, numerous stocks of companies in industries closely tied to
the ups and downs of the business cycle, such as metals, chemicals
and forest products, actually gain ground.
   Phelps Dodge rose 2} to 69~; Alcoa ~ to 71{; Dow Chemical 1\ to
93; Amax 1| to 26{; International Paper 1] to 54\, and Monsanto 1\
to 117.
   Walt Disney fell 4~ to 116[ in active trading after climbing 6]
points Thursday. Some analysts expressed skepticism about recent
takeover talk involving the company.
   Other losers among the blue chips included McDonald's, down \ at
29}; Coca-Cola, down 1\ at 65~, and American Telephone &amp; Telegraph,
down ] at 39}.
   Bolar Pharmaceutical, the most active issue on the American
Stock Exchange, tumbled 4} to 23. Investigators in Congress said
Thursday they had received information suggesting that Bolar used a
Smithkline Beecham blood-pressure drug in getting approval to
market a generic version of the product.
   Bolar denied the allegations.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 169.75 million
shares, against 168.69 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 201.56 million shares.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $6.05 billion, or 0.18
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped .45 to 191.64.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index fell .48 to 393.14, and S&amp;P's
500-stock composite index was down .82 at 343.92.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market rose
.49 to 457.42, setting a record high for the second straight day.
At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index closed at
376.10, down .72.
