<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     08-04 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Petroleum Futures End Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil futures sank lower Friday but the
near-month contract failed to pierce the $18 level on the way down.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the September contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil,
fell 18 cents to finish at $18.03 a barrel. The contract traded at
a low of $18 during the session.
   Contracts for delivery in October and November were down 21
cents each to $17.70 and $17.66 respectively.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, unleaded gasoline
for September fell 0.42 cent to 50.24 cents a gallon, while other
contracts closed mixed. Heating oil for September delivery edged up
0.6 cent to close at 49.18 cents a gallon. Most other contract
months were lower.
   Traders said volume was extremely light in an uneventful session.
   ``There was not a lot going on,'' said John H. O'Connell, energy
broker for Refco Inc. in New York.
   Most of the concern about possible oil supply disruptions from
the Middle East have subsided, analysts said. Worry about political
events involving the U.S. hostages had given prices some support
earlier in the week.
   ``Now that the Middle East is out of the way, the market is
bearish,'' O'Connell said.
   Weak gasoline prices due to excess refinery output and an
increase in OPEC production have softened crude prices in recent
weeks.
</TEXT>
