<SECOND>BC-Morrison Knudsen-Gold,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Merger Will Increase Amount Of Gold From American Girl</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boise-based Morrison Knudsen Corp. has
entered into a joint venture with a British Columbia company to
develop a gold mine in southeastern California, MK Chairman William
Agee announced.
   MK said Friday it will enter into an equal partnership with
Eastmaque Gold Mines Ltd. of Vancouver to own, develop and operate
the American Girl gold mine now held by Eastmaque.
   MK will purchase 500,000 common shares from Eastmaque for $5 per
share U.S., contribute $10 million to the venture and assume
certain obligations.
   ``By acquiring an equity position in a productive gold mine we
have advanced a key goal in our mining strategy. Our owner's
position is a sensible expansion in an industry we know well
through 40 years' experience as a contract miner,'' Agee said.
   The mine currently produces 2,000 ounces of gold per month. With
improvements made this summer, it could increase the yield to about
3,200 ounces a month. When the mine is in full production next May,
it should come up with 6,000 ounces of gold each month, MK said.
   MK is an international engineering, mining and construction
company with 15,000 employees and annual revenue of about $2
billion.
