<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 1756EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Northwest     08-04 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northwest,0589</SECOND>
<HEAD>Checchi Completes Buyout of Northwest Airlines Parent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Los Angeles investor Alfred Checchi signed
the acquisition papers Friday to complete his group's $3.65 billion
buyout of NWA Inc., the parent of Northwest Airlines.
   The 41-year-old former Marriott Corp. treasurer said all
publicly held shares of NWA common stock have been purchased for
$121 each, officially ending the takeover battle initiated by
Checchi in late March.
   Checchi has said he will spend some of his time at NWA's Eagan,
Minn., headquarters but will not take a management position. Steven
Rothmeier will stay on as the company's chief executive officer and
chairman while Checchi will become a board member, a spokesman for
the airline said.
   As a result of the takeover, Moody's Investors Service announced
Friday it has lowered the senior debt ratings of NWA to Single-B1
from BAA2, and of Northwest to BA2 from Single-A3. About $400
million of long-term debt is affected, the credit rating agency
said.
   Checchi's group, described early on by Rothmeier as a friendly
suitor, beat out at least three other bidders: rival airline Pan Am
Corp.; the 20,000-member Machinists union local at Northwest; and
Los Angeles oil billionaire Marvin Davis, who started the public
bidding with an offer of $2.7 billion, or $90 a share, on March 28.
   Checchi, who once worked for the Bass brothers of Fort Worth,
Texas, financed the takeover with $700 million cash and another
$3.35 billion in financing from commercial banks led by Bankers
Trust Co. Equity partners include KLM Royal Dutch Airlines and
Elders Finance Group of Australia, neither of which are allowed a
controlling interest under laws that limit foreign investment in
U.S. airlines.
   The deal did not require government approval, but Checchi's
group will need an operating permit from the U.S. Transportation
Department, which is conducting a financial fitness review of the
new owners. Checchi has said it is ``laughable'' to think that the
permit would be withheld.
   He acquires an airline in the midst of tense contract talks with
its 5,000 pilots. The pilots have been without a contract for about
2{ years and have asked the National Mediation Board to declare an
impasse in the negotiations. If the request is granted, the pilots
would be free to strike legally after a 30-day ``cooling-off''
period.
   Checchi is depending on a steady cash flow to service the large
takeover debt and a pilots' strike could idle the carrier.
   Checchi also inherits an airline that earned the nickname
``Northworst'' after a prolonged performance slump that followed
the 1986 purchase of Republic Airlines. The carrier has vastly
improved its service, however, and earnings are on the rise.
   After posting record earnings in 1988 of $135 million, or $4.63
a share, NWA is positioned to surpass that mark. It earned $83.3
million, or $2.82 a share, in the first six months of this year.
   Of the 21.2 billion revenue passenger miles logged by
Northwest's 314 planes in the first six months of the year, 12.6
billion miles were domestic and 7.3 billion were flown on routes to
the Pacific Rim, where Northwest has the largest presence of any
U.S. carrier. A revenue passenger mile represents one paying
passenger flown one mile.
   Checchi has vowed to keep the company's headquarters in Eagan, a
St. Paul suburb minutes from the Minneapolis-St. Paul International
Airport, and he has said the jobs of the carrier's 37,590 employees
are secure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
