<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 1810EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommoditiesProbe 1stLd-Writethru f0231 08-04 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0231,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commodities Probe Indictments to Multiply; Half Cooperate With Feds</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last graf to CLARIFY that assets may be seized only if
they were obtained illegally. A version also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI T. PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There's no telling how many people will be
indicted as a result of the ongoing federal probe into fraudulent
trading at the world's largest futures exchanges, but it could be
as many as 200, a defense lawyer said Friday.
   Attorney George Collins, asked about a published report saying
the next few months could bring an additional 100 indictments, said
the government could seek many more than that _ or less.
   ``It could be as many as they want,'' said Collins, who
represents an indicted trader.
   U.S. Attorney Anton Valukas' office did not immediately return
telephone calls, but his office has consistently declined comment
about the breadth of the investigation into trading at the Chicago
Board of Trade and the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   ``They could potentially indict anybody who ever put a (trading)
jacket on'' said defense attorney Thomas Durkin, referring to minor
violations. ``I think it will go on for a couple of years.''
   The Chicago Sun-Times reported in Friday's editions that more
than 100 additional indictments are expected this fall, with
charges ranging from minor infractions to major violations like
those already charged.
   Meanwhile, 25 of the 46 traders indicted Wednesday were expected
to cooperate with federal authorities in meetings next week, the
Wall Street Journal reported in Friday's editions.
   A handful of traders had been cooperating for months, and 14
have agreed to plead guilty and help investigators, federal sources
have said.
   Collins said whether people decided to cooperate likely would be
a matter of personal character, the strength of evidence against
them, and whether they had information that was valuable to
authorities.
   ``It's a matter of selling something valuable,'' Collins said.
   ``You've got to sell something to get something,'' he said.
``Some people as a matter of principle wouldn't even tell the truth
to the government. Others would lie on their mothers to get out of
it.''
   Collins said his client, Bradley Ashman, would not cooperate.
Ashman was indicted on one count of conspiracy under the federal
Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations act, 13 counts of
violating the Commodities Exchange Act and one count of making
false statements to a government agent.
   The indictments capped a 2{-year undercover investigation in
which at least four FBI agents posed as traders at the two
exchanges.
   Pleas were scheduled Wednesday from 21 of those indicted before
U.S. District Judge George M. Marovich, who was assigned cases
involving the Japanese yen pit.
   The 19 soybean-pit defendants were to be arraigned Aug. 25
before U.S. District Judge William T. Hart.
   Three more traders were indicted for alleged activities in the
bond pit, and three others were accused of wrongdoing in the Swiss
franc pit.
   In the indictments, traders were accused of systematically
conspiring to skim profits from customer accounts and attempting to
hide earnings from the Internal Revenue Service.
   Brokers trading for their own accounts as well as customers'
accounts, a practice called dual trading, were alleged to have
routinely and illegally cheated customers with the cooperation of
``locals,'' or traders who traded only for their own accounts.
   Eighteen of the defendants charged Wednesday are accused of
violations of the RICO act, which carry penalties of up to 20 years
in prison.
   RICO empowers the government to freeze defendants' assets before
trial and to seize them upon conviction if they are found to have
been acquired through illegal means. But the Sun-Times quoted
government sources as saying prosecutors would not try to seize
defendants' homes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
