<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     08-04 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precious Metals Plunge On Dollar's Strength</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gold and silver futures prices fell sharply Friday on New York's
Commodity Exchange as the dollar surged in value against other
major currencies in reaction to the government's report on July
unemployment.
   On other markets, the major agricultural commodities were higher
while energy futures prices were mostly lower.
   Gold futures settled $5.40 to $6 lower with August at $367.80 a
troy ounce; silver was 12.2 cents to 13.3 cents lower with
September at $5.20 a troy ounce.
   The Labor Department's report of a 5.2 percent jobless rate in
July fell within the market's expectations and was considered
neutral for the financial markets, analysts said.
   But the agency's revision of the June non-farm payroll number,
showing a gain of 250,000 jobs instead of 180,000, indicated the
economy was healthier than had previously been believed.
   ``That revision obviously pointed toward the fact that while the
economy has slowed down significantly, it certainly is not pointing
toward an imminent recession,'' said Peter Cardillo, an analyst
with Josephthal &amp; Co. in New York.
   ``Either way, it means economic conditions do not favor
metals,'' he said. ``They'll have to look to the dollar for
direction.''
   The dollar skyrocketed and interest rates jumped in response to
the report, prompting a shift of investment dollars from the
precious metals to interest-bearing instruments.
   Soybean futures prices posted strong gains on the Chicago Board
of Trade, rebounding from a weeklong string of losses as traders
evened up their positions ahead of the weekend.
   Grain futures also advanced, partly in tandem with soybeans and
partly in reaction to a private crop-production estimate pegging
the 1989 corn and soybean harvests slightly below Agriculture
Department projections.
   Soybeans for delivery in August had fallen a total of more than
85 cents a bushel in the five previous sessions as growing
conditions improved and supplies of newly harvested South American
soybeans increased.
   ``This rally was long overdue,'' said Walter Spilka,
grain-market analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co. in New
York. ``The market was oversold technically and it was just a
matter of which day it would fall on.''
   Wheat settled } cent lower to } cent higher with September at
$3.87{ a bushel; corn was 1{ cents to 2{ cents higher with
September at $2.19{ a bushel; oats were 4 cents to 4} cents higher
with September at $1.40\ a bushel; soybeans were 6 cents to 16{
cents higher with August at $5.90} a bushel.
   Most live cattle futures climbed on buying spurred by strong
cash markets. Higher cash hog prices supported the pork complex.
   Live cattle settled .20 cent to .62 cent higher with August at
74.17 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .43 cent higher
with August at 84.50 cents a pound; live hogs were .28 cent to .90
cent higher with August at 46.80 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .65 cent to 1.28 cents higher with August at 26.27 cents a
pound.
   Crude oil futures sank on the New York Mercantile Exchange but
the near-month contract failed to pierce $18 a barrel.
   Traders said volume was extremely light in an uneventful session.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 16 cents to 21 cents
lower with September at $18.03 a barrel; heating oil was .11 cent
lower to .06 cent higher with September at 49.18 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .43 cent lower to .10 cent higher with
September at 51.24 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
