<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 2100EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-PrimeComputer     08-04 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prime Computer,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whitney Cuts Offer for Prime</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the wake of three consecutive quarterly losses,
Prime Computer Inc. on Friday reluctantly recommended that its
shareholders accept a buyout by J.H. Whitney &amp; Co. for about $1.1
billion, $74 million less than Whitney's previous offer.
   Prime's board of directors said the merger was still preferable
to selling its minicomputer business to MAI Basic Four Inc. of
Tustin, Calif., which has offered $525 million for the division.
   Whitney, a New York venture capital firm, said it would pay $20
a share for Prime's outstanding common stock, down from its
previous offer of $21.50 a share or about $1.2 billion.
   The reduction in Whitney's offer was not as drastic as Wall
Street had anticipated, and Prime's stock rose $1.12{ cents a share
to close at $17.75 Friday on the New York Stock Exchange.
   An arbitrageur, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Whitney's original offer had been widely viewed as untenable, and
the new offer was more realistic, raising traders' confidence that
the deal would go through.
   ``The board of directors of Prime is very disappointed that J.H.
Whitney and its financial sources have not completed the $21.50 per
share offer ...,'' said David J. Dunn, Prime's chairman.
   ``However, after review of all the alternatives, the board of
directors believes that the revised J.H. Whitney offer is the best
economic alternative available for Prime stockholders,'' Dunn said
in a statement.
   Prime, which makes minicomputers and computer-aided design and
manufacturing systems, turned a profit of $19 million on sales of
$1.6 billion in 1988. But the cost of defending against a takeover
and slow sales of minicomputers led to losses of $14.4 million in
the final quarter of 1988, $5 million in the first quarter of this
year and $19 million in the second quarter.
   Whitney emerged last month as a ``white knight,'' or friendly
buyer, to save Prime from a hostile, $970 million bid by MAI Basic
Four and its chairman, New York takeover specialist Bennett S.
LeBow.
   After Prime reported the most recent, $19 million loss last
week, Whitney came under pressure from its main financing sources _
Bank of Boston and Chemical Bank _ to line up an additional $50
million of financing to ensure that it could ride out a period of
continued losses.
   Whitney said Thursday it had been unable to obtain the
additional financing at $21.50 per share and was entering
negotiations with Prime to reduce the offer.
   The revised offer of $20 a share applies to Prime's 49.5 million
outstanding common shares, which represent about 79 percent of the
company's stock on a fully-diluted basis.
   Whitney has offered to exchange notes with a face value of $22
per share for the remaining 21 percent of Prime's shares.
Securities analysts said those notes would trade at a substantial
discount and estimated the total value of the deal at $17 to $18.50
a share, or $1.06 billion to $1.16 billion.
   Prime postponed its annual meeting from Aug. 9 to Aug. 24 to
give stockholders time to consider the revised offer.
</TEXT>
