<FIRST>u f AM-Unemployment 1stLd-Writethru f0138 08-04 0724</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Unemployment, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0138,0752</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jobless Rate Falls; Inflation Concerns Fueled</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 21st graf, `The payroll ...,' to CORRECT data for black
teenagers. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Civilian unemployment dipped a tick to 5.2
percent in July, the government said Friday. Analysts say the data
should ease fears of an imminent recession but heighten concerns
about inflation.
   Joblessness was down from 5.3 percent in June, with nonfarm
businesses adding 169,000 jobs, the Labor Department said.
   At the same time, June's job growth was revised from 180,000 to
250,000, additional evidence that the economy continues to grow,
though at a slower pace than last year.
   ``This suggests an economy that is clearly, clearly far from a
recession,'' said Elliot Platt, senior vice president of Donaldson,
Lufkin &amp; Jenrette. ``Despite a lot of signs of economic weakness
the labor market remains fairly strong.''
   Michael Boskin, chairman of the President's Council of Economic
Advisers, said the report was ``good news'' and ``suggests the
economy is continuing to expand.''
   While the job growth number provided encouraging news, analysts
were wary over data showing significant upward pressure on wages _
a welcome development for workers but a sign of stubborn inflation
as well.
   The Labor Department said average hourly earnings rose 0.8
percent in July after increasing just 0.1 percent in the prior two
months.
   ``That's a very, very powerful increase,'' said Platt.
   ``Ominous,'' was the way Boston Co. Economic Advisers Inc. chief
economist Allen Sinai described the wage gains.
   Both agreed that July's wage increase should give pause to the
Federal Reserve Board, which of late has relaxed monetary policy in
hopes of fueling enough new growth to avert a recession.
   ``There will be no more easing by the Fed until after Labor
Day.'' said Sinai.
   The government said the unemployment rate fell last month even
though civilian employment declined by 82,000 people to 117.45
million. The rate fell because of a larger decline, of 146,000
people, in the labor force _ the number of people who have jobs or
are seeking employment.
   The job growth again came predominantly in the service economy,
which accounted for 140,000 of the 169,000 new positions.
   Within services, government employment was down by 25,000 jobs
but retail trade added 52,000, wholesale trade 5,000,
transportation and public utilities 23,000 and finance, insurance
and real estate 11,000. Both business and health services posted
modest gains, the government said.
   The goods-producing sector added 29,000 jobs, with gains in
construction and manufacturing offset somewhat by declines in
mining and the automobile industry.
   The 35,000 boost in construction jobs came at the same time that
housing starts and home sales were rebounding. Manufacturing posted
a modest gain of 3,000 positions after three consecutive monthly
declines.
   Employment in the auto industry fell by 12,000 jobs last monh
after a decline of 16,000 in June, a slump coinciding with sluggish
car sales.
   Employment in mining was down 11,000, a figure heavily
influenced by coal strikes in Virginia, West Virginia and Kentucky
that have sparked wildcat actions in other coal-producing states.
   The government said the average workweek for production and
nonsupervisory employees in private industry increased by 0.3
hours, to 34.9 hours. The factory work week held steady at 41 hours
and overtime in July averaged 3.9 hours a week, up from 3.8 hours
in June, the Labor Department said.
   The jump in earnings brought average hourly pay in the private
sector to $9.70 on a seasonally adjusted basis, up from $9.62 in
June.
   The payroll and wage data are taken from the Labor Department's
monthly survey of businesses. A separate household survey found few
major shifts in unemployment among demographic groups, although
joblessness among black teen-agers fell to 27.4 percent last month
from 36.5 percent in June. The June total had been up from 32.4
percent in May.
   These were the July and June rates for other population groups:
   _Adult white men, 3.8 percent, up from 3.7.
   _Adult white women, 4.3 percent, up from 4.1.
   _White teen-agers, 13.4 percent, up from 12.6.
   _Adult black men, 9.3 percent, down from 9.4.
   _Adult black women, 9.9 percent, down from 10.5.
   _Hispanics, 9 percent, up fro 8.1.
   A separate calculation of unemployment that includes members of
the armed services stationed in the United States was unchanged at
5.2 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
