<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 2115EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Phillips-Hyundai     08-04 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Phillips-Hyundai,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Phillips Seeking Replacement For Hyundai in Venture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARTLESVILLE, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Phillips Petroleum Co. said Friday it
is seeking a new partner for a $100 million joint venture to
explore for oil and natural gas in the United States after Hyundai
Corp. withdrew.
   Phillips, Hyundai and the Overseas Petroleum and Investment
Corp. signed a joint venture agreement April 3 to launch a
three-year, 100-prospect drilling venture.
   Following the signing, the South Korean government was to review
the agreement for approval of Hyundai's investment in the project,
but the government did not give its approval to the Korean company.
   The South Korean government wanted assurances that all 100
prospects would be drilled in the three-year period and Phillips
was not prepared to make that guarantee because of variables
affecting oil exploration, said Jere Smith, a spokesman at Phillips
headquarters here.
   Smith said Hyundai sought a subsidy from the South Korean
government to underwrite its participation in the project.
   Phillips was to bear 10 percent of the cost of the venture while
45 percent each was to be provided by Hyundai and OPIC, an
affiliated company of Chinese Petroleum Corp. of Taiwan. The
Taiwanese government has given its approval to OPIC's participation.
   Smith said Phillips is, at least for now, accepting the cost of
Hyundai's part of the venture, which already has begun with 11
wells drilled or being drilled in the Gulf of Mexico, California,
Texas and elsewhere.
   ``We have made provisions in case something like this
happened,'' Smith said.
   He said Phillips is seeking a replacement for Hyundai in the
venture, but he would not say whether a new partner might be a
domestic or foreign company.
   ``We've had several prospects express interest. We're
optimistic,'' Smith said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
