<FIRST>r f BC-Crain-Fairchild     08-04 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Crain-Fairchild,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Auto Journal Name Change, Denies $1 Million Claim</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Friday ordered Fairchild
Publications to change the name of its Automotive Electronic News,
but denied a $1 million damage claim by publishers of a similarly
named trade journal.
   U.S. District Judge George LaPlata ruled that the new magazine's
name infringes on Crain Communications' trademark for its
long-established weekly Automotive News.
   He gave Fairchild until Oct. 1 to remove either ``automotive''
or ``news'' from the title.
   Both media companies appeared satisfied with the ruling, which
followed a three-week trial.
   ``We consider it to be a complete victory,'' said Raymond E.
Scott, an attorney for Chicago-based Crain. ``One would like to
have the money, but that is not the goal of trademark infringement
litigation.''
   ``The ruling in no way changes our future plans for the
newspaper,'' said Richard Bambrick, publisher of the biweekly
Automotive Electronic News. ``We've identified an audience ... that
until now has not had its own journal.''
   Fairchild is a division of Capital Cities-ABC Inc. of New York.
</TEXT>
