<DOCNO> AP890804-0194 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 1951EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Earns-PanAm     08-04 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Pan Am,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pan Am Reports $7.7 Million Second-Quarter Loss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pan Am Corp. on Friday reported it lost more
money in the second quarter than it did in the same period last
year.
   Pan Am reported a net loss of $7.7 million for the quarter,
compared with a loss of $5 million in the same quarter last year.
   The nation's eighth-largest airline company said revenue of its
main subsidiary, Pan American World Airways, continued to suffer
from lower international traffic in the wake of the Pan Am crash
over Scotland last December.
   The latest loss occurred despite ``aggressive pricing actions''
and some benefit from the strike affecting rival Eastern Airlines,
Pan Am said.
   The results for the latest quarter include a gain of $92.1
million on the sale of the company's Pan Am World Services unit and
expenses of $28.2 million stemming from its unsuccessful takeover
bid for NWA Inc., the parent of rival Northwest Airlines.
   Total revenue for the second quarter declined 1.7 percent to
$909.4 million from $925.4 million a year earlier.
   Combined revenue from the Pan Am Shuttle and Pan Am Express, a
commuter airline subsidiary, jumped 47.8 percent to $83.2 million
from $56.3 million, partly offsetting the decline at Pan American
World Airways.
   ``We are determined to stay on course with our efforts to
restore Pan Am's competitive position despite these unfortunate
setbacks,'' said Chairman Thomas G. Plaskett. ``While our bid (for
NWA) was unsuccessful, we believe Northwest presented the type of
opportunity we will pursue aggressively in order to secure Pan Am's
long-term future.''
   Separately Friday, Los Angeles investor Alfred Checchi signed
the acquisition papers to complete his group's $3.65 billion buyout
of NWA.
   For the first half of the year, Pan Am's net loss widened to
$158.8 million from $88.4 million in the same period of 1988.
   First-half revenue slipped 2.7 percent to $1.64 billion from
$1.69 billion a year earlier.
</TEXT>
