<FILEID>AP-NR-08-04-89 0032EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-SEC-Fraud     08-04 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SEC-Fraud,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC Accuses Two Investors Of Trying To Cheat 100 Brokerages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission on
Thursday accused two investors of a scheme to defraud more than 100
brokerages, including Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. Inc., Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc. and Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   In a civil lawsuit, the SEC says the investors, Jury Matt Hansen
and Fergus M. Sloan Jr., and their New York brokerage firm, Fermat
Associates, committed fraud by buying millions of dolars worth of
securities without having sufficient money to pay for them and
selling them later the same day at a profit to cover their cost,
The New York Times reported in Friday's editions.
   The illegal practice is known as ``free riding.''
   The SEC also charges the Toronto Dominion Bank violated federal
banking regulations by providing the investors with credit although
the two did not produce collateral. The bank was not charged with
fraud.
   The SEC said the investors, through a partnership registered in
Panama, Graycliff International SA, opened an account at the New
York branch of Toronto Dominion. The agency said the bank often
covered the investors' checks overnight when the funds in the
account were insufficient.
   The investors then opened 250 accounts at more than 100
brokerages, using 76 names, the suit charges. Since December 1984,
the SEC claims, the defendants used this ``web of accounts'' to buy
and sell securities on the same day.
   The agency says the men earned more than $1 million through the
scheme but left debts of $1.5 million at four brokerage houses at
which they had steep losses: Steinberg &amp; Lyman, Universal
Securities of America Inc., Merrill Lynch and Dominick &amp; Dominick.
   The SEC said it found no losses at any other brokerages.
   Calls to the investors' office were answered by someone who
identified himself as a temporary employee and said he had know
knowledge of the SEC suit, the Times reported. A message left on
Sloan's answering machine was not returned, the newspaper said.
Hansen's home phone number is unlisted.
   Elliot Schnapp, a laywer representing the men, said he belived
the charges were without merit.
   ``It appears to us that the SEC is seeking to retroactively
declare illegal a type of trading many investors and banks have
engaged in for many years and not thought to be illegal,'' he told
the Times.
   He also denied that the men left debts at the four brokerages.
   In response to an SEC request, a U.S. District Court judge in
Manhattan on Thursday issued a temporary restraining order to stop
the two men from continuing their investment activities. The court
also froze their assets.
   In addition, the court issued a temporary order to restrain the
Toronto bank from ``further violations of the credit extension
provisions.''
   In a statement, the bank said it had been cooperating with the
SEC for several months and was ``an innocent bystander in the areas
under investigation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
